Name: 0625_Heatshield
Title: Heatshield (0.625m)
Description: LEO-rated heat shield. Not rated for lunar returns.

Name: 1.25_Heatshield
Title: Heatshield (1.25m)
Description: LEO-rated heat shield. Not rated for lunar returns.

Name: 11D33
Title: 11D33
Description: Developed version of S1.5400 engine for Block L stage of Molniya launch vehicle. Slightly better performance.

Name: 11D33M
Title: 11D33M
Description: The S1.5400A engine, as used on Block ML on the Molniya M launch vehicle. Further performance improvements to the basic S1.5400/11D33 engine.

Name: 1x3SPanels
Title: OX-2L 1x3 Photovoltaic Panels
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel. 0.63m^2.

Name: 1x3WPanels
Title: OX-4M 2x3 Photovoltaic Panels
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel. 2.28m^2.

Name: 2_5mAdapter
Title: CST-100 Atlas V Adapter
Description: A structural adapter to connect the service module of the CST-100 to the Atlas V launch vehicles.

Name: 2.5_Heatshield
Title: Heatshield (4m) - Mk 1-2 Pod
Description: LEO-rated heat shield for Mk1-2 and other 4m pods. Not rated for lunar returns.

Name: 25mKossak
Title: Boeing 737 cockpit
Description: Cockpit for the Boeing 737- short-to medium range twinjet airliner. First flight: April 9, 1967.

Name: 3_75mAdapter
Title: CST-100 4M Adapter
Description: A structural adapter to connect the service module of the CST-100 to 4.65 meter parts.

Name: 3.75_Heatshield
Title: Heatshield (3.75m)
Description: Sturdy thermal shield to keep the fiery death on the outside of the pod. Make sure the shield points to the travel direction while reentering, or the pod may still get heated up. Recommended for any pods reentering atmospheres.

Name: 400N_Engine
Title: S-400 Bipropellant Engine (400N)
Description: The S400 400N bipropellant Engine is designed for apogee orbit injection of geostationary satellites and for trajectory and planetary orbit manoeuvres of deep space probes. Notable missions include Galileo, Mars Express, Venus Express & the ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: 45DegreeRCS
Title: RCS Quad, 45deg (275/445 N class)
Description: A generic RCS quad with 45degree side-thruster orientation. Use this for attitude control or translation/ullage for medium stages and spacecraft (when using NTO/MMH, same performance as the Apollo SM quads).

Name: 625mBonny
Title: Bonanza Cabin
Description: Cabin section for the Beechcraft Bonanza

Name: 7k_ok_lsolar
Title: Soyuz 7K Left Solar Array
Description: Soyuz 7K series LEFT solar panels.

Name: 7k_ok_rsolar
Title: Soyuz 7K Right Solar Array
Description: Soyuz 7K series RIGHT solar panels.

Name: 890N_Engine
Title: R-42 Bipropellant Engine (890N)
Description: The R-42 Engine is designed for apogee orbit injection of geostationary satellites and for trajectory and planetary orbit manoeuvres of deep space probes. The engine is an evolution of the R-4D series of engines used on the highly successful HTV vehicle and the legendary Cassini probe. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: A-6
Title: A-6
Description: The production version of the NAA75-110 engine as used on Redstone and the Mercury-Redstone Launch Vehicle.

Name: A-7
Title: A-7
Description: NAA75-110 using Hydyne fuel for increased thrust and specific impulse. Used on the Redstone-derivative Jupiter-C sounding rocket and Juno I launch vehicle.

Name: A-9
Title: A-9
Description: Derivate of the A-4/V-2 engine for use with the A-9 upper stage / spaceplane. Fuel mixture is speculative.

Name: A7
Title: NAA-75-110 A-Series
Description: Used on the Redstone missile.  Designed for Ethanol/LOx (A-6) (1.5 O/F Ratio), it was later adapted to burn Hydyne/LOx (A-7) (1.73 O/F Ratio)(higher performance (12%) yet more toxic) for use in Jupiter C / Juno I.  When Redstone MRLV was adapted from Jupiter C for manned use the A7 was switched back to Ethanol, accepting slightly lower performance for lack of toxicity. Thrust Vector Control was provided by carbon thrust vanes (add the Redstone Fin / Thrust vane part in 4x symmetry), and additional attitude control was provided by actuating fins. Mass includes thrust frame. Diameter: [1.77 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: AccelerometerFGA
Title: AIES FGA Accelerometer
Description: A device for measuring the forces of 'G'. What a surprise.

Name: ADAPTER_BLOCK_I
Title: Soyuz/Progress Payload Adapter
Description: A payload adapter for the Soyuz and Progress spacecrafts.

Name: ADAPTER_BLOCK_I2
Title: Soyuz ST Payload Adapter
Description: The expanded adapter is used with the ESA fairing for the Soyuz 2 (ST-A & ST-B) launch vehicle, accepting payloads of up to 2.5 meters in diameter.

Name: adapter-125-0625-2
Title: SM-2 Stack Dual Adapter
Description: Converts a 1.25m stack into two 0.625m mounts, suitable for mounting all manner of small engines.

Name: adapter-125-0625-3
Title: SM-3 Stack Triple Adapter
Description: Converts a 1.25m stack into three 0.625m mounts. Tiny, tiny mounts.

Name: adapter-125-0625-4
Title: SM-4 Stack Quadruple Adapter
Description: Converts a 1.25m stack into a quartet 0.625m mounts.

Name: adapter-25-125
Title: Rockomax Skeletal Structural Adapter
Description: A barebones adapter from Rockomax that upholds the company's reputation for quality bargain-bin parts.

Name: adapter-25-multi-01
Title: SE-4-OMNI Stack Multi-Adapter
Description: This breakthrough in modularity allows for a 2.5m stack to be split to between 2 and 8 0.625m stacks. With a cookie on top. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: adapter-375-25
Title: Rockomax Skeletal XL Structural Adapter
Description: Rockomax's first hurried attempt to enter the Kerbodyne-dominated extra-large parts market was met with limited applause.

Name: adapter-rad-0625
Title: S-MINI Radial Stack Adapter
Description: A pretty tiny radial stack adapter for 0.625m stacks. Now we don't need to use large tanks full of explosive fuels to do this. It's a win-win situation!.

Name: adapter-rad-125
Title: S-MED Radial Stack Adapter
Description: A radial stack adapter for 1.25m stacks. Studies show that this could increase the ease of building rockets by up to 16.2%.

Name: adapterEngines
Title: Mk3 Engine Mount
Description: A structural mounting plate for rocket engines. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterLargeSmallBi
Title: TVR-200L Stack Bi-Adapter
Description: After realizing 'larger circles' wasn't a very patentable concept, O.M.B. Enterprises rolled out a new line of ingenious multi-connector adapters to fit Rockomax sized parts. Lawsuit still pending. Converts a single 2.5m stack into two 1.25m stacks.

Name: adapterLargeSmallQuad
Title: TVR-400L Stack Quad-Adapter
Description: After realizing 'larger circles' wasn't a very patentable concept, O.M.B. Enterprises rolled out a new line of ingenious multi-connector adapters to fit Rockomax sized parts. Lawsuit still pending. Converts a single 2.5m stack into four 1.25m stacks.

Name: adapterLargeSmallTri
Title: TVR-300L Stack Tri-Adapter
Description: After realizing 'larger circles' wasn't a very patentable concept, O.M.B. Enterprises rolled out a new line of ingenious multi-connector adapters to fit Rockomax sized parts. Lawsuit still pending. Converts a single 2.5m stack into three 1.25m stacks.

Name: adapterMk3-Mk2
Title: Mk3 to Mk2 Adapter
Description: Our engineers insisted on a way to reuse Mk2 parts on the new Fuselage system. Manufacturing a streamlined adapter despite the considerable difference of the two cross sections required quite a radical design. It is often used as a slide on Take Your Kids to Work Day. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterMk3-Size2
Title: Mk3 to 4.3m Adapter
Description: Perfectly pointy, carefully curved and devastatingly destructive, this Mk3 to 2.5m adapter can satisfy your wildest of dreams. Or it'll let you bridge the gaps between parts on your craft while giving you a bit of fuel... Your choice. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterMk3-Size2Slant
Title: Mk3 to 4.3m Adapter Slanted
Description: Makes your craft hang in the air like bricks don't! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterrads
Title: AIES RAD-S Adapter
Description: Light fuselage adapter. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterSize2-Mk2
Title: 4.3m to Mk2 Adapter
Description: When you can't decide between a rocket and a spaceplane, why not both? (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterSize2-Size1
Title: C7 Brand Adapter - 2.5m to 1.25m
Description: While the popular Rockomax Adapter has served its purpose fairly well over the years, C7 engineers thought they could do better. Improvements of this in-house product include an integrated fuel tank and a longer structural frame.

Name: adapterSize2-Size1Slant
Title: C7 Brand Adapter Slanted - 2.5m to 1.25m
Description: While the popular Rockomax Adapter has served its purpose fairly well over the years, C7 engineers thought they could do better. Improvements of this in-house product include an integrated fuel tank and a longer structural frame.

Name: adapterSize3-Mk3
Title: Mk3 to 6.5m Adapter
Description: An adapter for when your craft turns from a massive rocket into a gargantuan plane! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: adapterSmallMiniShort
Title: FL-A5 Adapter
Description: A small parts adapter for FL-T based fuselages.

Name: adapterSmallMiniTall
Title: FL-A10 Adapter
Description: A small parts adapter for FL-T based fuselages.

Name: AdvancedCanard
Title: Advanced Canard
Description: Our engineers thought this design looked "high tech" and therefore must be clear improvement on earlier models.

Name: ADVINTER
Title: EDS - IV Propellant Tank
Description: Nothing is really known about this thing. Use it at your own risk.

Name: advSascr3
Title: AIES CR3 - Advanced S.A.S
Description: By using the latest breakthroughs in material compression it became possible to make the A.S.A.S. unit that is thinner than the ones of competitors.

Name: advSasModule
Title: Advanced Inline Stabilizer
Description: This module uses an electric motor to spin its internal flywheels, producing torque, which allows for minor attitude adjustments without expending propellant.

Name: AIESrcsThrusrmt1
Title: AIES MT-1 RCS Thruster Port
Description: Linear RCS drive, best used for rotation. (This part refers to an RO RCS config that is not defined, and may not work correctly.)

Name: AIESrcsThrusrom9
Title: AIES ROM-9 RCS Thruster Block
Description: The RCS drive is necessary to maneuver spacecraft in space and allows greater control in the atmosphere.

Name: airbrake1
Title: A.I.R.B.R.A.K.E.S
Description: Research into feasible ways to slow down a plane in mid-air showed that loose hull panels are pretty great as drag-inducing deceleration devices. The discovery led to the invention of the Aerodynamically Integrated Retrograde Braking Robustly Armed Kinetic Extending System (A.I.R.B.R.A.K.E.S.), which is now popular mostly as a cheap alternative to longer runways. C7 Engineers are still trying to come up with a shorter name for such a long acronym.

Name: airlinerCtrlSrf
Title: FAT-455 Aeroplane Control Surface
Description: Large conventional control surface.

Name: airlinerMainWing
Title: FAT-455 Aeroplane Main Wing
Description: One of the largest lifting surfaces in production. The internal volume of these is big enough to carry generously sized fuel tanks.

Name: airlinerTailFin
Title: FAT-455 Aeroplane Tail Fin
Description: Large conventional wing with built-in control surface.

Name: airplaneTail
Title: Tail Connector A
Description: A simple aerodynamic tail for aircraft. Designed to fit onto all standard 1.25m attachments, this part is the embodiment of our "Let's Fly", line of parts.

Name: airplaneTailB
Title: Tail Connector B
Description: This raised variant of our popular airplane tail provides a lot of ground clearance during take-off.

Name: airScoop
Title: XM-G50 Radial Air Intake
Description: An intake duct version that can be mounted at the sides of a fuselage. Warranty does not cover engine flame-outs or any objects, inanimate or otherwise, sucked in by the intake. Optimized for subsonic flight.

Name: AJ10_104
Title: AJ10 Series (Mid)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents mid-period AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Thor-Ablestar and Delta E through Delta N. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: AJ10_137
Title: AJ10-137 (Service Propulsion System)
Description: The Aerojet AJ10-137 rocket engine used on the Apollo Service Module as the Service Propulsion System. Diameter: [3.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: AJ10_137
Title: AJ10-137 (Service Propulsion System)
Description: The Aerojet AJ10-137 rocket engine used on the Apollo Service Module as the Service Propulsion System. Diameter: [3.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: AJ10_190
Title: AJ10-190
Description: Low thrust pressure-fed hypergolic engine. It was used on the Space Shuttle for orbital insertion, maneuvering and deorbiting. Currently used by the Orion MPCV. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: AJ10_37
Title: AJ10 Series (Early)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This is the original Vanguard second stage / Able / Delta configuration, without restart capability. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: AJ10-101A
Title: AJ10-101A
Description: Used on Able II on Thor and Atlas.

Name: AJ10-104
Title: AJ10-104
Description: Used on Ablestar

Name: AJ10-118
Title: AJ10-118
Description: Used on Delta A

Name: AJ10-118D
Title: AJ10-118D
Description: Used on Delta B-D

Name: AJ10-118E
Title: AJ10-118E
Description: Used on Delta E-N

Name: AJ10-142
Title: AJ10-142
Description: Used on Thor-Delta

Name: AJ10-37
Title: AJ10-37
Description: Used on Vanguard second stage.

Name: AJ10-42
Title: AJ10-42
Description: Used on Able I

Name: aje_al31
Title: AL-31FM turbofan
Description: Modern afterburning turbofan used on the Su-27M, Su-30, and Su-34 featuring vector thrust.  122.4 kN wet, 76.2 kN dry, SFC 0.75/1.92 lb/lb hr. Max 2.5 Mach.

Name: aje_atar
Title: Atar 9K-50 Turbojet
Description: Early 1970s afterburning turbojet, used on the Mirage 5S, Mirage 50, Mirage IV-A/P/R, and Mirage F1C. Comparitively low overall pressure ratio (6.2) leads to high fuel consumption but good high-speed performance. 70.6kN wet, 49.18kN dry. SFC 0.98/1.99 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.8.
SPACECRAFT: Mirage 5S, Mirage 50, Mirage IV-A/P/R, Mirage F1C

Name: aje_avon
Title: Avon RB-146 Mk.302 Turbojet
Description: The Avon was Rolls-Royce's first axial-flow turbojet, introduced in 1950. The RB.146, an early 1960s model, was the ultimate military Avon, an afterburning turbojet powering the English Electric Lightning F.6. 72.77kN wet, 56.45kN dry. SFC 0.85/1.85 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.4.

Name: aje_f404
Title: F404-GE-402 Turbofan
Description: General Electric F404-GE-402 low-bypass turbofan with afterburner as used on F/A-18C/D. 78.7kN wet, 53.16kN dry. SFC 0.82/1.74 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.85.

Name: aje_j57
Title: J57-P-21 Turbojet
Description: Late 50s turbojet. The J57 was a workhorse, designed in the early 1950s and powering the B-52, most of the Century Series fighters, and even the U-2. This represents a later model, the -21, which powered the F-100C/D/F. 75.4kN wet, 45.4kN dry. SFC 0.77/2.1 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 1.9.

Name: aje_j75
Title: J75-P-17 Turbojet
Description: Essentially a larger J57, the P&W J75 saw extensive military and civilian use. This afterburning variant powered the F-106 A/B. 109.0kN wet, 76.5kN dry. SFC 0.8/2.15 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.5.

Name: aje_j79
Title: J79-GE-17 Turbojet
Description: The first US "Mach 2" engine, the J79 saw extensive service, powering the B-58 Hustler and the F-4 Phantom and F-104 Starfighter among others. This mid-1960s model powered the USAF F-4E and G, and with minor mounting differences (as the -19) the final development of the Starfighter line, the F-104S.79.63kN wet, 52.8kN dry. SFC 0.84/1.97 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.6.

Name: aje_ramjet
Title: CR2 Ramjet
Description: A fictional CR2 Ramjet. Works best when faster than Mach 2. This engine provides no thrust below Mach 0.3!

Name: aje_solarPanels
Title: ST4 Solar Panel
Description: Static Level 3 solar panel 5m^2.

Name: ALCOR_LanderCapsule
Title: ALCOR Pod(A)
Description: Advanced Landing Capsule for Orbital Rendezvous, a lander pod that actually is as lightweight as the manufacturer claims. Warranty void when subjected to atmospheric entry, sneeze, hard knocks and misplaced screwdrivers and/or wrenches. Packed full of high technology, leaving precious little space for the crew.

Name: almaz_pan_l
Title: Almaz Left Solar Array
Description: Almaz series LEFT solar panels.

Name: almaz_pan_r
Title: Almaz Right Solar Array
Description: Almaz series RIGHT solar panels.

Name: almaz_sample_return
Title: Almaz Film Return Capsule
Description: Almaz film return capsule. Attach inside Almaz capsule bay.

Name: almaz_sr_dec
Title: Almaz Film Return Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for Almaz film return capsule. Surface attach inside Almaz payload bay. Then use stack nodes to attach film capsule, retros and parachute.

Name: almaz_sr_para
Title: Almaz Film Return Capsule Parachute
Description: Parachute for Almaz film return capsule.

Name: almaz_sr_retro
Title: Almaz Film Return Retro Boosters
Description: Almaz film return top retrograde booster block. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: almaz3-5
Title: Almaz 2/3/5
Description: Almaz 2, 3 & 5 military orbital laboratory. Salyut ASAS REQUIRED for station to function. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: altairPod
Title: Altair Ascent Module
Description: The ascent module for the Altair lunar lander.

Name: Angledpanel
Title: M-1x1T Structural Panel
Description: An M-1x1 panel, cut in half along the diagonal.  For structural designers who are too hip to be square.

Name: antenna_cone
Title: CA-A02 Helical Omnidirectional Antenna
Description: A low gain omnidirectional antenna for short range, high bandwidth communications.

Name: antenna_cone_toggle
Title: CA-A02 Conic Antenna
Description: Due to the lack of roads on Kerbin, we were able to purchase a large number of surplus traffic cones and turn them all into a fairly efficient omni antenna. Multiple attachment options and colors available using the toggle buttons. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: antenna_quetzal
Title: CA-A06 Omnidirectional Antenna
Description: A simple omnidirectional antenna. Can be used for short range telecommunications or as a backup medium gain antenna.

Name: antenna_tv
Title: CA-A01 Ground Plane Antenna
Description: A simple omnidirectional antenna for telemetry purposes.

Name: Antennacomtec1
Title: AIES CommTech-1 Antenna
Description: A small folding antenna that must be deployed before use. Most useful for Comm satellites.

Name: Antennacomtec2
Title: AIES CommTech-2 Antenna
Description: The next generation of the CommTech 1. Slightly larger, but capable of reaching to the inner planets.

Name: AntennaDF2
Title: AIES CommTech DF-RD Antenna
Description: A very small onmi antenna. It is always on, lightweight, and requires little power, however, it has a very short range. Best used during ascent, or for a lander to communicate with a orbiting relay.

Name: Antennaesc
Title: AIES CommTech ESC-EXP Antenna
Description: Standard deployable omni.

Name: Antennaexpatvr2
Title: AIES CommTech EXP-VR-2T Antenna
Description: Deployable omni. Considerable range even when retracted, always on.

Name: APAS89-95
Title: APAS-89/95
Description: The Androgynous Peripheral Attach System series 89/95.

Name: argon-0625-1
Title: ERG-MICRON-C Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: The largest 0.625m tank out there for the noble gases of houses Argon, Xenon and Krypton. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-0625-2
Title: ERG-MICRON-B Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: This should be at least... five times bigger! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-0625-3
Title: ERG-MICRON-A Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: The MICRON-A is the poor man's tiny electric propulsion tank. Well, we say that, but it's still ain't cheap. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-125-1
Title: ERG-30 Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: Fuelling your spacecraft with medium-weight noble gas, this tank is a limited offer and won't be on the market forever. Get one now, before all of them... are gone. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-125-2
Title: ERG-20 Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: There was some demand for a half-size ERG-30, so Argyle delivered a few of these. They have some interesting features and look like someone cut one of the ERG-30s in half.

Name: argon-125-3
Title: ERG-10 Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: What a small tank! Hopefully it will come in handy, because it's just too cute to ignore! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-25-1
Title: ARG-600K Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: Originally designed to hold propane fuel for the KSC's kitchens, this tank was repurposed (stolen) by an Argyle engineer (janitor) and converted to hold his favourite noble gases. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-25-2
Title: ARG-300K Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: The ARG-300K is the sub-pinnacle of Argyle Argonics' tank line. It's pretty big and reasonably solid.

Name: argon-25-3
Title: ARG-150K Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: Budget cutbacks at space agencies make this smaller electric propulsion pressure vessel viable. It still holds a respectable amount of some noble gases. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-radial-0625-1
Title: A-101 Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: This slightly larger radial electric propulsion tank can deliver slightly more propellant. Got it? (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: argon-radial-125-1
Title: A-102 Electric Propulsion Tank
Description: A micro electric propulsion tank, for all your micro electric propulsion needs. May or may not be a repainted PB-X50R with a tube on the side. The tube doesn't seem to do anything. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Ariane3Stage1
Title: Ariane 3 L145 (1st stage)
Description: The first stage of Ariane 3 is powered by 4 Vulcain V engines. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Ariane3Stage3
Title: Ariane 3 H8 (3rd stage)
Description: A small liquid fuel engine to circle orbit. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Ariane4Decoupler1
Title: Ariane 3/4 decoupler (1st stage)
Description: Just a stack decoupler with tiny retro-SRBs.

Name: Ariane4Decoupler2
Title: Ariane 3/4 decoupler (2nd stage)
Description: Just a stack decoupler with tiny retro-SRBs.

Name: Ariane4Fairing
Title: Ariane 3/4 fairing
Description: A fairing to protect the payload.

Name: Ariane4NoseCone
Title: Ariane 4 liquid booster's nosecone
Description: A small nosecone to put on the top of liquid booster, to permit a better jettison.

Name: Ariane4NoseCone2
Title: Ariane 4 solid booster's nosecone
Description: A small nosecone to put on the top of solid booster, to permit a better jettison.

Name: Ariane4RadialDecoupler
Title: Ariane 4 radial decoupler
Description: A radial decoupler to jettison SRB.

Name: Ariane4Stage1
Title: Ariane 4 L220 (1st stage)
Description: The first stage of Ariane 4 powered by 4 Vulcain V engines.

Name: Ariane4Stage2
Title: Ariane 3/4 L33 (2nd stage)
Description: Nearly nothing changed since Ariane 1.

Name: Ariane4Stage3
Title: Ariane 4 H10 III (3rd stage)
Description: The cryogenic third stage of the variety used in the majority of Ariane 4 launches. Powered by a HM7B++ engine, and equiped with small attitude control thrusters fueled with gaseous hydrogen (boil-off from the main tank).

Name: Ariane4Sylda
Title: Ariane 3/4 SYLDA
Description: A system to place 2 payloads in the Ariane 4 fairing.

Name: Ariane5_EAP
Title: EAP MPS-241A
Description: Ariane 5's solid booster

Name: Ariane5_engine
Title: Ariane 5 engine Vulcain II
Description: The Vulcain II is the engine of the Ariane 5 cryogenic stage.

Name: Ariane5_EPS
Title: Ariane 5 EPS
Description: The EPS is the second stage of the Ariane 5.

Name: Ariane5_FairingBig
Title: Ariane 5 big fairing
Description: A big fairing for big payload.

Name: Ariane5_FairingSmall
Title: Ariane 5 small fairing
Description: A small fairing for small payloads.

Name: Ariane5_NoseCone
Title: Ariane 5 EAP nosecone
Description: A small nosecone to put on the top of EAPs, to permit a better jettison and land smoothly with a parachute.

Name: Ariane5_RadialDecoupler
Title: Ariane 5 radial decoupler
Description: A radial decoupler to jettison EAP (SRB).

Name: Ariane5_tank
Title: Ariane 5 EPC
Description: The EPC is the main stage of Ariane 5. It's a huge fuel tank.

Name: Ariane6_Fairing
Title: Ariane 6 fairing
Description: A fairing to protect payload.

Name: Ariane6_Stage1
Title: P135 (three)
Description: The original proposal for Ariane 6 would have consisted of four P135 solid boosters and a cryogenic upper stage. Three P135 boosters strapped together would have made up the first stage, while a single P135 would serve as the second stage. This booster design was later dropped in favor of a cryogenic core with two or four P120 boosters.

Name: Ariane6_Stage2
Title: P135
Description: The P135 was intended to serve as the first and second stage of the Ariane 6 PPH. The first stage would have consisted of three P135 boosters, with a single booster acting as second stage.

Name: Ariane6_Stage3
Title: H30
Description: The H30 is powered by the Vinci engine and contains approximately 30 t of propellant. It is intended to serve as the upper stage of Ariane 6.

Name: asasmodule1-2
Title: Advanced Reaction Wheel Module, Large
Description: Using a powerful electric motor, this large reaction wheel allows for minor attitude adjustments even to larger spacecraft without expending propellant.

Name: ASDecoupler
Title: AIES AS Decoupler
Description: New decoupled system allowing safe separation stages large side

Name: ASET_LL
Title: ASET Landing Leg
Description: (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: AtlasVAdapter
Title: CST-100 3M Adapter
Description: A structural adapter to connect the service module of the CST-100 to 3.75 meter parts.

Name: ATV_RCS_back
Title: ATV RCS aft
Description: Intended to represent the ATVs aft RCS thrusters. Place four near the aft end of ATVs sides. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: avionicsNoseCone
Title: CH-J3 Fly-By-Wire Avionics Hub
Description: Have you ever wanted to impress your peers by showing off your elite flying skills, but lacked the skills to become a trained pilot? C7 Aerospace's Fly-By-Wire Avionics Hub is the solution! This module allows even the most minimally trained crew to fly like an Ace! WARNING: This module cannot operate autonomously. Warranty void if attempting to do so. WARNING: Module contains no internal gyroscopes or control systems (control actuators sold separately). WARNING: Warranty void without proper use of C7 Aerospace Brand Sickness Bags (sold separately, currently out of stock).

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_ControlSurface_SH_4mProcedural
Title: Wing - Control Surface (B9 SH) [Procedural]
Description: Control surface of unknown size, mass and other measurements as well. The results of many years of mutual industrial espionage / cooperation.

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_Procedural_TypeA
Title: B9 Procedural Wing (Spaceplane)
Description: Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_Procedural_TypeB
Title: B9 Procedural Control Surface (Spaceplane)
Description: Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_Procedural_TypeC
Title: B9 Procedural Wing, All-Moving (Spaceplane)
Description: Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: B9_Control_RCS_Port_R1Ox
Title: R1 - C Attitude Jet (550/890N class)
Description: A generic, single port, RCS thruster for attitude control.

Name: B9_Control_RCS_Port_R1x
Title: R1 - A Attitude Jet (69/111N class)
Description: A generic, single port, RCS thruster for attitude control.

Name: B9_Control_RCS_Port_R1X1x
Title: R1 - B Attitude Jet (138/233N class)
Description: A generic, single port, RCS thruster for attitude control.

Name: barquetta
Title: SSTL-150 Satellite Bus
Description: A generic satellite bus for mini satellites and probes.

Name: basef1sond
Title: AIES F1 'Sond' Base Plate
Description: Useful to hold all scientific instruments, perfect for a probe core. Comes in two different shapes.

Name: baseinstrul8
Title: AIES L8 Base Plate
Description: Useful to hold all scientific instruments, perfect for a probe core. Comes in two different shapes.

Name: basepuntv2r10
Title: AIES V2-R11 Fairing Base
Description: Basis for protective fairings (TOP-1000, TOP-1500, TOP-2000). Not a decoupler.

Name: basicCanard
Title: Basic Canard
Description: After many late night snack binges, we've developed a new control surface: the Basic Canard! Perfectly sized for smaller craft or ships that don't need the extra control. Crafted out of the finest second-hand aluminum, the Basic Canard is light but lacks the duribility for atmospheric re-entry. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: basicFin
Title: Basic Fin
Description: This simple bolt-on aluminum fin may not be the cutting edge of aerospace engineering but it's dirt cheap and will make your rocket slightly less unstable.

Name: BasketTrussCX
Title: Delta IV DCSS Equipment Bay
Description: The Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS) avionics and engine mounting truss.

Name: battery-0625
Title: B-3K Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: The biggest selling point of the B-3K is its reliance on 28 AAAA batteries, for redundancy. Note, unit may not operate with any dead batteries present. Do not attempt to remove batteries while running.

Name: battery-125
Title: B-6K Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: The B-6K is generally more reliable than the B-3K, because it uses the less accident-prone E batteries in its inline mount. Batt-Direct also advertises replacement capability for each battery, but recommends that this not be done by anyone outside of Batt-Direct. And certainly not in space.

Name: battery-25
Title: B-12K Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: In order to undercut Zaltonic Electronics, Batt Man Batteries has begun selling its largest 12K battery pack at wholesale prices directly to the KSC. A key selling point? The integrated ladder.

Name: battery-375
Title: B-10K Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: It's likely that without the impetus for extra-large parts that Kerbodyne provided, the B-10K would have remained a far-off dream in Bandas Kerman's mind. An innovative system of removable wedge-shaped battery platters deliver quite a large amount of charge.

Name: battery-rad-125
Title: B-800 Rechargeable Battery
Description: After the collapse of Batt-Direct's "eclectic electric" scooter project, which has been generally attributed to poor management by top-level executives, the company found themselves with a surplus of large, potent scooter batteries. What better use for these than in a burgeoning space program?

Name: batteryBAEr
Title: AIES BAE-R Battery
Description: Small industrial battery, perfect for small probes and satellites.

Name: batteryBank
Title: Z-1k Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: The Z-1k is a stackable battery bank, with ten times the power capacity of the Z-100.

Name: batteryBankLarge
Title: Z-4K Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: New advances in surge control technology made The Z-4K, the largest battery pack ever put into production a reality. While Zaltonic admits intense electrical discharges can be really cool, shorting the Z-4K's contacts should probably be avoided.

Name: batteryBankMini
Title: Z-200 Rechargeable Battery Bank
Description: The Z-200 is a stackable variant of the Z-100 battery pack, with increased capacity. In emergency situations, please refrain from "reversing the polarity".

Name: batteryPack
Title: Z-100 Rechargeable Battery Pack
Description: The Z-100 battery pack is the standard model for electrical applications. Holds two (2) AAAA batteries and holds a maximum 100 units of charge.

Name: BE-3
Title: BE-3
Description: The BE-3 (Blue Engine 3) is a LH2/LOX rocket engine developed by Blue Origin. The BE-3 uses a combustion tap-off cycle engine design which takes a small amount of combustion gases from the main combustion chamber in order to power the engine turbopumps. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: BE3EngineCompartment
Title: BE-3 Engine Compartment
Description: The compartment which contains the BE-3 Engine. Also acts as a heat shield to prevent damage to the engine components during accent and landing burns. Usage: Place directly on to the bottom of the fuel tank, then add the BE-3 part from underneath.

Name: bluedog_ableEngine
Title: AJ10 Series (Early)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This is the original Vanguard second stage / Able / Delta configuration, without restart capability. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_ablestarEngine
Title: AJ10 Series (Mid)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents mid-period AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Thor-Ablestar and Delta E through Delta N. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_AgenaA
Title: Agena-A/B Flight Pack
Description: Flight Pack RCS for Agena-A and BAC Model 8048/8081 engine.

Name: bluedog_agenaAntenna
Title: Agena-D Antenna
Description: An extendible antenna for the Agena-D.

Name: bluedog_AgenaD
Title: Agena-D Flight Pack
Description: Flight Pack RCS for Agena-D and BAC Model 8096/8247 engine.

Name: bluedog_agenaLongTank
Title: Agena-D Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Agena-D Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_agenaLongWhiteTank
Title: Agena-B Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Agena-B Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_agenaMediumTank
Title: Agena-A Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Agena-A Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_agenaNoseCone
Title: Agena Nose Cone
Description: This nose cone is designed to go over the top of the Agena Docking Adapter for the Agena Target Vehicle.

Name: bluedog_agenaPort
Title: Gemini Agena Target/Docking Adapter
Description: Gemini target/docking adapter used to convert an Agena-D into a Gemini Agena Target Vehicle.

Name: bluedog_agenaProbeCore
Title: Agena Avionics Package [1.5m]
Description: An early but advanced avionics module for upper stages. Carries an 11.8 kWh battery, providing control for just over 47 hr, and an omnidirectional antenna with an effective range of 1,500 km to ground stations. Capable of maintaining a pitch and roll program. Allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: bluedog_agenaSecondaryEngine
Title: Agena-D Secondary Propulsion System
Description: SPS for Agena-D.

Name: bluedog_agenaShortTank
Title: Agena Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short length fuel tank for the Agena Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_agenaShortTankM
Title: Agena Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short length fuel tank for the Agena Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_alcyone
Title: BE-3/Alcyone
Description: Originally flown as the retrorocket in Block II Ranger probes, later used as apogee motor on Vela satellites and (in 1967) to launch Australia's first satellite. Diameter: [0.46 m].

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ActiveDockingMechanism
Title: Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Active)
Description: Once soft docking is achieved and the vessels properly aligned, retract the probe to hard dock and establish a solid connection. IT WILL ONLY WORK WITH THE Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Passive).

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Capsule
Title: Apollo Command Module
Description: The module that was used to transport astronauts to the Moon. Room for three crew.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Decoupler
Title: Apollo Command/Service Module Decoupler
Description: This is used to decouple the Command Module from the Service Module prior to reentry.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_DockingLight
Title: Apollo EVA / Docking Light
Description: This light (traditionally mounted to the decoupler ring on the Apollo CSM) swings out to provide illumination for docking/berthing operations and to aid astronauts on EVAs.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Heatshield
Title: Apollo 2.5m Heat Shield
Description: Large 2.5m structural heatshield for Apollo CSM. It is very thick in order to withstand the intense heat of lunar reentries. Remove some of the ablator for low orbital missions, to save weight. The structure itself is lighter as well, at the cost of removing the jettison hardware. Make sure your parachutes can stop the weight of the capsule and the heatshield.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_HGA
Title: Apollo High Gain Antenna
Description: A collapsable relay antenna consisting of four high gain dishes. Intended to be placed on the mounting bracket of the Apollo Service Engine.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_LES
Title: Apollo Launch Escape System
Description: The Apollo launch escape system (LES) purpose was to abort the mission by pulling the Command Module (the crew cabin) away from the launch vehicle in an emergency, such as a pad fire before launch, guidance failure, or launch vehicle failure likely to lead to an imminent explosion.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Parachute
Title: Apollo Parachutes
Description: Parachute landing systems for the Apollo CSM. Place in 3x symmetry around the Apollo Parachute Mount.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ParachuteMount
Title: Apollo Parachute Mount
Description: Structural adapter for Apollo parachutes and docking port. Place on top of the capsule, add parachutes in 3x symmetry. The Active Docking Mechanism goes on top. Includes a decoupler for the docking mechanism, to clear the way for the parachutes.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_PassiveDockingMechanism
Title: Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Passive)
Description: This is the passive port for the Apollo Docking Mechanism. IT WILL ONLY WORK WITH THE Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Active). This should be placed on the top of the LEM.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_RCSquad
Title: Apollo Service Module RCS Quad Thrusters
Description: This is the RCS Quad Thrusters for the Apollo Service Module. Place 4 pods 90 degrees apart. 2:1 O/F Ratio.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ServiceEngine
Title: AJ10-137 (Service Propulsion System)
Description: The Aerojet AJ10-137 rocket engine used on the Apollo Service Module as the Service Propulsion System. Diameter: [2.6 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ServiceModule
Title: Apollo Service Module
Description: The Apollo Service Module that has a complete package of fuel, monoprop, batteries, fuel cells, and storage bays for your service module.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_Capsule
Title: Apollo Block III+ Command Module
Description: Significant changes were made to better adapt Apollo to its new role as a crew shuttle for LEO, and the internal volume was modified to fit 5 crew for reentry. Be sure to bring extra living space by attaching the Mission Module to dock with after orbiting. By only using the Command Module, you will have resources for 5 crew for 72 hours. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_HGA
Title: Apollo Block III High Gain Antenna
Description: A collapsable relay antenna consisting of four high gain dishes. Intended to be placed on the mounting bracket of the Apollo Service Engine Block III. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_MissionModule
Title: Apollo Block III+ Mission Module
Description: In order to increase the living space and mission duration of the Apollo Block III CSM. This mission module is essentially several more cubic meters of living space for the crew. Place it upside down in place of the lunar module, with docking ports on each end. Extract with the CSM after circularization. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_ServiceEngine
Title: Apollo Block III Service Engine (LMAE)
Description: With the decreased weight and LEO operation design, there was no longer a need for a large engine to power the CSM. NASA decided to reuse the successful Lunar Module Ascent Engine. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_ServiceModule
Title: Apollo Block III+ Service Module
Description: Significant changes were made to better adapt Apollo to its new role as a crew shuttle for LEO and the Service Module was decreased in size and weight. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block5_SolarPanels
Title: Apollo Block V Solar Array
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel used for the Block V Apollo CSM. 8.05m^2. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Atlas_LR101_Radial
Title: LR101 Series
Description: Pump or pressure-fed kerolox vernier engine. Used for attitude control and final velocity adjustment in the MA-x system (2x LR89 + LR105 + 2x LR101) on Atlas, and MB-x system (LR79 or RS-27 + 2xLR101) on Thor-Able / Thor-Agena / Thor-Delta / Delta. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Atlas_LR105
Title: LR105 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator sustainer engine used in the Atlas launch vehicle. It, like the Atlas's booster engines (LR89s) are lit on the ground, but after a bit over 2 minutes' flight the boosters are dropped and the Atlas core continues to orbit under the power of the sustainer engine (and the verniers for roll control and final adjustment). The final configuration of the LR105 (like the LR89) uses RS-27 components for increased performance. As a sustainer engine, the LR105 has relatively poor sea level specific impulse compared to most boosters, but somewhat better vacuum specific impulse--though the difference in both is nowhere near as pronounced as when comparing a booster to an upper stage engine. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Atlas_LR89
Title: LR89 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator engine that served as booster for Atlas. Late model LR89s were upgraded with RS-27 components for higher efficiency. Very similar to LR79 (this was the pure-booster variant). Diameter: [1.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_atlas1AdapterTank
Title: Mercury-Atlas Adapter Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Atlas Launch Vehicle that will adapt to the Mercury Capsule

Name: bluedog_atlas1LongTank
Title: Atlas Fuel Tank
Description: Main fuel tank for the Atlas launch vehicle. Be sure to attach the Atlas Engine Adapter Fuel Tank to the bottom of this tank before attaching the LR105 and the Engine Fairing.

Name: bluedog_atlas1MediumTank
Title: Atlas Fuel Tank (Medium)
Description: Medium fuel tank for the Atlas launch vehicle.

Name: bluedog_atlas1ShortTank
Title: Atlas Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short fuel tank for the Atlas launch vehicle.

Name: bluedog_atlasFairingAdapterTank
Title: Atlas Engine Adapter Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank adapter for the bottom of the Atlas Main Fuel Tank. It provides special nodes for the attachment of the LR105 Sustainer engine as well as the Booster Fairing for the LR89 Booster Engines.

Name: bluedog_Castor120
Title: Castor 120
Description: The Castor 120 is a medium solid booster used on the Minotaur and Athena launch vehicles. Its design was based on the TU-903, which serves as the first stage of the Peacekeeper ICBM. The standard thrust curve can be modified to produce a regressive burn that reduces maximum acceleration or a saddle-shaped profile that limits aerodynamic forces. Burn time 79 seconds. Diameter: [2.34 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Castor30
Title: Castor 30A
Description: The CASTOR 30 is a low cost, robust, state-of-the-art upper stage motor. This development motor is nominally designed as an upper stage that can function as a second or third stage depending on the vehicle configuration. The design of the  CASTOR 30 uses all flight proven technology and materials. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_castorSRB
Title: Castor 1
Description: The Castor 1 was first used for a successful suborbital launch of a Scout X-1 rocket on September 2, 1960. Castor 1 stages were also used as strap-on boosters for launch vehicles using Thor first stages, including the Delta-D. Diameter: [0.79 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_D3Tank
Title: Centaur-D Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur-D Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_Centaur_D5Tank
Title: Centaur-D Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur-D Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_Centaur_LargeRCS
Title: Centaur 3-Way Large RCS Block (69/111 N Class)
Description: Three way RCS block for the Centaur stages. Place one on each of the mounting blocks on either side of the engine mount.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_SmallRCS
Title: Centaur 3-Way RCS Block (69/111 N Class)
Description: Three way RCS block for the Centaur stages. Place one on each of the mounting blocks on either side of the engine mount.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_Tank
Title: Centaur Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_centaur1875mAdapterFairing
Title: Centaur Interstage Fairing
Description: Interstage fairing for the bottom of the Centaur Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_centaur25mAdapterFairing
Title: Centaur Interstage Fairing Adapter
Description: Interstage fairing for the bottom of the Centaur Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_CentaurT_AdapterTank
Title: Centaur-T Fuel Tank Adapter
Description: Fuel tank adapter for the Centaur-T Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_CentaurT_ShortTank
Title: Centaur-T Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short fuel tank for the Centaur-T Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_CentaurT_WideTank
Title: Centaur-T Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur-T Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_CXA_APAS_A_L04F
Title: APAS-89/95 Active
Description: The Androgynous Peripheral Attach System series 89/95. This is the Active version of the APAS. It must work with the APAS-89/95 Passive in order to secure proper docking.

Name: bluedog_CXA_APAS_P
Title: APAS-89/95 Passive
Description: The Androgynous Peripheral Attach System series 89/95. This is the passive version of the APAS. It must work with the APAS-89/95 Active in order to secure proper docking.

Name: bluedog_Delta_GEM40
Title: GEM 40
Description: The Graphite-Epoxy Motor (GEM) replaced the steel case used on earlier Castor-series boosters with a lighter composite case. The 40-inch (1-meter) diameter GEM 40 was used on the Delta II 7000-series in sets of three, four, or nine. When nine boosters were used, six were ignited at liftoff and the remaining three were ignited after burnout and jettison of the first six. Burn time: 58 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta_GEM46
Title: GEM 46
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta_GEM60
Title: GEM 60
Description: The 60-inch (1.5-meter) diameter GEM 60 is used on the Delta IV in sets of two or four. When two boosters are used, both are equipped with thrust vector control (TVC). When four are used, two boosters use TVC while the other two use fixed nozzles to reduce weight. Burn time 90 seconds. Diameter: [1.52 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta2_RS27
Title: H-1/RS-27 Series
Description: The H-1 is an upgrade to the LR79 engine that propelled the Saturn-I and IB vehicles, as well as late-model Delta rockets (as the RS-27). The H-1/RS-27 are optimized for the first-stage main engine role. The RS-27A has a higher expansion ratio for increased performance at altitude since liftoff thrust on the Delta II is augmented by solid boosters and the core burns rather longer. Diameter: [1.0 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_DeltaK_AJ10
Title: AJ10 Series (Advanced)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents advanced era AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Transtage as AJ10-138; similar models but back with the -118 designation were used on the Delta F and Delta K upper stages. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Asterix
Title: Asterix Probe
Description: France's first satellite attained orbit in 1965. It was originally designated A-1, but later renamed after the popular comic character.

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Diapason
Title: Diapason/Diadme Probe
Description: The second French satellite was launched in 1966. It was attitude-stabilised by Earth's magnetic field and used for geodetic measurements. Two almost identical Diadme satellites followed a year later.

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Rita
Title: P4 (Rita 1)
Description: French solid motor, used in a submarine-launched missile and flown as the second stage of Diamant-BP4 rockets in 1975. Diameter: [1.50 m].

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Rubis
Title: P0.68
Description: 3rd stage of Diamant rockets. This is the somewhat larger version used in B and BP4 variants. Diameter: [0.80 m].

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Topaze
Title: P2.2 (Topaze)
Description: Second stage of Diamant-A and -B rockets. Four vectorable nozzles provided roll control as well. Diameter: [0.85 m].

Name: bluedog_Explorer1
Title: Explorer 1 Probe
Description: Explorer 1, the first satellite launched by the United States, was a very simple scientific probe of less than a dozen kilograms. It featured a cosmic ray detector and micrometeorite detectors, as well as temperature sensors. Mercury batteries provided a month of electricity for the high power transmitter and another two and a half months for the low-power transmitter.

Name: bluedog_explorer7probe
Title: Explorer 7 Probe
Description: A 1959 satellite designed to measure fluxes of solar x-rays, hydrogen spectral lines and cosmic rays, as well as collect micrometeorite impact data.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Ascent_Cockpit
Title: Apollo LEM Ascent Stage
Description: The Apollo LEM Ascent Stage provides accommodations for two astronauts to ride to the surface atop the LEM Decent Stage, then return to orbit. Includes integrated fuel tanks, RCS, and communications system. Put the ascent engine on the bottom, and the passive docking port on the top.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Ascent_Engine
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Ascent Engine (LMAE)
Description: Pressure-fed engine used for the ascent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Diameter: [0.86 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Descent_Engine
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Descent Engine (LMDE)
Description: Deeply throttleable pressure-fed vacuum engine used for the descent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Uses storable propellants which are not subject to boiloff, but are far less efficient than hydrolox or even kerolox. The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Descent_Tanks
Title: Apollo LEM Descent Stage
Description: The Apollo LEM Descent Stage contains fuel tanks, landing stability system, and recessed engine mounting point for the Apollo LEM. Also includes a vertical mobility device for Ascent Cockpit ingress and egress. Engine attach node located inside the hole in the bottom.

Name: bluedog_LR87_mod1
Title: LR87 Series
Description: The main engine block for the Titan II/III/IV launch vehicles, with thrust plate. 1.93 O/F Ratio.

Name: bluedog_LR91_mod1
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_LR91_mod2
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Pioneer1
Title: Pioneer 1 Probe
Description: The first spacecraft launched by NASA, in 1958. It was supposed to do a Moon flyby, but its rocket underperformed and it reentered the atmosphere two days after launch.

Name: bluedog_Pioneer4
Title: Pioneer 4 Probe
Description: First US probe to escape Earth's gravitational pull after it flew by the Moon in 1959. The tiny spacecraft was spin-stabilised and carried a radiation experiment as well as two small photocells, which failed to trigger.

Name: bluedog_rangerCore
Title: Ranger Block I Core
Description: Probe core used for early Ranger missions as well as (in stripped-down form)  the first Mariner missions.

Name: bluedog_redstone
Title: NAA-75-110 A-Series
Description: Used on the Redstone missile.  Designed for Ethanol/LOx (A-6) (1.5 O/F Ratio), it was later adapted to burn Hydyne/LOx (A-7) (1.73 O/F Ratio)(higher performance (12%) yet more toxic) for use in Jupiter C / Juno I.  When Redstone MRLV was adapted from Jupiter C for manned use the A7 was switched back to Ethanol, accepting slightly lower performance for lack of toxicity. Thrust Vector Control was provided by carbon thrust vanes (add the Redstone Fin / Thrust vane part in 4x symmetry), and additional attitude control was provided by actuating fins. Mass includes thrust frame. Diameter: [1.77 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_rl10
Title: RL10 Series Vacuum Engine
Description: Hydrolox restartable expander-cycle vacuum engine used in multiple upper stages, including Centaur, the Saturn I S-IV, and the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage. It has low thrust, but very high specific impulse and low mass, making it ideal for high energy, beyond-low-Earth-orbit applications like launching satellites to geostationary transfer orbits or to the Moon or other planets. However, like all hydrolox engines, hydrogen boiloff is a serious issue without heat pumps or radiators. Diameter: [0.92 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Saturn_S4_InstrumentUnit
Title: Saturn I Instrument Unit
Description: Guidance ring used for early Saturn I launches.

Name: bluedog_Soltan_Inline
Title: 100-Inch SRM (inline)
Description: Inline version of the 3-segment motor designed for a solid-augmented Titan II around 1961. Four test firings were made, of which two ended with the nozzle disintegrating. Burn time roughly 80 seconds. Diameter: [2.54 m].

Name: bluedog_Soltan_Radial
Title: 100-Inch SRM
Description: 3-segment motor designed for a solid-augmented Titan II around 1961. Four test firings were made, of which two ended with the nozzle disintegrating. Burn time roughly 80 seconds. Diameter: [2.54 m].

Name: bluedog_Soltan_SRBnose
Title: 100-Inch SRM nosecone
Description: Nosecone and separation rocket for 100-inch solid motors. Diameter: [2.54 m].

Name: bluedog_star20
Title: Star 20/Altair III
Description: The lightweight, external nozzle is a composite of graphite, plastic, and steel. The consumable pyrogen igniter is actuated by two 6-second-delay electrical initiators or two SBASI zero-time-delay initiators. Diameter: [0.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_star31
Title: Star 31/Antares III
Description: Antares III is the third-generation third stage for Vought Corporation's Scout launch vehicle. The design incorporates an 89-percent-solids HTPB propellant in a Kevlar(r) filament-wound case insulated with silica-filled EPDM rubber. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_star37
Title: Star 37FM
Description: The STAR 37 is a vacuum solid rocket motor, originally developed for the Surveyor lunar lander program as a braking stage. Later variants were used exclusively as apogee kick stages. Diameter: 0.93 m. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_star48
Title: Star 48B
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB3seg
Title: SRMU
Description: The Titan IVB Solid Rocket Motor Upgrade (SRMU, also know as the Upgraded Solid Rocket Motor or USRM), was developed with the goal of achieving a 25% increase in capacity over the Titan IVA with the UA1207 SRM. It achieved this through the use of a more energetic propellant and a 3-segment composite case that carried more fuel and weighed less than the UA1207's 7-segment steel case. Burn time 150 seconds, 3.2 m diameter. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB5seg
Title: UA1205
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. Diameter: [3.05 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB5segStack
Title: UA1205
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. This is the (never flown, but proposed) inline version with two TVC tanks. Diameter: [3.05 m].

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB7seg
Title: UA1207
Description: The UA1207 was used on the Titan IVA, which was developed to launch payloads that had been designed to fly on the Shuttle from Vandenberg. It was a 7-segment modification of the 5-segment UA1205 used on the Titan 3. Burn time 130 seconds. Diameter: [3.05 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB7segStack
Title: UA1207
Description: The UA1207 was used on the Titan IVA, which was developed to launch payloads that had been designed to fly on the Shuttle from Vandenberg. It was a 7-segment modification of the 5-segment UA1205 used on the Titan 3. Burn time 130 seconds. This is the (never flown, but proposed) inline version with 2 TVC tanks. Diameter: [3.05 m].

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRBseparator
Title: Titan SRM separation motor
Description: Lower separation motor for Titan solids.

Name: bluedog_vanguardEngine
Title: Vanguard X-405
Description: First stage engine used on the Vanguard launch vehicle. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: BMWIIIa
Title: BMW IIIa
Description: WWI-era supercharged water-cooled straight six inline engine, rated at 230HP to 2km at 1400RPM (max). 9ft 2-blade fixed pitch propeller.

Name: BuffaloCanard
Title: Buffalo Canard
Description: A half-sized version of the Buffalo Winglet, the canard helps inprove flight stability. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: BuffaloElevon1
Title: Type 1 Buffalo Elevon
Description: Feel the need to attach an elevator, rudder or aileron to just about any surface you can get your mitts on? Well this small elevon is for you. Made of mostly new factory parts, it will fit just about anywhere. Just don't expect a huge performance out of such a small part. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: BuffaloWinglet
Title: Buffalo Winglet
Description: This winglet has a movable control surface that affords it the ability to alter a vessel's flight path. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Bumper_Body
Title: A-4 Mid Section
Description: Liquid Oxygen tank of A-4 rocket.

Name: Bumper_Control
Title: A-4 Guidance Unit
Description: Early, inefficient guidance.

Name: Bumper_Engine
Title: A-4
Description: Thiel Lox/Alcohol rocket engine. Used on V-2 missile. Work began June 1936. Interim design, but went into production. Used 18 x 1.5 tonne thrust chambers, feeding common mixing chamber. Tested from 1939, mass production 1943-1945. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Bumper_Engine_Unclad
Title: A-4
Description: Thiel Lox/Alcohol rocket engine. Used on V-2 missile. Work began June 1936. Interim design, but went into production. Used 18 x 1.5 tonne thrust chambers, feeding common mixing chamber. Tested from 1939, mass production 1943-1945. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Bumper_Fin
Title: A-4 Fin
Description: Stability and control fin for A-4 rocket.

Name: Bumper_Nose
Title: A-4 Nose Section
Description: Ethanol tank and nose section of A-4 rocket. Contains 738kg of ballast.

Name: ca_aacs
Title: CA-AACS Advanced Attitude Control System
Description: An integrated computer system utilizing two star trackers and ring laser gyroscopes (RLG) to provide attitude control information to the spacecraft.

Name: ca_accelerometer
Title: CA-SC103 Accelerometer
Description: The SC103 has sensitive sensors that can detect seismic vibrations and vehicle accelerations.

Name: ca_ant_gps
Title: CA-KPS KerbNet Position System Antenna
Description: This antenna provides access to the KerbNet system for very detailed tracking of the spacecraft's position. It can be used as a omni-directional antenna, but it is not very powerful (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_barometer
Title: CA-SC102 Barometer
Description: The SC102 measures the local atmospheric pressure.

Name: ca_battery_l
Title: CA-300i Battery
Description: A 500 Wh capacity battery.

Name: ca_battery_m
Title: CA-100i Battery
Description: A 170 Wh capacity battery.

Name: ca_battery_s
Title: CA-25i Battery
Description: A 85 Wh capacity battery. Low profile for easier placement.

Name: ca_DUSTC
Title: CA-DUST-C Dust Sample Collector
Description: The DUST-C array features an aerogel - coated collector for trapping the dust particles to return them to Earth for analysis. NOTE: heat shield and parachutes are not included.

Name: ca_DUSTX
Title: CA-DUST-X Cosmic Dust Counter
Description: The DUST-X is an instrument that collects dust particles and provides information about their size, speed and direction.

Name: ca_ELIX
Title: CA-ELIX Electrostatic & Ionization Experiment
Description: The ELIX is an electrostatic analyzer for analyzing the synthesis of charged particles. By employing electric and magnetic fields ELIX concentrates and separates the different particles by their mass and charge, allowing for very precise measurements of plasma density, velocity and distribution.

Name: ca_ESM
Title: Pioneer 10/11 Science Package
Description: An integrated science package originally designed for the Pioneer 10 & 11 deep space probes. Includes a thermal control system with a thermal rejection capability of 50 Watts.

Name: ca_ESM2
Title: CA-ESM2 Quetzal Extended Service Module
Description: When life give you lemons (or broken Quetzal probes from the factory), learn to make lemonade (Stick inside of them a fuel tank, batteries, new electronics). Profit! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_fom_drogue
Title: CAE-PD7 Fomalhaut Drogue Parachute
Description: Some Fomalhaut atmospheric entry profiles call for earlier and/or more gentle braking. For those, we've designed this massive and resilient drogue chute. Warning: This chute is not rated for low touch-down velocities. Prepare for harsh, bumpy landings (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_fom_heatS
Title: CAE-HS100 Fomalhaut Heat Shield
Description: This is the bottom piece of the Fomalhaut spherical atmospheric entry shell. It is coated with a very heat-resistant ablative material to keep the stuff inside from getting cooked. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_fom_lander
Title: CAE-L165 'Fomalhaut' Lander Probe
Description: The CAE Planetary Science Division has produced this rugged 'metal tank', and crammed it with batteries, radiation lining, a thermometer, a camera to image the landing site, and an antenna wrapped around the top. It is designed to survive rough landings in extreme environments (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_fom_parachute
Title: CAE-P16 Fomalhaut Parachute
Description: This part is the top cover of the Fomalhaut atmospheric entry capsule. This parachute attaches directly to the Fomalhaut lander for deployment after re-entry. It does so successfully most of the time. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_fom_sp
Title: CAE-E175 Fomalhaut Solar Panel
Description: A small and basic solar panel angled for mounting on the Fomalhaut lander collar to provide electric recharge of the batteries (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_gravioli
Title: CA-SC104 Gravity Gradiometer
Description: The SC104 gravity gradiometer is used to measure the acceleration due to gravity of a planetary body. By measuring the gravity gradient several indirect observations about the subsurface synthesis and morphology can be made.

Name: ca_GRS
Title: CA-SCGRS Gamma Ray Spectrometer
Description: The Gamma Ray Spectrometer measures the gamma ray energy generated from the planetary surfaces when these are bombarded by cosmic rays. By measuring the gamma ray energy we can determine the elemental synthesis and concentration of the soil.

Name: ca_H2RS
Title: CA-H2RS High-Resolution Radar System
Description: This High-Resolution Radar System uses its 6 antennas mounted in 3 booms to create very accurate radar scans. The system is very sensitive and can track direction and speed of object in the surface. It was designed to both track the speed of vehicles moving between KSC buildings (For speeding tickets) and to justify yet another satellite launch. Win-win (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_HOLA
Title: CA-HOLA Laser Altimeter
Description: Since KSC pilots kept crashing into mountains to the West, we were asked to help. We developed an instrument to lower their altitude by shooting lasers at their peaks from orbit. That failed completely, but we discovered that the laser bounced back at different time intervals depending on the altitude, thus the High-Power Orbital Lazer Altimeter was born (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_jib
Title: Generic 0.5 kN Thruster
Description: A generic mono/bipropellant rocket motor. Can be configured within a great range of propellants. Plume configured by RealPlume.
COST NOTES: Same costs as other 0.5 kN engine

Name: ca_KLIR
Title: CA-THEMIS Infrared Spectrometer
Description: The THEMIS (Thermal Emission Imaging System) is used to measure the thermal emissions of the planetary bodies, calculate the surface temperature or even map small details of surface features. The spectrometer can also measure the wavelength of IR emissions to detect certain minerals in the soil.

Name: ca_lahar
Title: R-40 Series
Description: A bipropellant rocket motor burning either MMH and MON3 (R-40A/B and R-42) or Hydrazine and MON3 (R-42DM). Used for attitude control, orbital insertion or as an apogee motor. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ca_landv_battery
Title: Surveyor Battery Pack
Description: The main battery pack of the Surveyor lunar lander. Capacity: <color=orange>3650</color> Wh.

Name: ca_landv_cam_s1
Title: Surveyor Landing Survey Camera
Description: The main survey television camera of the Surveyor lander. The integrated mirror can be rotated by 360 degrees to create panoramas of the landing site.

Name: ca_landv_core
Title: Surveyor Core
Description: The main assembly of the Surveyor lander. Includes a set of landing legs, attitude control system and propellant for its 3 vernier engines (sold separately). A solid fueled retro-motor is required for normal landing operations.

Name: ca_landv_hga
Title: Surveyor Planar Antenna and Solar Array
Description: The planar high gain antenna and solar array for the Surveyor lander.

Name: ca_landv_omni
Title: Surveyor Omni Antenna
Description: The omnidirectional low gain antenna for the Surveyor lander. Can serve as a backup for the main planar antenna.

Name: ca_landv_soilScoop
Title: Surveyor Soil Mechanics Surface Sampler
Description: The soil mechanics surface sampler is an instrument designed to test the physical properties of the topsoil (density, porosity, resistivity) and to expose subsoil material for photography.

Name: ca_landv_srm
Title: STAR 37
Description: The STAR 37 is a vacuum solid rocket motor, originally developed for the Surveyor lunar lander program as a braking stage. Later variants were used exclusively as apogee kick stages. Diameter: 0.93 m. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ca_landv_vernier
Title: TD-339
Description: The Vernier System as used on the Surveyor Probes. Uses storable hypergolic propellants, has infinite restarts and is not subject to ullage. Throttleable down to 30%. Historically 3 of them were used on the Surveyor probes which landed on the Moon. Diameter: [0.13 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ca_linkor
Title: Fregat-M Upper Stage
Description: The Fregat is an upper stage used on the Soyuz and Zenit launch vehicles for injecting/placing payloads into low, medium or high energy orbits. It originated as a propulsion module for the Soviet Luna and Mars missions and later modified to serve as a standalone upper stage. Versions include the original Fregat, the Fregat-M with increased propellant loading and extended S5.92 nozzle, the Fregat-MT with additional propellant tanks and the Fregat-SB designed specifically for the Zenit launch vehicle family (featuring an auxiliary drop tank). Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ca_louver_m
Title: CA-TCL8 Thermal Control Louver
Description: Thermal Control Louvers are heat control systems that can expel heat by exposing cooling fins and a radiator. Toggle the vents open to release heat from the spacecraft. This system has double the height and performance of the TCL4-B for better cooling. Rated heat rejection capability 100 Watts.

Name: ca_louver_s
Title: CA-TCL4 Thermal Control Louver
Description: Thermal Control Louvers are heat control systems that can expel heat by exposing cooling fins and a radiator. Toggle the vents open to release heat from the spacecraft. This is the standard size system with a rated heat rejection capability of 40 Watts.

Name: ca_louver_s2
Title: CA-TCL4-B Thermal Control Louver
Description: Thermal Control Louvers are heat control systems that can expel heat by exposing cooling fins and a radiator. Toggle the vents open to release heat from the spacecraft. This is an alternate, longer version of the TCL4, with a rated heat rejection capability of 50 Watts.

Name: ca_LUV
Title: CA-IUVS Imaging Ultraviolet Spectrometer
Description: IUVS (Imaging Ultraviolet Spectrometer) images the lower part of the UV spectrum. By doing so it can measure the global characteristics of the upper atmospheric and ionospheric layers, providing information about the synthesis, the morphology and the interactions between the solar wind and the atmosphere.

Name: ca_magneto2
Title: Triaxial Helium Vector Magnetometer
Description: The magnetometer instruments are used to determine the magnitude and direction of planetary magnetic fields The long boom separates these instruments from any interference caused by magnetic elements in the probe.

Name: ca_RM01
Title: CAE-RM01 RCS Thruster Block
Description: An RCS thruster block for attitude control of upper stages or medium - sized spacecraft.

Name: ca_RM02
Title: CAE-RM02 RCS Thruster Block
Description: A modified RM01 RCS Module with its nozzles facing in opposite directions
MOD: meant for rotational control. The elongated nozzles are the same featured in our Linkor Service Module and are very efficient in a vacuum. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_RM03
Title: CAE-RM03 RCS Thruster Block
Description: An RCS thruster block for attitude control of upper stages or medium - sized spacecraft.

Name: ca_RM04
Title: CAE-RM04 RCS Thruster Block
Description: An RCS thruster block for attitude control of upper stages or medium - sized spacecraft.

Name: ca_RPWS
Title: CA-RPWS Radio and Plasma Wave Science
Description: The Radio and Plasma Wave Science (RPWS) uses sensitive wideband electric/magnetic monopole and dipole antennae to receive low frequency radio transmissions caused by trapped charged particles (cyclotron waves), electrostatic discharges and whistlers (lighting) and thermal plasma. All these sources can be used to analyze the spectrum and type of the plasma, the electron density and distribution of the magnetospheres and the various lighting effects on the lower atmospheric layers.

Name: ca_rs01
Title: CA-RS01 RCS Thruster Block
Description: This small RCS system provides directional thrust in a very compact package.

Name: ca_rs04
Title: CA-RS04 RCS Thruster Block
Description: This four-nozzle RCS block is designed to compliment attitude control systems in small spacecraft.

Name: ca_rst
Title: CA-RST RCS Thruster Block
Description: This compact thruster block uses a single nozzle as a directional RCS or all three as a throttleable rocket engine. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0, RO IN PROGRESS)

Name: ca_rtg2000
Title: Pioneer SNAP-19 RTG
Description: The SNAP-19 radioisotope thermoelectric generator as found on the Pioneer spacecraft. Developed by the Atomic Energy Commission (AEC).

Name: ca_rtg3900
Title: Voyager MHW-RTG
Description: The Multihundred-Watt radioisotope thermoelectric generator (MHW-RTG) as found on the Voyager spacecraft.

Name: ca_rtg8200
Title: GPHS-RTG
Description: The General-Purpose Heat Source radioisotope thermoelectric generator as found on the Ulysses and the New Horizons spacecrafts.

Name: ca_rw_large
Title: RW-4A Radial Reaction Wheel Assembly
Description: This reaction wheel assembly combines three RW4 high performance reaction wheels for larger spacecraft that require precision attitude control.

Name: ca_rw_medium
Title: RW-2A Radial Reaction Wheel Assembly
Description: This reaction wheel assembly combines two RW4 high performance reaction wheels for medium size spacecraft that require precision attitude control.

Name: ca_rw_small
Title: RW4 Radial Reaction Wheel
Description: High performance reaction wheels for precision spacecraft attitude control.

Name: ca_rw_xsmall
Title: RW1 Radial Reaction Wheel
Description: High performance reaction wheels for precision spacecraft attitude control.

Name: ca_sciBoom
Title: Voyager Science Boom
Description: The science boom of the Voyager deep space probe. The boom mounts Narrow and Wide field cameras for orbital survey images, as well as an Infrared and an Ultraviolet spectrometer. NOTE: Deploy the boom to keep experiments away from electromagnetic interference and radiation.

Name: ca_startrack
Title: CA-ACS 'StarTrack' Attitude Control System
Description: A highly sensitive star tracker. By measuring the angle between different stars and comparing them with the stored database it provides attitude control information to the spacecraft.

Name: ca_SWIS
Title: CA-SWIA Solar Wind Analyzer
Description: The Solar Wind Analyzer (SWIA) instrument is designed specifically to detect and measure solar wind electron/ion velocity and density.

Name: ca_tank_lfo_m
Title: CA-LT80 Propellant Tank (Pressurized)
Description: A generic inline high pressure propellant tank for use on medium - sized spacecraft.

Name: ca_tank_mp_m
Title: CA-MT170 Propellant Tank (Pressurized)
Description: A generic inline high pressure propellant tank for use on medium - sized spacecraft.

Name: ca_tank_mp_s
Title: CA-MT10 Propellant Tank (Pressurized)
Description: A generic radially attached high pressure propellant tank for use on upper stages or small - sized spacecraft.

Name: ca_telescope_a
Title: CA-HiRISE Telescope
Description: The High Resolution Imaging Science Experiment (HiRISE) is a Cassegrain - type visible spectrum telescope and one of the biggest to ever fly in a deep space probe. With it's high resolution capability it can acquire high definition color surface images.

Name: ca_thermometer
Title: CA-SC100 Infrared Radiometer
Description: The SC100 radiometer measures the infrared radiant flux, providing information about the atmospheric and/or the surface soil temperature.

Name: ca_torekka_truss
Title: CA-T2A-R33 Torekka Truss Adapter
Description: This structural attaches to the bottom of the Torekka bus to safely and securely attach its propulsion module. Our engineers have included a Shunt Radiator which doubles as a... and let us tell you, we know shunting, we have the best shunting; you're going to love it. Now, where were we? (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_torekkaPM
Title: Voyager Propulsion Module
Description: The Voyager Propulsion Module is powered by a modified version of the STAR-37E solid rocket motor. It includes a Reaction Control System (RCS) for controlling the attitude of the Voyager stack for the duration of the SRM injection burn. Attach it to the bottom of the Voyager truss adapter.

Name: ca_trident
Title: Bi-Propellant Apogee Engine
Description: A cluster of three 400N Bi-Propellant Apogee Motors. Designed for apogee orbit injection of geostationary satellites and for trajectory and planetary orbit maneuvers of deep space probes. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ca_TRIXIE
Title: CA-TRIXIE Multi-spectral Imager
Description: TRIXIE pairs two camera assemblies to image and scan multiple light wavelengths from Ultraviolet to Near-Infrared. This provides a good way to determine surface features and biomes from orbit. The principal designer, Dr. Ed Kerman, did not include what the heck the acronym stands for. There is an optional cover which you can toggle from the right-click menu (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ca_vor_camera
Title: CAE-SC-VIS Vorona Imaging System
