Name: FASAFairingNosecone_4mSRB
Title: Nose Fairing [156" UA156X SRM]
Description: A 156" nose fairing for all your UA156X SRM needs. Includes a separation motor. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAFairingNosecone_6_6mSRB
Title: Nose Fairing [260" UA156X SRM]
Description: A 260" nose fairing for all your AJ-260 SRM needs. Includes a separation motor. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAFairingsApolloPlate375m
Title: Big Gemini Decoupler [260"]
Description: This 260" decoupler is for S-IVB sized payloads like Big Gemini.

Name: FASAFairingsCone1m
Title: Payload Launch Fairing Expanded Base [Medium]
Description: A medium expanded payload launch fairing base for all your fairing needs.

Name: FASAFairingsCone3m
Title: Payload Launch Fairing Expanded Base [Large]
Description: A large expanded payload launch fairing base for all your fairing needs.

Name: FASAFairingsPlate1m
Title: Payload Launch Fairing Base [Small]
Description: A small payload launch fairing base for all your fairing needs.

Name: FASAFairingsPlate2m
Title: Payload Launch Fairing Base [Medium]
Description: A medium payload launch fairing base for all your fairing needs.

Name: FASAFairingsPlate375m
Title: Payload Launch Fairing Base [Large]
Description: A large payload launch fairing base for all your fairing needs.

Name: FASAFairingWall05m
Title: Fairing Wall Half [Small-Short]
Description: A small wall half, short length, for all your fairing needs.

Name: FASAFairingWall05m_agena
Title: Agena Bottom Fairing
Description: Place 2 on bottom area of agena above engine to cover flight pack.

Name: FASAGemini4X800Mini
Title: XLR11
Description: While it doesn't look a thing like it, this model represents the Reaction Motors XLR11, the first liquid fueled rocket engine designed for airplanes. Powered the X-1. Diameter: [0.46 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiAntenna
Title: Gemini Antenna
Description: This antenna is meant to be mounted on the Gemini rendezvous and recovery section.

Name: FASAGeminiBigG
Title: Big Gemini Passenger Compartment
Description: This is the lower half of the Big Gemini re-entry module, the passenger compartment.  This module gives the Big G a max 9 person crew capacity with additional cargo space.

Name: FASAGeminiBigGDec
Title: Big Gemini Decoupler
Description: A lighter decoupler for Big G.

Name: FASAGeminiBigGDock
Title: Big Gemini Service Module
Description: The service module and cargo storage for the Big Gemini spacecraft. Decouples before re-entry burn.

Name: FASAGeminiBigGDockExt
Title: Big Gemini Docking Ring
Description: Extendible docking ring for the Big G science lab.

Name: FASAGeminiBigGWhite
Title: Big Gemini Passenger Compartment - White
Description: This is the lower half of the Big Gemini re-entry module, the passenger compartment.  This version is made of new lightweight materials and painted white for rescue operations.  It has less cargo space but can support up to 12 person crew, including the flight compartment.

Name: FASAGeminiDecDark125
Title: FASA Dark Decoupler [Small]
Description: A small sized dark decoupler for all your decoupling needs.

Name: FASAGeminiDecDark125_Atlas
Title: Mercury - Atlas Spacecraft Adapter
Description: Spacecraft adapter for the Mercury - Atlas Launch Vehicle.

Name: FASAGeminiDecDark125_Redstone
Title: Mercury - Redstone Spacecraft Adapter
Description: Spacecraft adapter coupler for Mercury - Redstone Launch Vehicle

Name: FASAGeminiDecDark25
Title: FASA Dark Decoupler [Medium]
Description: A medium sized dark decoupler for all your decoupling needs.

Name: FASAGeminiDecDark25_Titan3m
Title: Titan Decoupler [120"]
Description: Decoupler for Titan II/III/IV Series rockets and other 120" Parts

Name: FASAGeminiDecDark375
Title: FASA Dark Decoupler [Large]
Description: A large sized dark decoupler for all your decoupling needs.

Name: FASAGeminiEngFuelDescent
Title: FASA Advanced Gemini Descent Pack
Description: This pack contains an engine and more fuel for a Gemini based lander. Attach this as a descent stage to the Gemini for landings. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiEngineFuel2
Title: FASA Advanced Gemini Equipment Section
Description: This equipment section models the thrusters as an engine, rather than as RCS. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiLegsX1
Title: FASA Advanced Gemini Landing Leg
Description: Need something to put a foot down, attach some of these and you won't have to crumple that cool spaceship.

Name: FASAGeminiLegsX1White
Title: FASA Advanced Gemini Landing Leg
Description: Need something to put a foot down, attach some of these and you won't have to crumple that cool spaceship.

Name: FASAGeminiLES
Title: Big Gemini Launch Escape System (LES)
Description: A launch escape system for use with Big Gemini. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiLFECentarTwin
Title: AJ10-138
Description: This can be an upper stage / orbital taxi for various Titan III configurations. Uses 2x AJ10-138. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiLFT_TitanIV
Title: Titan IV Series Fuel Tank
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the lower stage in Titan IV series builds.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTBigGAdapt
Title: FASA Fuel Tank Adapter
Description: A 3:2 Ratio Adapter Fuel Tank (Missing entryCost field)

Name: FASAGeminiLFTCentar
Title: Centaur A/B/C/D/D1
Description: Tank and thrust structure for the Centaur A/B/C/D/D1 models. Add two RL10A series engines to complete the stage.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTCentarCSM
Title: FASA Fuel Tank
Description: A generic fuel tank.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTCentarCSM_D1T
Title: Centaur D-1T
Description: Tank and thrust structure for the Centaur D1T models. Used on the Titan III-E. Add one or two RL10A series engines to complete the stage.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTCentarCSM_D2
Title: Centaur D2
Description: Tank and thrust structure for the Centaur II and IIAS models. Used on the Atlas II and IIIA. Add one or two RL10A series engines to complete the stage. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: FASAGeminiLFTCentarCSM_D5
Title: Centaur D3
Description: Tank and thrust structure for the Centaur III used on the Atlas V. Add one or two RL10A series engines to complete the stage.  Includes integrated avionics for the full Atlas V launch vehicle. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: FASAGeminiLFTCentarCSM_T
Title: Centaur T
Description: 4.32m Tank and thrust structure for the Centaur T used on the Titan IV. Add a single RL10A series engines to complete the stage. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: FASAGeminiLFTExtSmH2O2
Title: External Tank (Orange)
Description: A small external tank, painted orange.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTExtSmMono
Title: External Tank (White)
Description: A small external tank, painted white.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTLong
Title: Titan II Series Fuel Tank
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the lower stage in both Titan II ICBM and Titan II Gemini Launch Vehicle builds.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTLonger
Title: Titan 3 Series Fuel Tank
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the lower stage in Titan 3BS/34D series builds.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTLongIF
Title: Titan 23G/3 Series Fuel Tank
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the lower stage in Titan 23G and Titan 3A/B/C/D/E series builds

Name: FASAGeminiLFTMed
Title: Titan II Upper Stage Fuel Tank
Description: This propellant tank represents the tank used on the Titan II ICBM.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTMedWhite
Title: Titan II/III/IV Series Upper Stage Fuel Tank
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the upper stage in Titan 23G, Titan III series, and Titan IV series builds. Also includes a radio guidance module.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTShort
Title: FASA Fuel Tank
Description: A generic fuel tank.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTShortWhite
Title: FASA Fuel Tank
Description: A generic fuel tank.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTTitan1
Title: Titan 1 Series Fuel Tank
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the lower stage in Titan 1 series builds.

Name: FASAGeminiLFTTriSm
Title: External Tri-X Tank
Description: A small external tank pack.

Name: FASAGeminiLR87Twin
Title: LR87 Booster
Description: Used in the first stage of the Titan rocket family, the LR87 is composed of two engines with separate turbomachinery integrated into one unit. The version used on Titan I burned kerosene and liquid oxygen, while Titan II through Titan IV burned storable propellants. A modified version burning liquid hydrogen was developed for the upper stages of Saturn V and Saturn IB, but the J-2 was selected instead. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiLR91
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiLR91Mini
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiMiniSRB
Title: Gemini Retro Solid Rocket Motor
Description: Nice tiny solid rocket motor, designed to work with others and bring Gemini safely home again. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGeminiMOLEquip
Title: Manned Orbital Lab (MOL) Cargo Bay
Description: This equipment module is a part of the Manned Orbital Laboratory. Contains storage space for equipment, fuel tanks and small probes.

Name: FASAGeminiMOLEquip1m
Title: Gemini MOL-S Equipment Module 1.25m
Description: The MOL-S is a tiny service module for all your science support needs.  It contains storage space for equipment, fuel tanks, or tiny probes and keeps it nice and cool. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASAGeminiMOLEquipCap
Title: Manned Orbital Lab (MOL) Cargo Bay - Cap
Description: This cap goes on either end of MOL Equipment Module stack to complete the module.

Name: FASAGeminiMOLEquipStack
Title: Manned Orbital Lab (MOL) Cargo Bay - Stack
Description: This is a stackable version of the MOL Equipment Module that allows for a larger storage bay.

Name: FASAGeminiMOLSci
Title: Manned Orbital Lab (MOL) Science Module
Description: Planned crewed orbiting laboratory for the US Air Force (with secret orbital photographic reconaissance mission).

Name: FASAGeminiNoseCone2
Title: Gemini Rendezvous and Recovery Section Fairing
Description: This section contains all the necessary equipment for rendezvous and docking with the Agena Target Vehicle. After re-entry jettison this section to deploy the drogue parachute, after which the main parachute can then be deployed as well.

Name: FASAGeminiNoseCone2Aero
Title: Big Gemini Aerodynamic Nose Fairing
Description: Since the rendezvous electronics are not needed with Big Gemini this recovery section is a bit more aerodynamic than before. Jettison this before deploying the parachutes.

Name: FASAGeminiNoseCone2Cap
Title: Gemini Nose Fairing
Description: A nose fairing to protect the fragile equipment contained in the rendezvous and recovery section during launch.

Name: FASAGeminiNoseCone2White
Title: Gemini Rendezvous and Recovery Section Fairing
Description: This section contains all the necessary equipment for rendezvous and docking with the Agena Target Vehicle. After re-entry this section is jettisoned with deployment of the drogue parachute, after which the main parachute can then be deployed. Made of new lightweight material and painted white to match the white rescue Gemini pod.

Name: FASAGeminiParachute2
Title: Gemini Recovery Main Parachute
Description: The Gemini recovery main parachute. Put this on top of the RCS Control section.  May be attached radially.

Name: FASAGeminiParachute2D
Title: Gemini Recovery Drogue Parachute
Description: The Gemini recovery drogue parachute. Put this on top of the main parachute.  May be attached radially.

Name: FASAGeminiPod2
Title: Gemini Cabin
Description: The Gemini cabin.  Contains two astronauts.

Name: FASAGeminiPod2RCS
Title: Gemini Re-entry Control System
Description: This section contains fuel and thrusters to provide Gemini 3 axis attitude control after detaching the adapter section. RCS O/F Ratio 1.3:1.

Name: FASAGeminiPod2RCSWhite
Title: Gemini Re-entry Control System - White
Description: This section contains fuel and thrusters to provide Gemini 3 axis attitude control after detaching the adapter section. Made of new lightweight material and painted white to match the white rescue Gemini pod. RCS O/F Ratio 1.3:1.

Name: FASAGeminiPod2White
Title: Gemini Cabin - White
Description: The Gemini cabin.  Contains two astronauts.  This one is made of new lightweight material and painted white to increase efficiency for rescue operations.

Name: FASAGeminiPodLight
Title: Gemini Light Pod
Description: Can't see, put one of these on. Problem solved.

Name: FASAGeminiROTitanIIGLVUpper
Title: Titan II GLV Upper Stage Fuel Tank
Description: This propellant tank represents the tank used on the Titan II Gemini Launch Vehicle. It provides 8 more seconds of burn time via an extra ton of propellant.

Name: FASAGeminiSasRcs
Title: FASA Gemini RCS Section
Description: This IMAGINARY Gemini RCS Section houses RCS for translation up/down/left/right/aft. Modelled with the 2 backwards firing thrusters as well. RCS O/F Ratio 1.3:1.

Name: FASAGeminiSciRadmeter
Title: Mini Goo Radiometer
Description: Houses a Mini Goo sample and exposes it to different types of radiation. Also extremely fragile!

Name: FASAGeminiUtilityPack
Title: Gemini Adapter Equipment Section
Description: The Gemini Adapter Equipment Section.  It contains O2 and H2 for fuel cell consumption and life support.  It also contains fuel for manoeuvring and attitude control thrusters.  This is the configuration as found on Gemini 10+. RCS O/F Ratio 1.3:1.

Name: FASAGeminiUtilitySasRcs
Title: Gemini Adapter Retrograde Section
Description: The Gemini Adapter Retrograde Section. Contains the retrograde engines to de-orbit Gemini. Also houses RCS for translation up/down/left/right/aft. Modelled with the 2 backwards firing thrusters as well. RCS O/F Ratio 1.3:1.  Provides approximately 106dV for re-entry burn. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGerminiSRB175
Title: UA1205 SRM
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGerminiSRB175_5Seg
Title: UA1204 SRM
Description: Earliest UA120 series booster designed. Designed for Titan booster augmentation for DynaSoar. Candidate for various Saturn INT studies. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGerminiSRB175_7Seg
Title: UA1206 SRM
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan 34D. Burn time 114s. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGerminiSRB175White
Title: UA1205 SRM
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. Painted white. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAGerminiSRBInlineSep
Title: In-Line Separation Motor
Description: A in-line separation motor for the Titan III Solid rocket boosters. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAICBMMIRV
Title: W53 Warhead - 9MT
Description: The Titan II ICBM W53 Warhead.  Installed as a single warhead atop the Guidance Package.

Name: FASAICBMNosecone
Title: Mark 6 Re-Entry Vehicle Fairing
Description: This fairing protects the RVs from the heat of ascent.

Name: FASAICBMProbe
Title: Titan II ICBM Guidance Package
Description: Delco Universal Space Guidance System (USGS).  Carousel IV IMU.  Magic 352 Computer.

Name: FASAICBMSAS
Title: Titan II Mk6 Re-Entry Vehicle Base
Description: This part is both the interface from the Titan II to the Mk6 Re-Entry Vehicle and the base of the Mk6 Re-Entry Vehicle itself.  It is modelled as simply the re-entry vehicle.

Name: FASAlaunchClamp125
Title: Redstone and Juno I Launch Clamp
Description: This clamp attaches to the bottom of the A-7 Rocket Engine used in the Redstone-Mercury and Juno I launch vehicles.

Name: FASAlaunchClamp25
Title: Generic Launch Clamp
Description: A launch clamp that is resizable to match whatever you need.

Name: FASAlaunchClampApollo
Title: FASA Apollo Launch Clamp
Description: Similar to the clamps that held the Saturn V down while the engines spooled up. The clamp had a special hood it retracted into. It protect the clamps from rocket exhaust so they could be reused for multiple launches.

Name: FASAlaunchClampAtlas
Title: FASA Atlas Launch Clamp
Description: The "Atlas Clamp" attaches to the sides of rockets to help stop the launch wiggles. This clamp works just like the stock launch clamps except they do not provide electricity.

Name: FASAlaunchTower
Title: FASA Launch Tower
Description: This launch tower lets you load Kerbals from the tower to your spacecraft.  Load it up with Kerbals from the astronaut complex and right click on the doors at the top or bottom to EVA.

Name: FASALM_Antenna
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Antennas
Description: Just antennas, good for communicating. Place on top of the ascent stage.

Name: FASALM_AscentEngine
Title: Lunar Module Ascent Engine
Description: Pressure-fed engine used for the ascent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Diameter: [0.86 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASALM_AscentStage
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Ascent Module
Description: Apollo Ascent Module. Contains two astronauts.

Name: FASALM_DecouplerRing
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Stage Separator
Description: This part splits the Ascent Module and Descent Module into two.  Hope you remembered everything, you won't be going back this trip.

Name: FASALM_DescentEngine
Title: Lunar Module Descent Engine
Description: Deeply throttleable pressure-fed vacuum engine used for the descent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Uses storable propellants which are not subject to boiloff, but are far less efficient than hydrolox or even kerolox. The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASALM_DescentStage
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Descent Module
Description: This part contains fuel for landing, experiments, and importantly legs to set down softly.

Name: FASALM_DockingCone
Title: Apollo Docking Mechanism Drogue
Description: Apollo Lunar Module Docking Drogue. Will only works with the Apollo Command Module Probe.

Name: FASALM_DockingConern
Title: Skylab Docking Mechanism Drogue
Description: Skylab Docking Drogue. Will only works with the Apollo Command Module Probe. Place two on the station.

Name: FASALM_LandingLegs
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Leg
Description: A landing leg with contact sensor.

Name: FASALM_LandingLegsSA
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Leg - Surface Attach
Description: A surface attachable LEM landing leg with contact sensor.

Name: FASALM_LandingLegStaircase
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Leg - Ladder
Description: The landing leg with ladder.

Name: FASALM_OutputPlace
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Mobility Enhancer
Description: A walkway to get from the door to the ladder.

Name: FASALM_RCS
Title: Apollo Lunar Module RCS Quad Pod
Description: A RCS thruster pod, set at 45 degree angles to make it more useful. RCS O/F Ratio 1.6:1.

Name: FASALM_StairCase
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Staircase
Description: A generic ladder for any need.

Name: FASAMercruyCap2
Title: Mercury Nose Fairing
Description: This nose fairing protects the parachute during flight.

Name: FASAMercuryAtlasEng
Title: LR105 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator sustainer engine used in the Atlas launch vehicle. It, like the Atlas's booster engines (LR89s) are lit on the ground, but after a bit over 2 minutes' flight the boosters are dropped and the Atlas core continues to orbit under the power of the sustainer engine (and the verniers for roll control and final adjustment). The final configuration of the LR105 (like the LR89) uses RS-27 components for increased performance. As a sustainer engine, the LR105 has relatively poor sea level specific impulse compared to most boosters, but somewhat better vacuum specific impulse--though the difference in both is nowhere near as pronounced as when comparing a booster to an upper stage engine. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAMercuryAtlasEngBooster
Title: LR89 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator engine that served as booster for Atlas. Late model LR89s were upgraded with RS-27 components for higher efficiency. Very similar to LR79 (this was the pure-booster variant). Diameter: [1.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAMercuryAtlasLFTLong
Title: Atlas SLV-3 Fuel Tank
Description: The fuel tank for the Atlas SLV-3 launcher. Used with the Gemini Agena Target Vehicle.

Name: FASAMercuryAtlasVernierEngine
Title: LR101 Series
Description: Pump or pressure-fed kerolox vernier engine. Used for attitude control and final velocity adjustment in the MA-x system (2x LR89 + LR105 + 2x LR101) on Atlas, and MB-x system (LR79 or RS-27 + 2xLR101) on Thor-Able / Thor-Agena / Thor-Delta / Delta. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAMercuryDec
Title: Mercury Retro Strap / Decoupler
Description: Straps to hold retro pack to heatshield (place on heatshield, then add retro pack). Decouple before re-entry.

Name: FASAMercuryFairing
Title: Atlas Fairing Decoupler
Description: Part of the MA-2/3/5 Propulsion Unit, this is a decoupler/fairing for the booster engines of Atlas. Place this on top of the main engines, then add the boosters.

Name: FASAMercuryLFTShortLarge
Title: FASA Fuel Tank
Description: A generic fuel tank.

Name: FASAMercuryMiniSRB
Title: Mercury Posigrade Solid Rocket Motor
Description: A tiny solid rocket motor, designed to separate Mercury spacecraft from its booster. Mount in a set of three to the Mercury retropack and stage along with the Atlas or Redstone decoupler. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASAMercuryPod
Title: Mercury Re-entry Module
Description: The Mercury re-entry module.  Contains one astronaut.  Built in RCS thrusters.

Name: FASAMercuryPodRCS
Title: Mercury RCS Roll Thruster Pack
Description: Mercury roll control thrusters.  Put 1 pack on right side of spacecraft at height of lowest part of hatch.

Name: FASAMercuryRedstoneFin
Title: A-7 Fin / Thrust Vane
Description: The Redstone / Jupiter-C / Juno engine could not gimbal.  Instead TVC was obtained by use of carbon thrust vanes. Apply in 4x symmetry to A7 engine unit.

Name: FASAPioneerAnt
Title: Pioneer Probe Antenna
Description: Antenna for the Pioneer probe. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASAPioneerLFE
Title: Pioneer Mono Engine
Description: A mini mono engine for all your rocket needs. Works great as a pod de-orbit engine too... Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASAPioneerProbe
Title: Pioneer Probe Core
Description: Pioneer contains a material science bay and its own solar panels.  The Pioneer program ( Pioneer 6,7,8, and 9)formed a series of solar orbiting satellites designed to gather the first detailed information of solar wind, magnetic field and cosmic rays in interplanetary space. They formed the humanities first solar weather network. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASAProbeCamera
Title: Probe Camera
Description: This camera lets you to make remote crew reports from probes. Also includes a HD camera for scouting landing sights.

Name: FASAProbeDecoupler
Title: Probe Decoupler
Description: A probe sized radial decoupler, like most other decouplers, is equipped with a small explosive charge that will sever the structural linkage between itself and whatever it's connected to. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASAProbeGeigerCounter
Title: Geiger Counter
Description: This Geiger counter measures gamma rays and stores that data for scientific study.

Name: FASAProbeLaser
Title: Laser Mass Spectrometer
Description: You must have "Surface Sample" unlocked to use this part! This small laser lets probes remotely analyse soil samples.

Name: FASAProbeParachute
Title: Mercury Parachute Mini
Description: The Mini Parachute is a lot weaker than the standard one and useless for anything heavier than a probe core. DO NOT USE ON LIVE SUBJECTS!!!!

Name: FASASaturnSLA
Title: Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter - Base
Description: This part is the Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter base used to cover the Lunar Module during ascent.  It is fitted with two separate decouplers.  One separates the CSM through staging.  The other separates the LEM manually.  No extra decoupler is needed.

Name: FASASaturnSLA_long
Title: Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter - Long Base
Description: This part is the Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter base used to cover the Lunar Module during ascent.  It is fitted with two separate decouplers.  One separates the CSM through staging.  The other separates the LEM manually.  No extra decoupler is needed.  This is a longer (3m) version to negate the collider issue with the LEM and IU.

Name: FASASaturnSLA_med
Title: Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter - Med Base
Description: This part is the Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter base used to cover the Lunar Module during ascent.  It is fitted with two separate decouplers.  One separates the CSM through staging.  The other separates the LEM manually.  No extra decoupler is needed.  This is a slightly longer (2.6m) version to partially negate the collider issue with the LEM and IU while still maintaining the same basic height of the SLA.

Name: FASASaturnUllage
Title: S-II Ullage Rocket
Description: Attaches to the upper part of the S-II interstage, in sets of 4 to 8. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FASASolarLarge
Title: Station Solar Panel Large
Description: A large unfolding station solar panel for your stations electrical needs. It does not track the sun! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASASolarMed
Title: Station Solar Panel Medium
Description: A medium unfolding station solar panel for your stations electrical needs. Also it tracks the sun. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FASASolarMini
Title: FASA Solar Panel
Description: A nice small 0.05m^2 solar panel for small parts.

Name: FASAStrF1Fairing
Title: Saturn V Engine Fairing
Description: Fairing cone designed to shield the powerful F-1 engines.

Name: FASAStrFairing3m4x
Title: Spacecraft Lunar Module Adapter - Fairing
Description: This part, placed in a set of 4 covers the Apollo Lunar Module during ascent.

Name: FASAStrS1BWing
Title: Saturn S-IB Fin
Description: A fin to help stabilize the Saturn IB.

Name: FASATitanLR91Dec
Title: LR91 Decoupler
Description: Place this part under the LR91 for staging.

Name: FASAUmbilicalTower
Title: FASA Umbilical Tower
Description: This umbilical tower functions as a launch clamp and fuel pump for liquid fuel, oxidizer and mono-propellent. It also Provides electricity. Right click on the tower to start the fuel flow.

Name: Focke-Wulf?Bearcat?Cockpit
Title: FW-190 Cockpit
Description: Take to the skies! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: foldingRadLarge
Title: EATCS Retractable Radiator (Large)
Description: A large retractable External Active Thermal Control System radiator.

Name: foldingRadMed
Title: EATCS Retractable Radiator (Medium)
Description: A medium retractable External Active Thermal Control System radiator.

Name: foldingRadSmall
Title: EATCS Retractable Radiator (Small)
Description: A small retractable External Active Thermal Control System radiator.

Name: FREFRE1
Title: FRE-1
Description: The Firefly Research Engine 1 (FRE-1) is an upper stage engine developped by Firefly, and intended to be used with the Firefly Alpha launch vehicle. It features a low production cost along a simple and efficient pressure-fed system. The Firefly engines will burn RP1 on the first flights, but they will be upgraded to burn Methane and therefore improve their efficiency. [1.3m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREFRE2
Title: FRE-2
Description: The Firefly Research Engine 2 (FRE-2) is a lower stage aerospike-clustered engine developped by Firefly, and intended to be used with the Firefly Alpha launch vehicle. Using an aerospike noozle surrounded by twelve combustion chambers, the FRE-2 is efficient at a wide range of altitude. The Firefly engines will burn RP1 on the first flights, but they will be upgraded to burn Methane and therefore improve their efficiency. [1.85m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FRELE5
Title: LE-5 Series
Description: Advanced upper stage hydrolox japanese engines developped by Mitsubishi. The LE-5 powers the H-II launch vehicle second stage. [1.5m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FRELE7
Title: LE-7 Series
Description: 1990s medium TWR, atmospheric and vacuum use. Fuel-rich staged combustion engines used on the core stage of H-II series launchers. The original LE-7 was replaced by the LE-7A, which sacrificed some performance in favor of reduced cost and better reliability. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREP80
Title: P80
Description: The P80 is an high-performance European Solid Rocket Motor. It powers the first stage of the Vega launch vehicle and may be upgraded to an heavier and more powerful version in order to boost Ariane 6. The P80 SRM is currently the largest and most powerfull single segment solid rocket motor. Burn time ~110s.[3m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FRERD843
Title: RD-843
Description: The RD-843 is a Ukrainian single nozzle liquid propellant rocket engine powering Vega fourth stage (AVUM). Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FRERUTHERFORD
Title: Rutherford
Description: Rocket Labs flagship engine, the 4,900lbf Rutherford, is an electrical turbo-pumped LOX/RP-1 engine specifically designed for the Electron Launch Vehicle. [0.3m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FRERUTHERFORDVAC
Title: Rutherford Vacuum
Description: The Rutherford engine with an extended nozzle for better vacuum performance. [0.6m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREVIKINGEARLY
Title: Viking (2/2B)
Description: Early Viking engines used on Ariane 1, 2 and 3. Thanks to the magic of hypergolic propellant, Vikings engines were able to achieve a substainable amount of thrust at all altitude. Includes configs for Viking 2 and 2B. [1.5m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREVIKINGLOWER
Title: Viking (5B/5C/6)
Description: Later Viking engines used on Ariane 4. Includes configs for Viking 5B, 5C and 6 (liquid fuel booster). [1.5m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREVIKINGUPPER
Title: Viking (4/4B)
Description: Upper stage Viking engine used on Ariane 1 and 4 as well as on Indian Lauch Vehicles GSLV and PSLV. Includes configs for Viking 4, 4B, Vikas 2, 2B and X. [1.8m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREZEFIRO23
Title: Zefiro 23
Description: The Zephiro 23 is an high performance upper stage solid rocket motor. It powers Vega's second stage. Burn time ~77s. [1.9m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FREZEFIRO9
Title: Zefiro 9
Description: The Zephiro 9 is an high performance upper stage solid rocket motor. It powers Vega's third stage. Burn time ~120s. [1.9m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: FSoblongToRoundAdapter
Title: FS1ORA Oblong to Round Adapter
Description: Easily mix and match regular round parts with oblong parts with this stylish adapter. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSoblongToSmallAdapter
Title: FS1OSA Oblong to Small Adapter
Description: Easily mix and match regular round 0.625m parts and oblong parts with this stylish adapter. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSoxidizerTank
Title: FS3OT Oxidizer Tank
Description: When you need just a little bit of Oxidizer, without all that nasty liquid fuel it usually comes bundled with, this is for you! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSPROpeller
Title: FS1PRO Customizable Propeller engine
Description: A totally customizable propeller engine. Tweak the engine size and power, the number of blades and their length. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSPROpellerElectric
Title: FS1PRE Customizable Electric Propeller engine
Description: A totally customizable electric propeller engine. Tweak the engine size and power, the number of blades and their length. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Description: 500 horsepower, consumes about 400 EC/s

Name: FSswampEngine
Title: Swamp Propeller
Description: 600 HP piston engine and low-speed propeller

Name: FStailBoom
Title: FS2TB Tail Boom
Description: The thing that makes your tail rotor get some distance from the rest of your helicopter. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FStailWing
Title: FS1TW2 Tail Wing
Description: This small tail wing will let you yaw and pitch as smooth as butter. We wish buttery smoothness was actually useful, instead of all this lift and drag stuff. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FStailWingLarge
Title: FS1TW3 Large Tail Wing
Description: This large tail wing will let you yaw and pitch as smooth as butter. We wish buttery smoothness was actually useful, instead of all this lift and drag stuff. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: fstrimgadget
Title: FS3TA Trim Adjustment Gadget

Name: FSturboProp

Description: Modern turboprop, 675 HP at takeoff (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSVTOLengine
Title: Bell Boeing V-22 VTOL Engine&Rotor 1/2
Description: a smaller V-22 Osprey, max take-off is 7 tons per engine. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSVTOLengineLarge
Title: Bell Boeing V-22 VTOL Engine&Rotor
Description: V-22 Osprey, max take-off is 14 tons per engine. (Missing entryCost field) (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FSwinglet
Title: FS1TW1 Tail Winglet
Description: This thing goes on the back of your plane so you can pitch it. If that's the sort of thing you care about. No pressure. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: FuelCell
Title: Fuel Cell
Description: A 750W fuel cell. Consumes about 41 liters of LH2 and 29 liters of LOX per week. These figures were determined by ground tests and include boil-off. The actual hydrogen boil-off rate may be considerably higher depending on the situation and the surface to volume ratio of your storage tanks.

Name: FuelCellArray
Title: Fuel Cell Array
Description: A 4.5kW fuel cell. Consumes about 245 liters of LH2 and 175 liters of LOX per week. These figures were determined by ground tests and include boil-off. The actual hydrogen boil-off rate may be considerably higher depending on the situation and the surface to volume ratio of your storage tanks.

Name: fuelLine
Title: FTX-2 External Fuel Duct
Description: New breakthroughs at FLOOYD Dynamics have made the FTX Fuel Duct a reality. Altough criticized by some as being no more than 'a sewage pipe painted yellow', most agree that the yellow is a relatively nice color, and that fuel lines are indeed able to pump fuel from side-mounted fuel tanks. After the recall of the FTX-1 series, All FTX-2 lines have arrows painted on to indicate the fuel flow direction, so engineers can tell which way around they are supposed to go.

Name: fuelTank
Title: FL-T400 Fuel Tank
Description: The FL series was received as a substantial upgrade over previous fuel containers used in the Space Program, generally due to its ability to keep the fuel unexploded more often than not. Fuel tanks are useless if there isn't a Liquid Engine attached under it. They can also be stacked with other fuel tanks to increase the amount of fuel for the engine below.

Name: fuelTank_long
Title: FL-T800 Fuel Tank
Description: A stretched variant of the FL-T400, the FL-T800 holds twice the fuel in a slightly stronger container. The black stripes that were along the side made the rocket go faster, so fast in fact, that they wore off.

Name: fuelTank1-2
Title: Rockomax X200-32 Fuel Tank
Description: Developed after one J. Kerman complained that the fuel tanks available were 'way too small', the X200-32 holds a generous amount of fuel, for all your... fueling needs or something like that. Shut up, Rockomax hires rocket scientists, not writers.

Name: fuelTank1-5
Title: Rockomax X200-48 Fuel Tank
Description: The Oscar-B Fuel Tank from Probodobodyne is a compact fuel container for small space probes, or a backup tank for other small spacecraft. Do not wash in cold water, or feed after midnight.

Name: fuelTank2-2
Title: Rockomax X200-16 Fuel Tank
Description: After many, many studies, Rockomax engineers found that the space program does indeed have a use for a tank half the size of the X200-32. No refunds.

Name: fuelTank3-2
Title: Rockomax Jumbo-64 Fuel Tank
Description: The largest tank available from Rockomax, the Jumbo-64 holds a vast amount of fuel in a large metal tube. After deciding that the tank was too light, Rockomax decided to paint the Jumbo-64, bringing its appearance in-line with the rest of its fuel tanks.

Name: fuelTank4-2
Title: Rockomax X200-8 Fuel Tank
Description: A compact fuel tank, designed for small upper stages and landers. Rockomax takes no responsibility for the Dawton Kerman Aboveground Pool Company stickers on the inside because it totally is not a swimming pool frame we stole from their back lot.

Name: fuelTank7k
Title: AIES K7 Fuel Tank
Description: A large tank with lots of fuel. Features "1mm Steel Plate" to protect it from environmental hazards. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: fuelTanklunderl
Title: AIES Lunder-L Fuel Tank
Description: This tank (actually a set of tanks) was created to meet the requirements of lunar and interplanetary missions. It is lightweight and efficient. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: fuelTankmr1
Title: AIES MR1 vr2 Fuel Tank
Description: The half sized cousin of the K7 tank. Thickness of the protective steel plate was increased to astonishing 1.4mm! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: fuelTankSmall
Title: FL-T200 Fuel Tank
Description: The T200 tank had some difficulty being accepted in the spacecraft engineering world, because most rocket builders had trouble overcoming their urges to squee at the "cute little fuel tank". This initial reaction was only put aside when the amount of fiery explosions in assembly areas became so high, strict guidelines were put in place to prohibit "teasing the fuel containers". The T200 Tank now is widely used in several space programs and does a remarkably good job, if assembled politely.

Name: fuelTankSmallFlat
Title: FL-T100 Fuel Tank
Description: The T100 is a miniature fuel tank made to be even more adorable than its bigger brother, the T200. Handle stoically and with care.

Name: fuelTanksul
Title: AIES SUL-V1 Fuel Tank
Description: A little cousin to the Superior-V3 continues the 'strategic' line of fuel tank design. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: fuelTanksuperior3
Title: AIES Superior-V3 Fuel Tank
Description: This enhanced version of "Superior-R2" gave birth to the new 'strategic' line of fuel tank designs. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: galaxvr2
Title: Aestus Vacuum Engine
Description: Upper stage engine of the Ariane 5ES. Burns hypergolic propellants. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: galileo_aprobe
Title: Galileo Atmospheric Probe
Description: This is the atmospheric probe for Galileo spacecraft. Detach this before reaching Jool.

Name: galileo_aprobe_bot
Title: Galileo Atmospheric Probe Bottom
Description: Bottom portion of the Galileo atmospheric probe. Attach this under the main body.

Name: galileo_hs_bot
Title: Galileo Atmospheric Probe Heatshield Bottom
Description: Bottom part of the 3 heatshield pieces for Galileo probe.

Name: galileo_hs_mid
Title: Galileo Atmospheric Probe Heatshield Middle
Description: Middle part of the 3 heatshield pieces for Galileo probe.

Name: galileo_hs_top
Title: Galileo Atmospheric Probe Heatshield Top
Description: Top part of the 3 heatshield pieces for Galileo probe.

Name: galileo_mb
Title: Galileo Spacecraft
Description: Galileo probe main body. Attach dish to top and atmospheric probe to bottom. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: galileo_probe_hs_parachute
Title: Galileo Probe Heatshield Parachute
Description: Parachute for Galileo atmospheric probe heatshield. Attach to top of heatshield.

Name: galileo_probe_parachute
Title: Galileo Probe Parachute
Description: Parachute for Galileo atmospheric probe. Attach to top of probe.

Name: gasspectrometer-01
Title: AIReS Atmospheric Sounder
Description: Use this advanced spectrographic sounder to retrieve the concentrations of various noble gases from planetary atmospheres. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: GasTurbineGenerator

Description: While it generates an insignificant amount of thrust, the gas turbine generator generates large amounts of electricity. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: GasTurbineGenerator2
Title: GTG-250 Gas Turbine Generator
Description: While it generates an insignificant amount of thrust, the gas turbine generator generates large amounts of electricity. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: gdish_actual
Title: Galileo Dish "Actual"
Description: Actual broken version of the galileo dish.

Name: gdish_intended

Description: Intended unbroken version of Galileo dish.

Name: GearFixed
Title: LY-01 Fixed Landing Gear
Description: Simple wheel-on-a-stick Landing Gear to bring your birds down safely. (That means your airplanes, LightYear Co. does not encourage attempting to attach landing gear to actual birds)

Name: GearFree
Title: LY-05 Steerable Landing Gear
Description: Simple wheel with steering actuation. It has become evident that aerodynamic control surfaces don't offer much control while slowly taxiing on the ground. Hopefully these wheels will reduce the number of low altitude low speed collisions with buildings. And Kerbals.

Name: GearLarge
Title: LY-99 Extra Large Landing Gear
Description: Heavy-duty retractable landing gear. With it's six large tires and sturdy assembly it's the gear of choice for heavy cargo planes and airliners.

Name: GearMedium
Title: LY-60 Large Landing Gear
Description: Heavy-duty retractable landing gear. With it's four large tires and sturdy assembly it's the gear of choice for heavy cargo planes and airliners.

Name: GearSmall
Title: LY-35 Medium Landing Gear
Description: High performance retractable landing gear. This bigger version features two large tires to support big and heavy planes. The longer assembly allows for improved ground clearance.

Name: GeminiNosecone1m
Title: Nose Fairing [Medium]
Description: A medium nose cone fairing for all your fairing needs.

Name: GeminiNosecone2m
Title: Nose Fairing [Large]
Description: A large nose cone fairing for all your fairing needs.

Name: GeminiNosecone625m
Title: Nose Fairing [Small]
Description: A small nose cone fairing for all your fairing needs.

Name: godLandingLeg
Title: AIES GODEX-1A Landing
Description: Guaranteed not to crack on the heavyweight crafts. Warranty - one day after purchase.

Name: godLandingLeg2
Title: AIES GODEX-1B Landing Strut
Description: The same as "GODEX-1A", the only difference is the color. It's all about variety!

Name: GooExperiment
Title: Biological Sample Capsule
Description: This is a capsule containing biological samples (fruit flies, fungus, perhaps even a mouse or two). While some observations of the sample may be transmitted, only by recovering the sample safely can the most information be gained about life's response to the given situation.

Name: grab-1
Title: GRAB 1
Description: United States reconnaissance satellite GRAB 1

Name: GrapplingDevice
Title: Advanced Grabbing Unit
Description: Kerbal Motion engineers have long struggled with the problem of how to extract dropped tools from complicated machinery. After observing an intern cleaning out his shoes by turning them upside and shaking them inside the lab, our team was hit with a stroke of inspiration! Why not turn the rocket parts upside down and shake them? The grabbing arm perfectly filled this niche, and is quite capable of lifting heavy machinery. It has since found other uses, besides delicate tool extraction operations. AKA "The Klaw!"

Name: Griffon101
Title: Rolls-Royce Griffon 101 piston engine
Description: Rolls Royce Griffon 101. Two stage three speed supercharger (only two stages modeled, so it overperforms 1-3km). Rated 2420HP at 1.5km, 2250HP at 4.4km, and 2050HP at 6.4km. 11ft 5-blade constant speed propeller.

Name: Griffon88
Title: Rolls-Royce Griffon 88 piston engine
Description: Rolls Royce Griffon 88. 2350HP sea level with a two stage two speed supercharger maintaining 2100HP to 5km.

Name: GuidanceEarly1m
Title: Guidance Unit (Early), 1m
Description: Small (3ft / 1m) early avionics ring for Vanguard/Redstone/Juno/R-5 class rockets. Provides control for about 6 minutes. This avionics unit allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: GuidanceEarly2m
Title: Guidance Unit (Early), 2m
Description: Medium (6.5ft / 2m) early avionics ring for Thor/Atlas class rockets. Provides control for 9 minutes. This avionics unit allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: GuidanceEarly3m
Title: Guidance Unit (Early), 3m
Description: Large (10ft / 3m) early avionics ring for R-7 class rockets. Provides control for 9 minutes. This avionics unit allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: GuidanceLate1m
Title: Guidance Unit, 1m
Description: Small (3ft / 1m) advanced avionics ring. This avionics unit allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: GuidanceStart1m
Title: Guidance Unit (Starting), 1m
Description: Earliest control system for rocketry. Lasts approximately 3 minutes. Quickly made obsolete by advances in electronics. This avionics unit allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: HA3SLCenterDecoupler

Name: HA3SLPayloadDecoupler

Description: Payload adapter for Zenit. Includes nodes for Procedural Fairings

Description: Keeps the shaft slick and quick

Name: HA3SLPayloadFairingLong

Name: HA3SLRD120
Title: RD-120
Description: High altitude engine used in the Zenit second stage. First production Russian engine to be test fired in the United States (3 test burns were made).

Name: HA3SLRD171
Title: RD-171
Description: The RD-170 and RD-171 engines consisted of 4 chambers, 1 turbo-pump and 2 gas generators were developed simultaneously, the difference being one-plane gimballing in the RD-170 used in the Energia launch vehicle strap-ons versus two-plane gimablling in the RD-171 used on the first stage of the Zenit launch vehicle. The RD-171 can be gimballed using bellows to 6 degrees normally but it has reached 8-10 degrees in tests. The chamber conditions are 300 atmosphere pressure and at a 400 degrees C oxygen-rich gas mixture - very dangerous conditions. The RD-170 was very hard to prove and many designers thought it couldn't be done. The first stage strap-ons were recovered under parachutes and returned to Baikonur for study. The engine was designed for 10 reuses but tests showed they could stand up to 20 burns.
COST NOTES: Used values from other RD-171 (RN's version)

Title: Communotron HG-55
Description: Mariner-style extendable high-gain antenna, suitable for missions to Venus and (with some care) Mars.

Name: HighGainAntenna5
Title: HG-5 Retractable Parabolic Antenna
Description: A retractable, short range parabolic antenna for high speed telecommunications.

Name: HiPAT
Title: R-4D HiPAT (445N)
Description: The HiPAT or High Performance Liquid Apogee Thruster. The HiPAT performs orbit-raising manoeuvres for many of the worlds communication satellite platforms, including the Astrium Eurostar 3000, Boeing Space Systems 702HP, MELCO DS-2000 and Loral LS-1300. The R-4D has also played a critical role in NASA missions such as Cassini's orbit insertion of Saturn. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Title: FW - Conic Fairing
Description: Made from the finest materials found in the fields around the Space Center. Conic version.

Name: hydrogen-10-1
Title: HI-530 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: The biggest cryogenic tank available from Argyle Hydroponics has a truly staggering volume, however, it's actually pretty light for the size. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-125-1
Title: Centi-3 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: The almost-new look of this tank is slightly suspicious, given that it was sent to the KSC new in the package. Uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-125-2
Title: Centi-2 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: The smallest stackable tank for storing cryogenic propellants isn't the most popular of tanks. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-25-1
Title: HI-M-21 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: The medium Argyle tank line is nothing special. In fact, it didn't even get an eye-catching name! However, it still uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-25-2
Title: HI-M-10 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: Middle of the road size, middle of the road capacity, middle of the road price, heck, even found in the middle of the road! Uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-25-3
Title: HI-M-5 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: Moderate diameter and a short height give the HI-M-5 an almost disappointingly low capacity. But! It uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank, so that's something. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-375-1
Title: Mondo-60 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: The Mondo line of hydrogen tanks from Argyle is, as the name would suggest, monstrous. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-375-2
Title: Mondo-30 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: Demand for a half-sized Mondo tank was high, so the Mondo-30 was created. It is slightly less high. Uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-375-3
Title: Mondo-15 Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: The smallest model in the Mondo line looks a little crumpled, but is perfectly serviceable. It also uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-radial-125-1
Title: HB-D7 Radial Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: Affectionately known as the 'happy birthday tank' among the KSC staff. Responsible for 57 injuries when an engineer attempted to use a filled article as a cake - complete with candles. Due to regressions in plumbing technology, you may need to run a fuel line from this tank to get its "fuel" potential. Uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-radial-25-1
Title: HB-8 Radial Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: A large liquid hydrogen tank. Not particularly solid, but critic reviews include the words "stunning", "enormous" and "leaky". Wait, was I supposed to say that? Due to regressions in plumbing technology, you may need to run a fuel line from this tank to get its "fuel" potential. Uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: hydrogen-radial-375-1
Title: HB-D7 Radial Cryogenic Fuel Tank
Description: This tank was conceived when Argyle's lead engineer accidentally doubled the radius on the blueprints of the HB-8. After several dozen were built and met with critcal acclaim, it was slated for mass production. Due to regressions in plumbing technology, you may need to run a fuel line from this tank to get its "fuel" potential. Uses insulation and cooling systems to stop cryogenic fuels like liquid hydrogen from escaping the tank. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ICPSAdapterx
Title: Delta IV DCSS Truss (5 Meters)
Description: The structural support truss for the 5 meter Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS) liquid Hydrogen and liquid Oxygen propellant tanks.

Name: ICPSAdapterx2
Title: Delta IV DCSS Truss (4 Meters)
Description: The structural support truss for the 4 meter Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS) liquid Hydrogen and liquid Oxygen propellant tanks.

Name: idaONE
Title: NASA International Docking Adapter
Description: The International Docking Adapter (IDA) is a spacecraft docking system adapter being developed to convert APAS-95 to the NASA Docking System (NDS)/ International Docking System Standard (IDSS).

Name: InflatableHAB
Title: IKU-03 Kerbal Safety Bubble
Description: One of the biggest crew storage solutions available to any space program, the IKU-03 is able to inflate to nearly double it's initial size, letting it hold a total of 10 kerbals comfortably. If it isn't inflated, however... let's just say that they'll have very little to no room to do anything.

Name: InflatableHeatShield
Title: Heat Shield (10m)
Description: Based on the design of a child's toy, this heat shield uses a set of inflatable rings covered with a thermal blanket to provide a generous 10 meter heat shield for reentry and deceleration, and the aerodynamic qualities of an untethered bouncy castle. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: inlineCmdPod
Title: PPD-1 Heavy Command Module
Description: This large command module is optimized for use with Kerlington's PPD series of products. Its seats 2 pilots and 4 passengers. No reaction wheels, but plenty of storage make it an excellent choice for large craft.

Name: InlineRCS
Title: Inline RCS block (138/223 N class)
Description: A generic inline RCS block. Use this for orientation on small capsules and probes.

Name: IntakeRadialLong
Title: Adjustable Ramp Intake (Radial)
Description: This intake addresses those sometimes absurd contraptions that SSTO engineers designed in an attempt to pump more and more air into their engines. Optimized for supersonic flight.

Name: Interceptor?Cockpit
Title: Gloster Meteor Cockpit
Description: Sometimes you need to install stuff on the nose too.

Name: investpod
Title: CubeSat Core
Description: Something so small you can throw it away and not realize it's potential.

Name: ionArgon-0625
Title: NASA 457M Hall Thruster [Test]
Description: Designed and tested as part of an initiative to produce higher thrust electric propulsion for manned missions, the NASA 457M sacrifices the much higher Isp of other thrusters for extra push.  Requires a lot more power, up to 72kW. NOTE: This engine is a lab test article, and has not flown.

Name: ionArgon-0625-2
Title: P5 Hall Thruster
Description: Developed jointly by the AFRL and PEPL, the P5 is a dual-stage hall thruster. This means it can more effectively lens the charged ions, giving you more bang for your space-buck!

Name: ionArgon-0625-3
Title: GW3 'Triplet' Nested-Channel Hall Thruster
Description: The most promising of the Hall thruster technologies, the nested-channel thruster makes gains in thrust and specific impulse, and looks really cool. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ionArgon-125
Title: NASA 457M Hall Thruster[x4] [Test]
Description: Testing shows that clustering engines increases performance, further detaching the plume from the spacecraft. Tested in a laboratory, a cluster of 4 NASA 457Ms pushed the top end thrust density to about 57mN/kW, a substantial improvement.  This of course comes with a power cost, requiring 4 times as much power. (288kW) NOTE: This engine is based on a test article and theoretical predictions.

Name: ionEngine
Title: NSTAR Ion Thruster
Description: Small lightweight efficient ion engine. Takes a bit of power though and doesn't provide much thrust. Diameter: [0.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ionXenon-0625
Title: NEXT Ion Thruster
Description: The Advanced Fairly Trustworthy Electric Rocket engine was the next step for Ion Symphonic Protonic after the IX-6315 began to develop a reputation for being 'lame'. It runs on xenon fuel and is really quite a lot better.

Name: ionXenon-0625-2
Title: HiPEP Ion Thruster [Test]
Description: The High Power Electric Propulsion unit, designed and tested at NASA Glenn Research Center, can produce significantly more thrust than its smaller cousin.  But not that much more.  Requires about 39.3kW of electricity.
PLACEMENT NOTES: Ground test in 2003, 10 years? To fly

Name: ionXenon-0625-3
Title: DS4G Ion Thruster [Test]
Description: The Dual Stage 4 Grid Ion Thruster was developed primarily by the European Space Agency for a variety of future deep space missions.  This version is their most robust design, designed for deep space missions. Requires 50kW of electrical power.  NOTE: This engine is based on technical design and test articles.

Name: ionXenon-125
Title: NEXT Ion Thruster [x2]
Description: The NASA Evolutionary Xenon Thruster project at NASA GRC produced quite a little marvel.  Certified for flight use, and currently planned for several outer-solar system missions, the efficiency of the Ion thruster greatly increased the payload weight, at the expense of burn time. Hope you've got time on your hands! Oh, and about 6.9kW of electricity (13.8kW for two).

Name: ionXenon-25
Title: HiPEP Ion Thruster [x12] [Test]
Description: The High Power Electric Propulsion unit, designed and tested at NASA Glenn Research Center.  Due to low thrust, they clustered 12 of them to get more thrust! Still doesn't push all that hard. Requires about 471.6kW of electricity. NOTE: This engine is a lab test article, and has not flown.

Name: ISRU
Title: Convert-O-Tron 250
Description: This mobile processing plant can take raw materials containing even trace amounts of oxygen and hydrogen, and crack them into useful fuel products.  When operated by a skilled engineer, you will be able to operate with better efficiency.  These modules operate best at their ideal operating temperatures, and features auto-shutdown in the event of excessive overheating.  Radiators can be used to help manage excessive heat. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ISRU_RTG_100
Title: ISRU_RTG_100
Description: ISRU_RTG_100

Name: ius_bottom
Title: IUS Booster First Stage
Description: First stage of the IUS booster Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ius_dec_fs
Title: IUS First Stage Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for IUS booster first stage. Place between first and second stages

Name: ius_dec_ss
Title: IUS Second Stage Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for IUS booster second stage. Place between second stage and payload

Name: ius_top
Title: IUS Booster Second Stage
Description: Second stage of the IUS booster Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: IUSXNP_lft_?3322HORT
Title: Delta IV DCSS LH2 Tank (4 Meters)
Description: The liquid hydrogen tank for the Delta IV 4 meter DCSS.

Name: IUSXNP_lft_?375x3S222HORT
Title: Delta IV DCSS LH2 Tank (5 Meters)
Description: The liquid hydrogen tank for the 5 meter DCSS.

Name: J2
Title: J-2 Series
Description: The Rocketdyne J-2 rocket engine found on the Saturn S-IVB and S-II stages. Ensure you enable roll capability or disable gimbal as required for your application. Diameter: [2.01 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: JetEngine
Title: CF34-3B Turbofan
Description: The CF34 series high bypass turbofan powers many of the CRJ and Challenger lines of civil aircraft. 41.0kN thrust, SFC 0.346 lb/lbf-hr. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: JSIPrimitiveExternalCamera
Title: JSI External Radial-mount Camera
Description: Customers who like multi-function displays with JSI software keep looking around for simple external camera options. This is a most primitive camera, but it works fine when you don't have a better one. No, it's not just an RCS thruster with lens painted on, we have standards here! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: K2Pod
Title: K2 Command Pod (2.5 m)
Description: A two-person pod. Features an offset Center of Mass to allow lifting reentry and an integrated bipropellant Attitude Control System (ACS) for controlled reentries. Heat shield rated for LEO reentries.

Name: KA_Drill_Radial_04
Title: KA-625 Mini-Drill
Description: All of the goodness of Karbonite mining in a small and adorable package.  Also capable of mining Karborundum! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KAS_CPort1
Title: KAS/KIS - Connector Port
Description: A multi-purpose port. Can be used to plug a winch connector or for building pipes. Useful for making ground bases and transferring resources.

Name: KAS_Hook_Anchor
Title: KAS/KIS - Anchor
Description: An anchor to be used for boat, airship or everything else. In addition to its weight, it also provide drag and friction when touching the ground.

Name: KAS_Hook_GrapplingHook
Title: KAS/KIS - Grappling Hook
Description: This hook will attach to everything it collides with, as long as the impact is strong enough. Can be mounted on a winch. To be used with the winch eject function.

Name: KAS_Hook_Harpoon
Title: KAS/KIS - Harpoon
Description: This hook will attach to everything it collides with, as long as the impact is strong enough. Can be mounted on a winch. To be used with the winch eject function.

Name: KAS_Hook_Magnet
Title: KAS/KIS - Electro-Magnet
Description: This electro-magnet is perfect for grabing heavy objects without a connector or a docking port. Can be mounted on a winch or on a hook support.

Name: KAS_Pylon1
Title: KAS/KIS - Pylon
Description: A simple part that can be used as a support for attaching stuff (ports, pipes, etc...)

Name: KAS_Strut1
Title: KAS/KIS - Strut
Description: End point for building a strut from EVA. Links are restricted to the same vessel. Useful for strengthening a vessel.

Name: KAS_Winch1
Title: KAS/KIS - Winch (Stack)
Description: A winch used to extend and retract a cable. A hook or a connector port can be pre-attached if needed.

Name: KAS_Winch2
Title: KAS/KIS - Winch (Radial)
Description: A winch used to extend and retract a cable. A hook or a connector port can be pre-attached if needed.

Name: KerbCan
Title: 1.25m Crew Carrier
Description: One-person inline crew hab section for spaceplanes. Rated for suborbital, or very gentle LEO reentries. X-15 class.

Name: KK_Antares_Castor30Adapter
Title: Antares Castor 30 Adapter
Description: Connects the Castor 30 to the Interstage.

Name: KK_Antares_Castor30Cone
Title: Castor 30 Cone
Description: This is a segment attached between the Castor 30 and one of the payload attach fittings.

Name: KK_Antares_FirstStage
Title: Antares First Stage
Description: The first stage of Orbital Sciences Antares launch vehicle, powered by two AJ-26-62 engines, modified NK-33 engines. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_Antares_Interstage
Title: Antares Interstage
Description: Connects the payload fairing and first stage.

Name: KK_Antares_PayloadFairing
Title: Antares Payload Fairing
Description: The Antares Payload Fairing protects the payload during launch. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_Antares_PayloadFairing_e
Title: Antares Payload Fairing Extended
Description: The Antares Payload Fairing protects the payload during launch. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_Antares_RUAG937SPayloadAdapter
Title: Antares RUAG 937S Payload Adapter
Description: The RUAG 937S connects the Payload Adapter to the Castor 30 Payload Cone.

Name: KK_ATK_Castor30A
Title: Castor 30A
Description: The CASTOR 30 is a low cost, robust, state-of-the-art upper stage motor. This development motor is nominally designed as an upper stage that can function as a second or third stage depending on the vehicle configuration. The design of the  CASTOR 30 uses all flight proven technology and materials. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Castor4
Title: Castor 4
Description: The Castor 4 was developed as the second stage of the Athena H missile and first flew in 1971. It was later adapted to replace Delta's Castor 2 boosters, increasing GTO capacity from 1593 lb (723 kg) to nearly 2000 lb (900 kg). The resulting Delta 3000-series launched in 1975 and was the first to adopt a staggered booster staging sequence. Previous Delta vehicles burned their motors in a 6-3 sequence and then jettisoned all SRMs at once. The heavier and longer-burning Castor 4 required that the ground-lit motors be jettisoned immediately after depletion to reduce dead weight. Early launches used a less efficient 5-4 sequence to reduce acceleration but returned to a 6-3 sequence after Delta was strengthened in the early 80s. Diameter: [1.02 m].

Name: KK_ATK_Castor4A
Title: Castor 4A
Description: The Castor 4A was introduced on the first generation of Delta II launchers, the 6000-series, and offered improved thrust and specific impulse by replacing PBAA with higher energy HTPB. This, combined with a stretched first stage (the Extra-Extended Long Tank Thor) and a return to the more efficient 6-3 SRM ignition sequence, improved Delta's performance by 11% over the 3000-series. The Castor 4A was flown on the Delta II from 1989 until 1993, when it was replaced by the GEM 40. The boosters were also used on the Atlas IIAS from 1993 until 2004. Burn time 53 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM40
Title: GEM 40 (Ground Ignited)
Description: The Graphite-Epoxy Motor (GEM) replaced the steel case used on earlier Castor-series boosters with a lighter composite case. The 40-inch (1-meter) diameter GEM 40 was used on the Delta II 7000-series in sets of three, four, or nine. When nine boosters were used, six were ignited at liftoff and the remaining three were ignited after burnout and jettison of the first six. Burn time: 58 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM40AL
Title: GEM 40 (Air Ignited)
Description: The Graphite-Epoxy Motor (GEM) replaced the steel case used on earlier Castor-series boosters with a lighter composite case. The 40-inch (1-meter) diameter GEM 40 was used on the Delta II 7000-series in sets of three, four, or nine. When nine boosters were used, six were ignited at liftoff and the remaining three were ignited after burnout and jettison of the first six. Burn time: 58 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM46
Title: GEM 46 (Ground Ignited)
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM46AL
Title: GEM 46 (Air Ignited)
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star13B
Title: Star 13B
Description: Orbit insertion motor incorporated the lightweight case developed for the STAR 13 with the propellant and nozzle design of the earlier TE-M-516 apogee motor. The motor case was stretched 2.2 inches to provide for increased propellant loading. The motor was used to adjust orbit inclination of a satellite from a Delta launch. Diameter: [0.34 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star15G
Title: STAR 15G
Description: Single STAR 15G motor, used in a variety of applications. This has a straight nozzle. Diameter: [0.38 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star17A
Title: Star 17A
Description: Apogee kick motor. Modifications: 175 mm straight section added to the Star 17. The 17A has been used for circularized orbits for the Skynet 1, NATO 1, and IMP-H & J satellites. This motor provides the high case safety factor required for this program. The TE-M-521-7 model used for several Air Force missions provides a typical safety factor with a 1.3 pound weight savings. Diameter: [0.44 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star20
Title: Star 20
Description: The lightweight, external nozzle is a composite of graphite, plastic, and steel. The consumable pyrogen igniter is actuated by two 6-second-delay electrical initiators or two SBASI zero-time-delay initiators. Diameter: [0.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star27
Title: Star 27
Description: Apogee motor was developed for the Canadian Communications Research Centre's Communications Technology Satellite, and an offloaded version was qualified and flown successfully. With various propellant loadings and explosive transfer assemblies, it was used for the Broadcast Satellite Experiment, the Geostationary Meteorological Satellite, the Navigation Technology Satellite No. 2, the Global Positioning System Satellites, the P78-1 Satellite, and the Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite. Diameter: [0.68 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star27H
Title: Star 27
Description: Apogee motor was developed for the Canadian Communications Research Centre's Communications Technology Satellite, and an offloaded version was qualified and flown successfully. With various propellant loadings and explosive transfer assemblies, it was used for the Broadcast Satellite Experiment, the Geostationary Meteorological Satellite, the Navigation Technology Satellite No. 2, the Global Positioning System Satellites, the P78-1 Satellite, and the Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite. Diameter: [0.68 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star3
Title: Star 3
Description: The STAR 3 motor was developed and qualified in 2003 as the Transverse Impulse Rocket System (TIRS) for the Mars Exploration Rover (MER) program for the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) in Pasadena, CA. Three TIRS motors were carried on each of the MER landers. One of the TIRS motors was fired in January 2004 to provide the impulse necessary to reduce lateral velocity of the MER Spirit lander prior to landing on the Martian surface. The motor also has applicability for spin/despin and separation systems. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star30BP
Title: Star 30
Description: Total flown included in total for Star-30A. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star31
Title: Star 31
Description: Antares III is the third-generation third stage for Vought Corporation's Scout launch vehicle. The design incorporates an 89-percent-solids HTPB propellant in a Kevlar(r) filament-wound case insulated with silica-filled EPDM rubber. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star37FM
Title: STAR 37
Description: The STAR 37 is a vacuum solid rocket motor, originally developed for the Surveyor lunar lander program as a braking stage. Later variants were used exclusively as apogee kick stages. Diameter: 0.93 m. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star48B
Title: Star 48B
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star48BV
Title: Star 48BV
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star4G
Title: Star 4G
Description: This STAR motor was developed and tested in January 2000 under a NASA Goddard Space Flight Center program for a low-cost, high mass fraction orbit adjust motor for use in deploying constellations of very small satellites (nanosatellites). The first static test of the STAR 4G prototype motor was conducted 8 months after program start. The motor is designed to operate at high chamber pressure and incorporates a noneroding throat insert to maximize specific impulse. Diameter: [0.11 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star5C
Title: Star 5C
Description: The STAR 5C rocket motor was initially designed, developed, qualified, and placed in production (1960-1963) under a contract with Martin Marietta. The STAR 5C is used to separate the second stage from the trans-stage on the Titan II missile and Titan launch vehicle. The current version was qualified for use in 1976, replacing the earlier main propellant grain with TP-H-3062. Diameter: [0.12 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star63D
Title: Star 63D
Description: The STAR 63, as part of the PAM DII upper stage, has been flown from the Space Shuttle. The motor utilizes a head-end web and a carbon-phenolic nozzle. The case material is a Kevlar-epoxy composite, through future motors would be made using a graphiteepoxy composite. Testing of STAR 63 series motors began in 1978 with completion of the PAM DII motor qualification in 1985. The first STAR 63D flight was from the Shuttle in November 1985 to place a defense communication satellite in orbit. Diameter: [1.6 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star6B
Title: Star 6B
Description: The STAR 6B rocket motor was developed for spin-up and axial propulsion applications for re-entry vehicles. The design incorporates an aluminum case and a carbon-phenolic nozzle assembly. The STAR 6B was qualified in 1984 and first flew in 1985. Diameter: [0.18 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star9
Title: Star 9
Description: The STAR 9 rocket motor was developed in 1993 on independent research and development (IR&D) funds to demonstrate a number of low-cost motor technologies. These included an integral aft polar boss/exit cone, two-dimensional carbon-carbon throat, and caseon-propellant manufacturing technique. Diameter: [0.22 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_SPX_F1Fairing
Title: Falcon 1 Fairing
Description: The Fairing protects the Falcon 1's payload during ascent. The fairing gets jettisonned after ignition of the Kestrel second stage's engine.

Name: KK_SPX_F1IS
Title: Falcon 1 Interstage
Description: An interstage connecting the Falcon 1 first and second stages. A simple composite design fitted with explosive bolts.

Name: KK_SPX_F1S1FT
Title: Falcon 1 S1 Fuel Tank (Merlin 1A version)
Description: The Falcon 1 first stage fuel tank is a simple design using a common bulkhead and a lightweight structure. It also is the most reliable part of Falcon 1+, not being a direct cause of any of its failures.

Name: KK_SPX_F1S2FT
Title: Falcon 1 S2 Tank
Description: The second stage of SpaceX's Falcon 1 launch vehicle, equipped with a 3 axis attitude control system.

Description: Attach your payload on top. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Title: Falcon 9 Octaweb

Name: KK_SPX_F91_enginesec
Title: Falcon 9 1.0 Engine Section
Description: Attach the nine Merlin 1C engines to this. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Title: Falcon 9 1.0 Interstage
Description: Interstage for SpaceX Falcon 9 1.0 launch vehicle. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F91_S1tank
Title: Falcon 9 1.0 Main Fuel Tank
Description: This tank supplies the nine Merlin 1C engines of the Falcon 9. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F91_S2tank
Title: Falcon 9 1.0 Upper Fuel Tank
Description: Upper fuel tank for the Falcon 9 1.0 second stage, powered by a single Merlin 1C vacuum. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F912_Interstage_RCS
Title: Falcon 9 Interstage RCS Unit
Description: A small Reaction Control System block, featuring 4 small thrusters combined into a single body. This RCS unit gets attached in a pair to the Falcon 9 1.1/1.1 FT interstage, to reorient the first stage of the Falcon 9 rocket after its seperation. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F92_interstage
Title: Falcon 9 1.1 Interstage
Description: Interstage for SpaceX Falcon 9 1.1 launch vehicle. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F92_S1tank
Title: Falcon 9 1.1 Main Fuel Tank
Description: A stretched fuel tank for Falcon 9 1.1. Due to its stretch and overall weight reduction, it can carry more propellant than the 1.1 Fuel Tank, while still having the same weight. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F92_S2tank
Title: Falcon 9 1.1 Upper Fuel Tank
Description: Upper fuel tank for the Falcon 9 1.1. The tank was compared to Falcon 9 1.0 upper stage fuel tank stretched, and reduced in weight. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F93_interstage
Title: Falcon 9 1.1 FT Interstage
Description: A slightly stretched interstage compared to Falcon 9 1.1s Interstage, with one more seperation pusher to make stage seperation events more reliable. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F93_S1tank
Title: Falcon 9 1.1 FT Main Fuel Tank
Description: The first stage fuel tank for Falcon 9 1.1 Full Thrust. It was slightly stretched again, and supports now super densified propellants. This allows the stage to carry even more propellant and to allow a first stage landing even on GTO flights. It was also strengthened at certain aeras, to tolerate the higher propellant mass and forces the stages has to endure while reentry and landing burn. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F93_S2tank
Title: Falcon 9 1.1 FT Upper Fuel Tank
Description: Upper fuel tank for the Falcon 9 1.1 Full Thrust. It supports even more propellant than the upper stage tank of Falcon  9 1.1 by using densified propellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F93Heavy_seperator
Title: Falcon 9 (1.1 FT) Heavy Seperator
Description: This seperator seperates the two Falcon (1.1 FT) Heavy boosters attached to the core once they are out of fuel. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F9FT_Interstage_RCS
Title: Falcon 9 Full Thrust Interstage RCS Unit
Description: An improved version of the Falcon 9 1.1 Interstage RCS unit. Its thrusters are a little more powerful, the weight was slightly reduced, as was the drag. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_F9LandingLeg
Title: SpaceX Falcon Landing Leg
Description: (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_Falcon9_FC
Title: SpaceX Falcon 9 Flight Control System
Description: Flight Control unit for SpaceX Falcon 9. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_FalconGridfin
Title: SpaceX Gridfin
Description: These fins help SpaceX to steer their Falcon 9 first stage back to the ground using the atmosphere. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_FalconGridfin_FT
Title: SpaceX Gridfin (Full Thrust)
Description: These fins help SpaceX to steer their Falcon 9 first stage back to the ground using the atmosphere. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: KK_SPX_FalconPayloadFairing
Title: SpaceX Falcon Payload Fairing
