Name: KW1mengineMaverick1D
Title: RL10 Series Engine
Description: Hydrolox restartable expander-cycle vacuum engine used in multiple upper stages, including Centaur, the Saturn I S-IV, and the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage. It has low thrust, but very high specific impulse and low mass, making it ideal for high energy, beyond-low-Earth-orbit applications like launching satellites to geostationary transfer orbits or to the Moon or other planets. However, like all hydrolox engines, hydrogen boiloff is a serious issue without heat pumps or radiators. Diameter: [0.92 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KW1mengineVestaVR1
Title: AJ10 Series (Advanced)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents advanced era AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Transtage as AJ10-138; similar models but back with the -118 designation were used on the Delta F and Delta K upper stages. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeI
Title: Castor 4A
Description: The Castor 4A was introduced on the first generation of Delta II launchers, the 6000-series, and offered improved thrust and specific impulse by replacing PBAA with higher energy HTPB. This, combined with a stretched first stage (the Extra-Extended Long Tank Thor) and a return to the more efficient 6-3 SRM ignition sequence, improved Delta's performance by 11% over the 3000-series. The Castor 4A was flown on the Delta II from 1989 until 1993, when it was replaced by the GEM 40. The boosters were also used on the Atlas IIAS from 1993 until 2004. Burn time 53 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeV
Title: Saturn V S-IC Retrorocket
Description: Small solid motor to help separated stages or boosters. Numbers modelled after the S-IC retrorockets. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeVI
Title: AJ-60A
Description: The AJ-60A was developed for the Atlas V, which can be configured with up to five boosters. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeX
Title: GEM 46
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeX10L
Title: UA1207
Description: The UA1207 was used on the Titan IVA, which was developed to launch payloads that had been designed to fly on the Shuttle from Vandenberg. It was a 7-segment modification of the 5-segment UA1205 used on the Titan 3. Burn time 130 seconds. Diameter: [3.05 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeX10S
Title: SRMU
Description: The Titan IVB Solid Rocket Motor Upgrade (SRMU, also know as the Upgraded Solid Rocket Motor or USRM), was developed with the goal of achieving a 25% increase in capacity over the Titan IVA with the UA1207 SRM. It achieved this through the use of a more energetic propellant and a 3-segment composite case that carried more fuel and weighed less than the UA1207's 7-segment steel case. Burn time 150 seconds, 3.2 m diameter. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeX2
Title: GEM 60
Description: The 60-inch (1.5-meter) diameter GEM 60 is used on the Delta IV in sets of two or four. When two boosters are used, both are equipped with thrust vector control (TVC). When four are used, two boosters use TVC while the other two use fixed nozzles to reduce weight. Burn time 90 seconds. Diameter: [1.52 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbGlobeX5
Title: EAP-241
Description: Solid booster as found on the Ariane 5. Sky rockets in flight. Burn time 124 seconds. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbUllage
Title: Saturn V S-II Retrorocket
Description: Four of these were installed on the S-IVB Aft Interstage and stayed attached to the S-II upon separation of that stage. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KWsrbUllageLarge
Title: Saturn V S-II Ullage Motor
Description: Up to eight of these were installed on the S-II Aft Interstage to aid in ullage and separation. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Description: This payload fairing wall was designed for the Atlas series of heavy lifting rockets.  The pointed shape optimizes for low drag at high velocities, designed by the engineers who actually expect the rocket to reach those velocities.  Fools.

Name: KzProcFairingGryphonTsyklon
Title: FW - Tsyklon Fairing Wall

Name: KzProcFairingJupiter
Title: Payload Fairing - Jupiter [Procedural]
Description: This fairing is designed with a more curved shape for the Jupiter craft.  The blunted nose provides a better drag profile at lower velocities, and is thus suited for a steeper ascent, where the atmosphere quickly becomes a minimal design factor.  The engineers ran the calculations to see how steep the ascent would have to be before they didn't have to design any fairings.  The budget office laughed at their design proposal.

Description: This fairing wall designed for the Russian Proton Rocket features a two-tiered conic design, for oddly shaped payloads, multiple payloads, or just because it looks cool.

Title: Payload Fairing - Titan [Procedural]
Description: An old fairing design, but it still checks out.  Straight sections make the fairing easy and cheap to produce, while the varying angle of the segments make the aerodynamic drag profile ideal.  At least, that's what we told the bean-counters.  We just think it looks cool.

Name: KzResizableFairingBase
Title: FB - Payload Fairing - Base (Extended) [Procedural]

Name: KzResizableFairingBaseRing
Title: FB - Payload Fairing - Base [Procedural]

Name: KzThrustPlate
Title: Thrust Plate [Procedural]
Description: When quad-adapter just isn't enough, Keramzit Engineering has you covered with its wonderful Multi-adapter! Designed for bulding engine clusters, it also found its uses in multiple payload attachment and space bars.

Name: l11_astro
Title: Luna 11 Astro
Description: Astro unit for Luna 11. Contains batteries. Decouple before doing landing burn.

Name: l11_radio
Title: Luna 11 Radio
Description: Radio unit for Luna 11. Contains batteries, powerful transmitter and sciecne experiments. Decouple before doing landing burn.

Name: L25mSci
Title: Station Science Module (Early)
Description: This module, designed for use on space stations, contains various planetary science and space science equipment designed for use in repeatable experiments. However, all data must be returned to the surface, you can't exactly beam samples back and forth. Unlike other science equipment which records all data instantly, experimenents using this equipment may be repeated multiple times (on subsequent crew rotations) for further scientific value. Don't forget to transfer all the data to the RV before the crew returns home!

Name: ladder1
Title: Pegasus I Mobility Enhancer
Description: The Pegasus I Mobility Enhancer, known in some circles as a "ladder", is a state-of-the-art vertical mobility device, allowing your intrepid crew to scamper around the exterior of your ship like highly caffeinated rodents.

Name: landerCabinMedium
Title: Mk1 Lander Can Advanced
Description: This capsule was designed for lightweight non-atmospheric landers, and seats two occupants.

Name: landerCabinSmall
Title: Mk1 Lander Can
Description: A small, single-person cabin for use on non-atmospheric landers and small spacecraft.

Name: landingleg-pod-1
Title: LT-POD Landing Assembly
Description: The LT-POD Landing Assembly shields a retractable leg inside a tastefully designed aerodynamic pod. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: landingLeg1
Title: LT-1 Landing Struts
Description: It may have been originally designed as a heavy-duty metal detector, but this landing leg certainly emphasises an important fact in surface landings: you don't need to put a crater in the ground to stop yourself!

Name: landingLeg1-2
Title: LT-2 Landing Strut
Description: The LT-2 Landing Strut offers a heavy-duty method for planting yourself firmly on the ground, without the severe consequences that usually accompany planting yourself firmly on the ground.

Name: Large_Crewed_Lab
Title: Mobile Processing Lab MPL-LG-2
Description: No longer are you limited to research facilities only on Kerbin!  With the Mobile Processing Lab, you can conduct long-term experiments and ongoing research with the data you collect in the field.  Be sure to check back on your scientists from time to time, and transmit the results of their research home! This model is guaranteed to spontaneously combust less than previous models, and also has the equipment necessary to clean out and restore functionality to inoperable experiments. Contains O2 supply for it's scientists, however there is no food or water allowed in the science facility. Ships with 1 day supply, able to store 30 days.

Name: largeAdapter
Title: Rockomax Brand Adapter
Description: Governmental pressure and several lawsuits led Rockomax to finally consider creating an adapter to connect its own parts to that of its competitors. As much as the CEOs hated it, however, it was a resounding success.

Name: largeAdapter2

Description: A shorter adapter from Rockomax, formed under similar circumstances to its big brother. Coated with spaceproof paint for maximum integrity.

Description: The Communotron 88-X is the chubby hotrod of antennas, fast speedy communications can be yours in a bulky 3m package. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: LargeInflatableHAB
Title: PPD-20 Jumbo Kerbal Can
Description: The biggest crew container you can possibly get for your rocket or station, some exceptions do apply. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: LargeOMS
Title: Astris
Description: German pressure-fed vacuum engine burning Aerozine50 and NTO. Used on the stage of the same name on the Europa I and II launch vehicles. Diameter: [2.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: largeSolarPanel
Title: XT4 Solar Panel Array Mk1
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 4 solar panel. 13.0m^2.

Name: largeSolarPanelEarly
Title: XT3 Solar Panel Array Mk1
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel. 6.0m^2.

Name: LargeTank
Title: Large Holding Tank
Description: A large tank that can be used for storing raw materials.  Not to be used as a bouncy castle. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: largeTrussMount
Title: Modular Girder Universal Mounting Plate
Description: Place anything anywhere with the Modular Girder Universal Mounting Plate!

Name: launchClamp1
Title: TT18-A Launch Stability Enhancer
Description: The TT18-A Stability Enhancer uses ground-breaking fastening technology to significantly increase the stability of spacecraft during the pre-launch phase. While OMB Demolition has been criticized in the past for using "big fancy words for a rocket holder" in their description of their device, none can say the TT18 series doesn't deliver rock-solid clamping action, as advertised. The owner's manual strongly suggests these devices be placed on the bottommost section of the spacecraft, and activated as soon as the engines are lit, for optimal de-clamping performance.

Name: LaunchEscapeSystem
Title: Apollo Launch Escape System
Description: Stock LES with the performance of the Apollo LES built by Lockheed for use with the stock Mk1-2 pod. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: legstrotLandingLeg
Title: AIES Legstrot Landing Leg
Description: VHME-T is an effective landing system leaving enough space below. This development was a challenge for the AIES engineering department but we are very satisfied with the results.

Name: LEROS1b
Title: LEROS-1b (635N)
Description: LEROS is a family of chemical rocket engines manufactured by Moog-ISP. LEROS engines have been used as primary apogee engines for telecommunications satellites such as the Lockheed Martin A2100 as well as deep space missions such as Juno. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: LEROS4
Title: LEROS-4 (1100N)
Description: The LEROS 4 High Thrust Apogee Engine is a ESA funded 1100 N spacecraft main engine undergoing development by Moog. The engine will uniquely support the agencies future interplanetary exploration missions by reducing the mass of spacecraft propellant required for orbit insertion manoeuvres and so allow increased scientific payload to be accommodated on these missions. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: LFUELM3
Title: PPD-SM1600 Service Module
Description: An innovative multi-purpose design. Allows the storage of multiple and various resources to suit most mission parameters.

Name: LGLadderUtility

Description: The MK III Mobility Enhancer, known in some circles as a "ladder", is a state-of-the-art vertical mobility device, allowing your intrepid crew to scamper around the exterior of your ship like highly caffeinated rodents.

Name: LgRadialSolarPanel
Title: ST3 Solar Panel
Description: Static Level 2 solar panel. 1.24m^2

Name: Liberty12
Title: Liberty L-12
Description: Liberty V12 engine rated at 449HP at 2000RPM (max). 10ft 2-blade fixed pitch propeller.

Name: linearRcs
Title: RCS Thruster (550/890 N class)
Description: A generic single RCS thruster. Use this for attitude control or translation/ullage for large stages.

Name: liquidEngine
Title: LR105 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator sustainer engine used in the Atlas launch vehicle. It, like the Atlas's booster engines (LR89s) are lit on the ground, but after a bit over 2 minutes' flight the boosters are dropped and the Atlas core continues to orbit under the power of the sustainer engine (and the verniers for roll control and final adjustment). The final configuration of the LR105 (like the LR89) uses RS-27 components for increased performance. As a sustainer engine, the LR105 has relatively poor sea level specific impulse compared to most boosters, but somewhat better vacuum specific impulse--though the difference in both is nowhere near as pronounced as when comparing a booster to an upper stage engine. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngine1-2
Title: LR79 Series
Description: Long-lasting US Kerolox gas-generator booster engine. The same components and broadly the same performance as the LR89, the LR79 (also known as S-3D in Jupiter / Juno II) powered Jupiter, Thor, and Thor-Delta (Delta) rockets. Diameter: [1.53 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngine2
Title: S1.5400/RD-58 Series
Description: World's first closed-cycle kerolox vacuum engine. The S1.5400 served as an R-7 upper stage and the RD-58 (an upgrade) as upper stage / OMS for many Soviet and Russian launchers and spacecraft (Proton, N1, Zenit, Buran...). The S1.5400 was designed for the Blok L stage which was the final stage for the Molniya configuration of the R-7, used to launch communication satellites and interplanetary probes. Unlike prior upper stages, it was restartable (this was needed to perform apogee kick to place Molniya satellites in their final orbits). It was given the industry designation 11D33. An upgraded version, termed 11D33M, had slightly improved performance. The RD-58 is a derivative of the 11D33M engine with higher performance (industry designation 11D58); it has been used on many Russian launchers and is still in use today on Proton and Zenit. In comparison to hydrolox upper stages, kerolox ones do not suffer boiloff as badly and need far less volume (kerosene being far denser than liquid hydrogen), but have much lower specific impulse. Diameter: [2.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngine2-2
Title: Lunar Module Descent Engine
Description: Deeply throttleable pressure-fed vacuum engine used for the descent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Uses storable propellants which are not subject to boiloff, but are far less efficient than hydrolox or even kerolox. The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngine3
Title: RD-0105/0109 Series
Description: Kerolox gas generator vacuum engine which served in R-7 upper stages (Luna, Vostok). The RD-0105 was designed for Luna launches; it was the first upper stage for the R-7 series and was reused for uncrewed Vostok tests. An enhanced version, the RD-0109, was used for crewed Vostok launches. Diameter: [2.56 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngineconstelacion
Title: J-2X
Description: 2000s medium TWR, vacuum engine. The J-2X was intended to be used on the upper stages of Ares I and Ares V. Development continued after the cancellation of Ares, and early designs of SLS incorporated the engine, but selection of the RL10-powered Exploration Upper Stage resulted in the project being mothballed. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngineMini
Title: Lunar Module Ascent Engine
Description: Pressure-fed engine used for the ascent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Diameter: [0.86 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngineMiniRescale
Title: Aestus II
Description: Smaller MMH/NTO upper stage rocket engine that can also be used for orbital manuevers. [1.5 m] Plume configured by RealPlume.
PLACEMENT NOTES: Not ready yet, but tech not really Near Future

Name: liquidEngineMiniTurbo
Title: BE-4
Description: The BE-4 is an oxidizer-rich staged combustion engine that burns LNG/LOX. Though initially developed for use on a Blue Origin launch vehicle, in 2014 United Launch Alliance announced that their new Vulcan booster, the successor to the Atlas V and Delta IV, will be powered by a pair of BE-4 engines. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEnginemogulmp1500
Title: RD-170 Series
Description: 1980s to present, High TWR, atmospheric booster engine. The RD-170 is the most powerful liquid rocket engine ever flown. Originally developed for the Energia launcher's boosters, the engine consists of four combustion chambers fed by a single turbopump. A modified version, the RD-171, is used on the first stage of the Zenit launch vehicle. Diameter: [3.8 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngineorbit2
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: liquidEngineprodulVR2
Title: LR87 Booster
Description: Used in the first stage of the Titan rocket family, the LR87 is composed of two engines with separate turbomachinery integrated into one unit. The version used on Titan I burned kerosene and liquid oxygen, while Titan II through Titan IV burned storable propellants. A modified version burning liquid hydrogen was developed for the upper stages of Saturn V and Saturn IB, but the J-2 was selected instead. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Description: Studies conducted by Probodobodyne Inc have found that today's youth consider mono-propellent engines to be quote 'totally main-stream, uncool, and Grandpa Bill always talks about how Mono-propellent engines saved his butt in the first Mun landing, ugh what is with all of these questions?!'. Upon being bribed for further information, the participants revealed that Xenon powered Ion engines were the current trending item. So in an effort to reach out to the youth and more importantly increase sales, the JKSS has had a tank of xenon crammed inside of it. Solar panels and ion engine sold separately. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

NASA selected the J-2 over the LR87-LH2, however, and it was canceled in 1961. This version represents a version of the engine with a larger nozzle optimized for vacuum use. Name: MiniDrill
Title: Drill-O-Matic Junior' Mining Excavator
Description: A smaller version of the popular Drill-O-Matic, this drill is designed to help extract valuable resources from the crust of planets and asteroids.  Unlike it's larger cousin, this smaller model is only suitable for ore concentrations in excess of 2.5%.  When operated by a skilled engineer, you will be able to operate with better efficiency.  These modules operate best at their ideal operating temperatures, and features auto-shutdown in the event of excessive overheating.  Radiators can be used to help manage excessive heat. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: miniFuelTank

Description: The Oscar-B Fuel Tank from Probodobodyne is a compact fuel container for small space probes, or a backup tank for other small spacecraft. Do not wash in cold water, or feed after midnight.

Name: miniFuselage
Title: 0.625m Fuselage
Description: Propellant-tank fuselage, 0.625m diameter. Rated for suborbital, or very gentle LEO reentries. X-15 class.

Name: miniIntake
Title: Small Circular Intake
Description: A must-have for air breathing engines, this intake duct will pull in outside air to run turbine engines on, as long as there is any outside air to begin with, of course. Optimized for subsonic flight.

Name: MiniISRU
Title: Convert-O-Tron 125
Description: A smaller version of Kerbodyne's mobile processing plant, this module can take raw materials containing even trace amounts of oxygen and hydrogen, and crack them into useful fuel products.  When operated by a skilled engineer, you will be able to operate with better efficiency.  While this smaller model is lighter than it's bigger cousin, it is less efficient, and not designed for long-term operations.  These modules operate best at their ideal operating temperatures, and features auto-shutdown in the event of excessive overheating.  Radiators can be used to help manage excessive heat. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: miniJetEngine
Title: J85-GE-4 turbojet
Description: General Electric J85 turbojet without afterburner, Thrust 13.1 kN, SFC 0.980 lb/lbf-hr static. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: miniLandingLeg
Title: LT-05 Micro Landing Strut
Description: A small landing leg designed for space probes or lightweight landers. Basically made of toothpicks... erm, Space-grade toothpicks mind you, but be careful with them anyway.

Name: Mk1?Mirage?Cockpit
Title: Mk1 Mirage 2000B
Description: Twin-seat fighter cockpit. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Mk1?S39?Cockpit
Title: F-101B Voodoo Cockpit
Description: Cheap and simple cockpit.

Name: Mk1?Su30?Cockpit
Title: Su-30 Cockpit
Description: Sometimes you need to install stuff on the nose and have two crew. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: MK1Cargobay
Title: MK1 Cargo Bay CRG-02
Description: This recently developed cargo bay is as small and compact as they come, with just enough space to store a small probe or a few pieces of science equipment.

Name: MK1CrewCabin
Title: Mk1 Crew Cabin
Description: Four-crew passenger cabin for Mk1 spaceplanes. Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: MK1Fuselage
Title: 1.25m Fuselage
Description: Propellant-tank fuselage, 1.25m diameter. Rated for suborbital, or very gentle LEO reentries. X-15 class.

Name: Mk1FuselageStructural
Title: 1.25m Fuselage (Pressurized)
Description: Highly-pressurized propellant-tank fuselage, 1.25m diameter. Rated for suborbital, or very gentle LEO reentries. X-15 class.

Name: MK1IntakeFuselage
Title: 1.25m Fuselage (Intake)
Description: This version of the Mk1 Fuselage module carries only a bit of fuel, but is fitted with a streamlined air intake. It consists of a "bump" and a forward-swept inlet cowl. This eliminates the need for a Splitter plate, while compressing the air to slow it down from supersonic to subsonic speeds. DSIs can be used to replace the intake ramp and inlet cone, which are more complex, heavy and expensive.

Name: mk1pod
Title: Mk1 Pod (2m)
Description: A one-person pod. Comes with built-in RCS thrusters running off High-Test Peroxide (HTP) and a large battery. Heat shield rated for LEO reentries. Center of mass can be offset slightly to allow lifting reentry (toggle Descent Mode).

Name: mk2_1m_AdapterLong
Title: Mk2 Adapter (Long) [2.0m]
Description: Generic Mk2 to 2m adapter. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2_1m_Bicoupler
Title: Mk2 Bicoupler
Description: One engine is not enough? We got you covered! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2CargoBayL
Title: Mk2 Cargo Bay CRG-08
Description: The longer version of the shorter cargo bay. Some ask us just how long is it? It's exactly double the length of the other one.

Name: mk2CargoBayS
Title: Mk2 Cargo Bay CRG-04
Description: Ever wanted to deploy small items into space such as Cubesats, ion-powered Probes or Kerbals? This is just the part for you! (Disclaimer: C7 Aerospace does not condone the deployment of Kerbals into space via Cargo Bays.)

Name: mk2Cockpit_Inline
Title: Mk2 Inline Cockpit
Description: After 'accidentally' snapping the nose off of the Mk2 Cockpit, the engineers over at the C7 Aerospace Division realised that such a design looked quite functional. They quickly hammered out the following part and spruced it up for all your inline spaceplane cockpit needs!

Name: mk2Cockpit_Standard
Title: Mk2 Cockpit
Description: Fits not one, but two Kerbals! This spearhead-shaped new Mk2 design from the lovable folks over at the C7 Aerospace Division should help you pierce the great blue yonder known as the Sky.

Name: mk2CrewCabin
Title: MK2 Crew Cabin
Description: A Mk2 Profile Compliant, compact and eco-friendly crew transportation module, made from up to 80% recycled aircraft components. C7 Engineers insist that all recycled components were meticulously scrubbed clean before assembly, and take no responsibility for any odd smells that may be detected inside and/or around the unit.

Name: mk2DockingPort
Title: Mk2 Clamp-O-Tron
Description: The new Clamp-O-Tron brand docking port comes complete with integrated monopropellant tanks for all your docking needs.

Name: mk2DroneCore
Title: MK2 Drone Core
Description: After extensive research and testing to improve the safety factor of next-generation modules for their Mk2 series, engineers at C7 Aerospace got fed up with having to constantly find new recruits willing to test their prototypes, and decided to develop an autonomous AI capable of doing the same job, only with a lot less screaming over the comms link. This was met with divided opinions, some criticizing C7 as taking the "booooring" route, others praising them for the innovation, while yet others reacted by shutting themselves in bunkers in anticipation of the time when these units will gain sentience and turn on their creators. C7 has vehemently denied any involvement in all sentient-AI-related catastrophes so far.

Name: mk2Fuselage
Title: Mk2 Fuselage (Long)
Description: This airframe fuselage features the latest in lifting technology. Not only does it stay together during flight, it's sleek design makes your plane just that much speedier! Only carries Liquid Fuel. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2FuselageLongLFO
Title: Mk2 Fuselage (Long) (Pressurized)
Description: This airframe fuselage features the latest in lifting technology. Not only does it stay together during flight, it's sleek design makes your plane just that much speedier! Now comes with at least 100% more Oxidiser. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2FuselageShortLFO
Title: Mk2 Fuselage (Short) (Pressurized)
Description: This airframe fuselage features the latest in lifting technology. Not only does it stay together during flight, it's sleek design makes your plane just that much speedier! Now comes with at least 100% more Oxidiser. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2FuselageShortLiquid
Title: Mk2 Fuselage (Short)
Description: This airframe fuselage features the latest in lifting technology. Not only does it stay together during flight, it's sleek design makes your plane just that much speedier! Only carries Liquid Fuel. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2FuselageShortMono
Title: Mk2 Fuselage (Short) (Pres, low volume)
Description: This airframe fuselage features the latest in lifting technology. Not only does it stay together during flight, it's sleek design makes your plane just that much speedier! Bursting to the brim with Monopropellant for all your attitude control needs! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk2LanderCabin
Title: Mk2 Lander Can
Description: 3-person cockpit for landers and space taxis. Much roomier than earlier models.

Name: mk2SpacePlaneAdapter
Title: Mk2 Adapter (Short) [2.0m]
Description: Generic Mk2 to 2m adapter. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: MK2VApod
Title: TKS VA Command Module
Description: The VA command module is part of the TKS/FGB spacecraft. It can be attached either to the FGB module of the TKS, to the front section of the Almaz station or to both. In the latter case, the station could be launched manned with the crew riding to orbit inside the VA capsule. The crew would be able to exit and enter the VA capsule in orbit via a hatch in the heat shield located at the bottom of the craft. Supports two crew for one day. Center of mass can be offset to allow lifting reentry (toggle Descent Mode).

Name: mk3-9pod
Title: Mk3-9 Orbital Command Pod
Description: This newer command cockpit is optimized for orbital operations - it sacrifices some durability for lower mass. It has extensive fly-by wire systems, and can even pilot a craft without crew! Beware running out of power, though...

Name: mk3CargoBayL
Title: Mk3 Cargo Bay CRG-100
Description: Originally we threw away the container the Rockomax Jumbo-64 tank came in, then one day a bright and upcoming engineer suggested we reuse them. He was promptly reallocated to another department and his boss came up with the brilliant idea of reusing these containers as cargo bays!

Name: mk3CargoBayM
Title: Mk3 Cargo Bay CRG-50
Description: Originally we threw away the container the Rockomax X200-32 tank came in, then one day a bright and upcoming engineer suggested we reuse them. He was promptly reallocated to another department and his boss came up with the brilliant idea of reusing these containers as cargo bays!

Name: mk3CargoBayS
Title: Mk3 Cargo Bay CRG-25
Description: Originally we threw away the container the Rockomax X200-16 tank came in, then one day a bright and upcoming engineer suggested we reuse them. He was promptly reallocated to another department and his boss came up with the brilliant idea of reusing these containers as cargo bays!

Name: mk3CargoRamp
Title: Mk3 Cargo Ramp
Description: A sophisticated deployment system for cargo delivery on the ground, or on the sea, or in mid-air, or in a vacuum. Wherever you want, really.

Name: mk3Cockpit_Shuttle
Title: Mk3 Cockpit
Description: A cockpit for those die hard explorers. Especially useful when transporting extra crew to a remote rock to save the day.

Name: mk3CrewCabin
Title: Mk3 Passenger Module
Description: At a capacity of 16 Kerbals, the Mk3 Passenger module is known in the Astronaut Complex breakrooms as the "Super Economy" class for spacetravel and allows only carry-on baggage. Any checked or emotional baggage may require one of the Mk3 Cargo Bays.

Name: mk3FuselageLF_100
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Long)
Description: C7 Aerospace Division had issues piping the fuel from the refinery, so they brought the refinery tanks to us! It sounded like they muttered "Good luck.." as they dropped off these parts. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk3FuselageLF_25
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Short)
Description: For the economically minded aerospace designer, who is building a massive plane... (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk3FuselageLF_50
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Medium)
Description: For when your fuel needs are only 1/4 as enormous. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk3FuselageLFO_100
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Long) (Pressurized)
Description: Filled to the brim with Rocket Fuel, C7 Aerospace's supplier Ekson-Kobil have assured us that this tank is absolutely airtight. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk3FuselageLFO_25
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Short) (Pressurized)
Description: A compact fuel tank for when the rest of your craft is taken up by cargo bays! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk3FuselageLFO_50
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Medium) (Pressurized)
Description: For that rare moment when your fuel needs are less than ludicrous. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk3FuselageMONO
Title: Mk3 Fuselage (Short) (Pres, low volume)
Description: The reaction to when the reaction control system doesn't have enough control in the system
MOD: more monopropellant! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mk4-1pod
Title: Mk4-1 Heavy Command Module
Description: The majestic Mark Four Dash One Command module is a sleek piece of Kerbal engineering. Seating up to seven occupants, it functions well in a multitude of situations. It can be used as a probe control point in a pinch, too. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: mm_shield1
Title: Skylab MicroMeteorite Shield 1
Description: Install this panel and decouple it while in flight to simulate real life event. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: mm_shield2
Title: Skylab MicroMeteorite Shield 2
Description: Install this panel and decouple it while in flight to simulate real life event. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Mode#1
Title: Mode#1
PLACEMENT NOTES: Cancelled in 1988, this is up to 15 years of dev

Name: Mode#1
Title: Mode#1
PLACEMENT NOTES: Cancelled in 1988, this is up to 15 years of dev

Name: Mode#2
Title: Mode#2
PLACEMENT NOTES: Cancelled in 1988, this is up to 15 years of dev

Name: Mode#2
Title: Mode#2
PLACEMENT NOTES: Cancelled in 1988, this is up to 15 years of dev

Name: moduldesspod
Title: AIES P1 'Moduldess'
Description: Previously a deep water research bathysphere (which previously was a pressure cooker) is now used for interplanetary travel. The waterproof interior has a single seat for kerbonaut and a full set of controls to operate the spacecraft. The waterproof quality is achieved by newly discovered phenomenon known as 'There is no water in space'.

Name: molniya_asas
Title: Molniya-1 ASAS
Description: Tiny ASAS for Molniya-1. Attach upside down radially on the main body. This allows the probe to be controlled upside down to use the engines, which face forwards instead of backwards.

Name: molniya1
Title: Molniya-1
Description: Soviet Molniya-1 satellite Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: MonkeyCargoBoosterSLSADJ
Title: SLS Core Booster (Block I/IB/II)
Description: The Space Launch System (SLS) core booster stage. Equipped with four RS-25E engines. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: MonkeyPodAirlock
Title: SP - 104 Airlock Module
Description: An airlock module designed for either on-orbit or surface operations. Provides ingress and egress support for up to 3 crew.

Name: MonkeyPodAirlock3x
Title: CHAKA / HAB Monkey Pod Intermediate (1.55)
Description: This is the smallest rigid monkey habitat module. Contains Monkey Snaxx (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: MonkeyPodLanderPSx3
Title: CHAKA / HAB Experimental
Description: Similar to Monkey Pod Lander, this module is an appropriate medium habitat for landing on Duna or Mun. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: MonkeyPodOrionTypeS22
Title: SP - 1000 Habitation Module
Description: A soft shell habitation module designed for deep space operations.

Name: MonkeyPodOrionTypeS22xa66ck2cx
Title: CHAKA / MTV Intersection
Description: This ultimate rigid habitat is used for transfer of monkeys or kerbals to Duna. Contains Monkey Snaxx (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: MonkeyPodOrionTypeS22xa66ckX4899
Title: CHAKA / Ultra Hab II
Description: This ultimate rigid habitat is used for transfer of monkeys or kerbals to Duna. Contains Monkey Snaxx (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: MonkeyPodpsADAPTER
Title: Logistics Module (Small)
Description: A general purpose cargo module for on-orbit operations.

Name: MonkeyPodpsADAPTERmtvLHSM66xsa
Title: CHAKA / Inverted Lander Sub Module
Description: "Adapter" Size monkey modules are medium sized and very handy.  Contains Monkey Snaxx (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: MonkeySMA8FPodLANDERPsXX
Title: SP - 600 Habitation Module
Description: A hard shell habitation module designed for surface operations.

Name: monoprop-tank-125-1
Title: FL-R-A750 Monopropellant Tank
Description: Rockomax provides this set of storage tanks, in a tasteful 1.25m form factor! This one is long. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-125-2
Title: FL-R-A375 Monopropellant Tank
Description: Rockomax provides this set of storage tanks, in a tasteful 1.25m form factor! This one is medium, and juuuust right. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-125-3
Title: FL-R-A185 Monopropellant Tank
Description: Rockomax provides this set of storage tanks, in a tasteful 1.25m form factor! This one is small. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-25-1
Title: FL-R-B3000 Monopropellant Tank
Description: The FL-R series stores monopropellant in bounteous quantities. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-25-2
Title: FL-R-B1500 Monopropellant Tank
Description: The FL-R series stores monopropellant in bounteous quantities, except, in this half-size model, a little less. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-25-3
Title: FL-R-B750 Monopropellant Tank
Description: Let's say you prefer your 750 L monopropellant tank to look good. This tank might be a better option than the FL-R-1 (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-375-1
Title: FL-R-C6000 Monopropellant Tank
Description: It's been said that you don't really need that much monopropellant for your spacegoing RCS needs. We beg to differ (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-375-2
Title: FL-R-C3000 Monopropellant Tank
Description: An above-average sized tank transports an above-average amount of fuel. In this case, it's monopropellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: monoprop-tank-375-3
Title: FL-R-C1500 Monopropellant Tank
Description: Building a big service module? Need a big monopropellant tank? This'll do you good. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: mpdt-0625
Title: DS01 'Charon' MPDT [Theoretical]
Description: An accelerated plasma thruster that can achieve very high thrusts (well, for an electric engine) at the cost of an really large amount of power. There's rumors that Kerb Kastria is trying to cover up an incident where one of their test stands melted from waste heat, but their PR department assures us that it's all unfounded.

Name: mpdt-125
Title: DS02 'Pyrios' MPDT [Theoretical]
Description: We added more and more magnets to the small magnetoplasmadynamic thruster, until we ran out of magnets. Then some more pipe, and some more wires. Then we bought some more magnets. This was the result.

Name: mpdt-25
Title: LF-9 'Colossus' Magnetoplasmadynamic Engine [Theoretical]
Description: Eventually, you need so much thrust that calling something a 'thruster' starts getting worn out. So, 'engine' it is. This MPD... E needs a small metropolis' worth of power, but the results are quite satisfying.

Name: MR_80b_MLE
Title: MR-80B (MLE)
Description: The Mars Landing Engine (MLE) is a derivative of the highly successful MR-80 engine used for the two Viking missions to Mars in 1976. Eight of these engines where used on the sky-crane which landed the Curiosity Rover on the martian surface. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: MR103
Title: MR-103 (1N)
Description: The MR-103 1N Rocket Engine Assembly is a hydrazine monopropellant rocket engine, flight proven as attitude control thruster for Voyager, GPS, Intelsat 5, MMAS 3000, 4000,. 5000, and 7000, Mars Observer, ACTS, and Magellan.

Name: MR104
Title: MR-104 (440N)
Description: MR-104 Monopropellant Engine family originally provided in-space propulsion for the Voyager 1 and 2 and Magellan missions. Subsequent MR-104 variants provided propulsion for Landsat and NOAA as well as for other U.S. government programs. A variation of this engine (MR-104G) is to be used on the Orion Deep Space Exploration Vehicle. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: MR106Axial
Title: MR-106 Axial (40N)
Description: The MR-106 40N monopropellant thruster is a small rocket engine designed for spacecraft and upper stage attitude control and velocity corrections, used on Radarsat, GPS Block 2R, HAS/Peace Courage, Titan Centaur, Atlas Centaur & many more.

Name: MR106Lateral
Title: MR-106 Lateral (40N)
Description: The MR-106 40N monopropellant thruster is a small rocket engine designed for spacecraft and upper stage attitude control and velocity corrections. This version is cantered at a 90 degree angle.

Name: MR107
Title: MR-107 (270N)
Description: MR-107 Monopropellant Engine family. A small dV correction engine used on many space probes and second stage vehicles. Also used as the landing engines for the Phoenix Mars Lander & the Mars Polar Lander. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: MR111
Title: MR-111 (4N)
Description: The MR-111 4N Rocket Engine Assembly is a hydrazine monopropellant rocket engine, flight proven as attitude control thruster for the Mars Observer, Juno spacecraft & to be used on the OSIRIS-REx Asteroid sample return mission.

Name: MR80TDE
Title: MR-80 (TDE)
Description: The Viking lander Terminal Descent Engine (TDE). The lander had three such engines, which were used during the final 45 seconds or so of the descent to the surface of Mars. Multiple small exhaust nozzles are used to diffuse the exhaust plume and eliminate a recirculation zone that could contaminate spacecraft instrumentation and avoid potential extensive erosion of the landing site. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: MRM106D
Title: MRM-106D (2 Engine 40N)
Description: The MRM-106D monopropellent rocket engine assembly is a small set of thrusters used for attitude control & propellent settling for upper stages. Used on the Atlas-Centaur upper stage as well as the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS).

Name: MRM106D4
Title: MRM-106D (4 Engine 40N)
Description: The MRM-106D monopropellent rocket engine assembly is a small set of thrusters used for attitude control & propellent settling for upper stages. Used on the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS).

Name: MRM106F
Title: MRM-106F (40N)
Description: The MRM-106F monopropellent rocket engine assembly is a small set of thrusters used for attitude control & propellent settling for upper stages. Used on the Atlas-Centaur upper stage.

Name: MRM111
Title: MRM-111 (4N)
Description: The MRM-111 4N Monopropellent Rocket Module, consists of three MR-111 rockets. Designed and flight proven as attitude control thruster block for the Juno spacecraft currently in orbit around Jupiter.

Name: ms1RCSTank
Title: AIES MS-1 RCS Fuel
Description: This fairly small and efficient RCS tank was designed for use with the SN-1 Micro RCS Thruster Block. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: mumech_MJ2_AR202
Title: Guidance and Control Module (Radial)
Description: A ruggedized version of MechJeb's neural circuits in a radial-mount case.

Name: mumech_MJ2_AR202_features1
Title: MechJeb Features- Maneuver & Translatron
Description: Unlocks the following MechJeb windows: Maneuver Planner, Translatron, Warp Helper, Attitude Adjustment, Thrust Window, RCS Balancer. Once unlocked, all existing MechJeb modules will be automatically upgraded to latest firmware. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: mumech_MJ2_AR202_features2
Title: MechJeb Features- Rover Autopilot
Description: Unlocks the following MechJeb windows: Rover Autopilot. Once unlocked, all existing MechJeb modules will be automatically upgraded to latest firmware. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: mumech_MJ2_AR202_features3
Title: MechJeb Features- Ascent, Landing, Spaceplane
Description: Unlocks the following MechJeb windows: Ascent Autopilot, Landing Autopilot, Spaceplane Guidance. Once unlocked, all existing MechJeb modules will be automatically upgraded to latest firmware. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: mumech_MJ2_AR202_features4
Title: MechJeb Features- Rendezvous & Docking
Description: Unlocks the following MechJeb windows: Rendezvous Guidance, Rendezvous Autopilot, Docking Autopilot. Once unlocked, all existing MechJeb modules will be automatically upgraded to latest firmware. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: mumech_MJ2_Pod
Title: Self Contained Probe
Description: After many years spent on research, our scientists still couldn't explain why Jebediah Kerman was such a good pilot, so we decided to make a mechanical copy of his brain to help pilot our ships. This is an unmanned pod version of MechJeb, designed to save the life of the brave Kerbals who volunteer to test new crafts. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: nacelleBody
Title: Engine Nacelle
Description: The Engine Nacelle is a self-contained solution for powering air-breathing engines. It includes some reserve fuel, making it a very practical option. C7 Engineers assure us that these units are quite safe, and that the dents and burn marks will give yours a more unique look. Optimized for subsonic flight; includes very powerful static suction. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: NASA-457M-V2
Title: (stored in NearFuture Configs)
PLACEMENT NOTES: Higher thrust, better ISP = next era

Name: NASA-457M-V2-X4
Title: (stored in NearFuture Configs)
PLACEMENT NOTES: Higher thrust, better ISP = next era

Name: ndsport1
Title: NASA Docking System (Passive)
Description: The NASA Docking System (NDS) is a spacecraft docking and berthing mechanism for US human spaceflight vehicles, such as the Orion Multi-Purpose Crew Vehicle and the Commercial Crew vehicles.

Name: ndsport3
Title: NASA Docking System (Active)
Description: The NASA Docking System (NDS) is a spacecraft docking and berthing mechanism for US human spaceflight vehicles, such as the Orion Multi-Purpose Crew Vehicle and the Commercial Crew vehicles.

Name: neo_dawn
Title: Dawn
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Dawn

Name: neo_deepimpact
Title: Deep Impact
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Deep Impact

Name: neo_deepimpact_impactor
Title: Deep Impact Impactor
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Deep Impact Impactor

Name: neo_ds1
Title: Deep Space 1
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Deep Space 1

Name: neo_near
Title: NEAR - Shoemaker
Description: Near Earth Object satellite NEAR Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: neo_stardust
Title: Stardust
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Stardust

Name: neo_stardust_collector
Title: Stardust Return Capsule
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Stardust Return Capsule.

Name: neo_stardust_para
Title: Stardust Return Capsule Parachute
Description: Parachute for Near Earth Object satellite Stardust Return Capsule. Flip this upside down to attach to return capsule.

Name: neo_ulysses
Title: Ulysses
Description: Near Earth Object satellite Ulysses

Name: neptuno
Title: HS-333 Satellite Bus
Description: Satellite bus originally launched in 1972.

Name: NERVA-I
Title: NERVA-I
PLACEMENT NOTES: Most likely wouldn't have launched till late 70s

Name: nervaII_kerbscalexx
Title: Bimodal NTR
Description: Low thrust pump-fed expander nuclear engine. Evolved for the original NERVA design the Bimodal NTR, instead of wasting precious propellant mass for cooling the engine reactor, uses a Brayton cycle electricity generator unit to convert the waste thermal energy into useful electrical power. It also supports liquid oxygen injection (TRITON - trimodal operation) for increased thrust but with the cost of a lower overall efficiency. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NK33
Title: NK-15/33
Description: The NK-15 and NK-33 were originally built in the 1960s/early 1970s for the Soviet N1 and then N1F rocket, respectively. Though the N1F was scrapped, the engines survived. Aerojet acquired several NK-33 engines in the 1990s and refurbished them as AJ26-62 engines for Orbital Science's Antares launch vehicle. Modifications made by Aerojet included increasing rated thrust and equipping the engines to support gimballing. Diameter: [1.83 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NK33_StockVersion
Title: NK-15/33
Description: The NK-15 and NK-33 were originally built in the 1960s/early 1970s for the Soviet N1 and then N1F rocket, respectively. Though the N1F was scrapped, the engines survived. Aerojet acquired several NK-33 engines in the 1990s and refurbished them as AJ26-62 engines for Orbital Science's Antares launch vehicle. Modifications made by Aerojet included increasing rated thrust and equipping the engines to support gimballing. Diameter: [1.83 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NK33attachment
Title: Soyuz-2-1V Vernier Assembly
Description: The vernier assembly of the Soyuz-2-1V launch vehicle first stage. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: NK33engine
Title: NK-15/33
Description: The NK-15 and NK-33 were originally built in the 1960s/early 1970s for the Soviet N1 and then N1F rocket, respectively. Though the N1F was scrapped, the engines survived. Aerojet acquired several NK-33 engines in the 1990s and refurbished them as AJ26-62 engines for Orbital Science's Antares launch vehicle. Modifications made by Aerojet included increasing rated thrust and equipping the engines to support gimballing. Diameter: [1.83 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NK43_StockVersion
Title: NK-15V/43
Description: Originally designed and built for the N1F, the NK-43 is a derivative of the NK-33 with longer bell and restart capability for upper stages. Diameter: [2.54 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NK43engine
Title: NK-15V/43
Description: Originally designed and built for the N1F, the NK-43 is a derivative of the NK-33 with longer bell and restart capability for upper stages. Diameter: [2.54 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: noseCone
Title: Aerodynamic Nose Cone
Description: Aerodynamic, lightweight and mostly non-explosive. As a reminder to all personnel operating nearby, this part is really sharp and it'd probably hurt if you fell on it.

Name: noseConeAdapter
Title: NCS Adapter
Description: The base of C7 Aerospace's Nose Cone system (NCS) (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: nosExplorerRadialEngine
Title: Pegasus Engine Pod
Description: Radially mounted engine pod, originally designed for the Pegasus Descent Module. Contains the engines and RCS thrusters for attitude control. Plume configured by RealPlume.
PLACEMENT NOTES: Fictional Advanced Lander, Same time as Altair

Name: nosMonkeyExplorerUtilityALTAIR3tga9XXX
Title: CHAKA / NOS Duna Expanded Ultra
Description: Lander for Altair (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: nosMonkeyExplorerUtilityHAB
Title: Pegasus Descent Module
Description: The Pegasus Descent Module is designed to carry heavy crew or cargo components on planetary surfaces. The radial attachment of the engines and the distance from the surface allows for safe propulsive landings.
PLACEMENT NOTES: Fictional Advanced Lander, Same time as Altair

Name: novapod
Title: AIES G1 'Nova' [2.0m]
Description: This compact and reliable multi-purpose probe features the best fake tinfoil available on the market to increase its lifetime.

Name: NP_AMLVUPPER289Jx221
Title: Falcon 9 Second Stage Equipment Bay
Description: The engine mount structure and attitude control system propellant tanks for the Falcon 9 upper stage. (Missing entryCost field)

Name: NP_CHAKAEMLVENGINE
Title: Delta IV CBC Engine Mount
Description: The RS-68 engine mount for the Delta IV Common Booster Core (CBC). (Missing entryCost field)

Name: NP_CHAKAEMLVENGINEx221
Title: MAV - II Propellant Tank
Description: A generic pressurized propellant tank for the Mars Ascent Vehicle (MAV). (Missing entryCost field)

Name: NP_lfe_25m_Orbitalbertha_Mini
Title: XLR99 Spaceplane Engine
Description: LOX/Ammonia gas generator engine which powered the X-15 spaceplane. The first large, throttleable, restartable liquid fuel rocket engine. Diameter: [1.42 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NP_S592
Title: S5.92
Description: The S5.92 is a Russian rocket engine currently powering the Fregat upper stage. The S5.92 engine was developed for use on the Phobos missions, then later adapted for use on the Fregat space tug which currently serves as the orbital stage for the Soyuz and Zenit launch vehicles. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: NP_S598M
Title: S5.98M (14D30)
Description: The S5.98M also known as the 14D30 is a Russian rocket engine, currently powering the Briz upper stages. The engines design was based on the S5.92 engine, but differs slightly in mass, performance and physical layout. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ntr-sc-125-1
Title: NERVA I
Description: 1970s low TWR vacuum engine. the NERVA (Nuclear Engine for Rocket Vehicle Applications) is designed for orbital tugs and large rocket upper stages. Diameter: [1.25 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.
PLACEMENT NOTES: Most likely wouldn't have launched till late 70s

Name: ntr-sc-125-2
Title: NERVA II
Description: A later 70s atomic engine. Relatively low TWR but high ISP and power generation of 4200 MW. Derived from the Phoebus 2A ground demonstrator, tested in 1968. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ntr-sc-25-1
Description: Low thrust pump-fed expander nuclear engine. Evolved for the original NERVA design the Bimodal NTR, instead of wasting precious propellant mass for cooling the engine reactor, uses a Brayton cycle electricity generator unit to convert the waste thermal energy into useful electrical power. It also supports liquid oxygen injection (TRITON - trimodal operation) for increased thrust but with the cost of a lower overall efficiency. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: nuclear-recycler-25
Title: Whirlijig Nuclear Reprocessor
Description: This centrifugal facility can both process Ore into Enriched Uranium and reprocess Depleted Fuel into Enriched Uranium or XenonGas. Both processes require a large amount of power and cooling capacity.

Name: nuclearEngine
Title: NERVA I
Description: 1970s low TWR vacuum engine. the NERVA (Nuclear Engine for Rocket Vehicle Applications) is designed for orbital tugs and large rocket upper stages. Diameter: [1.25 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: nuclearfuel-0625
Title: MF-7 Nuclear Fuel Drum
Description: This tiny and somewhat shielded container is probably good for some small amount of nuclear fuel.

Name: nuclearfuel-125
Title: MF-4 Nuclear Fuel Drum
Description: A medium sized container for storing nuclear fuel and depleted waste products.

Name: nuclearfuel-25
Title: MF-1 Nuclear Fuel Drum
Description: A large container for storing nuclear waste and fuel.

Name: OCTOs0Adapter
Title: Octagonal 0.625m Adapter
Description: An adapter that seamlessly connects the Octagonal frame to the standard 0.625 rocket parts.

Name: OCTOServiceBay
Title: Service Bay (OCTO)
Description: A smaller version of the normal service bays, this one has an octagonal format and it is ideal for small probes.

Name: OCTOTank
Title: Octagonal Fuel Augmented Strut
Description: A Octagonal strut that contains a fuel tank, all fuel is inside the fuel tank, not on the exterior structure.

Name: ok_bo_fem
Title: Soyuz 7K-OK Orbital Module Drogue
Description: Orbital module for the 7K-OK. This is the drogue version, can only be docked to the 7k-ok probe orbital module.

Name: ok_bo_male
Title: Soyuz 7K-OK Orbital Module Probe
Description: Orbital module for the 7K-OK. This is the Probe version, can only be docked to the 7k-ok drogue orbital module.

Name: ok_dec
Title: Soyuz 7K Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for Soyuz 7K series service modules

Name: ok_hs
Title: Soyuz 7K series heatshield
Description: Heatshield for Soyuz 7K series

Name: ok_pao
Title: Soyuz 7K-OK Service Module
Description: Service module for 7k-ok Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ok_para
Title: Soyuz 7K Series Main Parachute
Description: Parachute for soyuz 7k series craft, attach on top side of descent module

Name: ok_sa
Title: Soyuz 7K series Descent Module
Description: Descent module for 7K series of soyuz. Works with both ok and t versions Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: ok_tft
Title: Soyuz 7K Toroidal Fuel Tank
Description: Empty Soyuz 7k series toroidal fuel tank. This attaches under the service module and should remain EMPTY. It was never used as it was intended for the moonshot.

Name: omsEngine
Title: AJ10-190
Description: Low thrust pressure-fed hypergolic engine. It was used on the Space Shuttle for orbital insertion, maneuvering and deorbiting. Currently used by the Orion MPCV. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: orbitaiespod
Title: AIES C1 'Orbiter'
Description: The Orbiter pod was initially of a conical design, but the early prototypes had problems with ergonomics for spaceship controls. The production version became more bulky and heavy, but at least you can operate the craft now.

Name: orbital-engine-0625
Title: LV-95 Orbital Maneuvering Engine
Description: The efficient LV-95 engine operates on a monopropellant fuel source, making it a versatile option for many applications. Comes in mounted and compact varieties. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbital-engine-125
Title: LV-601 Orbital Maneuvering Engine
Description: The high-efficiency LV-601 monopropellant engine is a versatile, well-balanced engine that will see great use in a variety of spacecraft. Comes in standard, compact and shrouded variants. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbital-engine-25
Title: LV-95-6 Orbital Maneuvering Engine Assembly
Description: This assembly contains six LV-95 engines surrounding a crew transfer tube. Integration of engine components allows increases in TWR over the basic single engine model. Can be configured with optional integrated fuel tankage. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbital-engine-375
Title: LV-601-4 Orbital Maneuvering Engine Cluster
Description: Four LV-601 engines are mounted together to make up this powerful cluster. Several variants are available: mounted, shrouded and compact. A set of small fuel tanks can also be added. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbitalEngine-0625
Title: LV-T95 Liquid Fuel Engine
Description: The efficient LV-T95 engine competes with the modern Rockomax 48-7S, and is suitable for both orbital and atmospheric propulsion with its high specific impulse. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbitalEngine-25
Title: LV-T95-8 Liquid Fuel Engine Assembly
Description: This assembly contains eight LV-T95 engines surrounding a crew transfer tube. Integration of engine components allows increases in thrust over the basic single engine model. Also integrated is a torroidal fuel tank with a moderate amount of rocket fuel. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbitalEngine-375
Title: LV-T18 Liquid Fuel Engine Cluster
Description: This upper stage engine packs quite a punch, with four LV-T18 engines boosting payloads at high efficiency in atmosphere and vacuum. It's so flat that we thought Bob sat on it, so it may be great for landers. Also included is a bit of fuel in those orange spheres. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: orbitalorbx
Title: TMA Orbital Orb
Description: A lightweight command and control module designed for on-orbit operations.

Name: OrbitalScanner
Title: M4435 Narrow-Band Scanner
Description: Ideal for surveying potential landing sites, this scanner provides detailed information about the planet or moon that it orbits, though this data is limited to the spot directly below the scanner. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: OrionDockingPort3a49capXx
Title: Orion Forward Heat Shield
Description: The forward heat shield and docking adapter base for the Orion EFT and MPCV command modules.

Name: OrionDockingPortXWSTANDARDDOCKPORT
Title: Orion MPCV Docking System
Description: The NASA docking system for the Orion MPCV Crew Module.

Name: OrionDockingPortXx
Title: Orion EFT LAS Decoupler
Description: The Launch Abort System (LAS) explosive bolt decoupler of the Orion EFT Crew Module.

Name: OscarAtank
Title: Oscar - A Propellant Tank
Description: The Oscar-A Fuel Tank from Probodobodyne is the smallest fuel container available for small space probes, for use with the tiniest of spaceships or as a large footstool.

Name: OscarDtank
Title: Oscar - C Propellant Tank
Description: The Oscar-C Fuel Tank from Probodobodyne is a medium-sized fuel container for small space probes, or a backup tank for other small spacecraft.

Name: OscarEtank
Title: Oscar - D Propellant Tank
Description: The Oscar-D Fuel Tank from Probodobodyne is the largest fuel container available for small space probes, or a backup tank for other small spacecraft.

Name: p1_decoupler
Title: Pioneer 0/1/2 Booster Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for top of pioneer 0/1/2. Attach to top and then attach 8 boosters to it.

Name: P5-2
Title: (stored in NearFuture Configs)
PLACEMENT NOTES: Higher thrust, better ISP = next era

Name: pam_d
Title: Magellan Star-48 SRM
Description: PAM-D Star-48 SRM for Magellan. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: PAPBarometer
Title: AIES P.A.P. Barometer
Description: Measures the pressure of the atmosphere. Surprise!

Name: parachuteDrogue
Title: Mk25 Parachute
Description: The Mk25 is what's known as a "Drogue" parachute - small, deploys high up, and certainly not enough to stop you smashing into the ground on its own, but useful for slowing heavy craft down before the deployment of your main chutes.

Name: parachuteLarge
Title: Mk16-XL Parachute
Description: The Mk16-XL Parachute is a double-sized variant of the Mk16, now with only 50% of the structural integrity!

Name: parachuteRadial
Title: Mk2-R Radial-Mount Parachute
Description: A parachute comparable to the Mk16 chute, but which is placed radially instead of attached on top of something.

Name: parachuteRadial_Drogue
Title: Mk5-R Radial-Mount Parachute *Outdated*
Description: A parachute comparable to the Mk25 drogue chute, but which is placed radially instead of attached on top of something. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: parachuteSingle
Title: Mk16 Parachute
Description: The Mk16 Parachute might be considered by some to be little more than a random stitching together of the surplus parts it is, in fact, made from. But the fact remains that the Mk16 has been widely accepted as a generally better alternative to being in freefall.

Name: parachuteSingle_drogue
Title: Mk26 Parachute
Description: The Mk26 Drogue chute is the smallest part of the 'Drogue' family, and is best used on either slowing larger ships or as a primary for very light vessels.

Name: ParaDockingPort
Title: Clamp-O-Tron MK 16-XXL Docking Port
Description: This is a modified Clamp-O-Tron Docking Port that combines all your favorite features and adds a parachute to boot, terrific. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RO BUT PLACED AND COSTED BY RP-0)

Name: PAYLOADADAPTER
Title: FB - Payload Attach Fitting - DCSS (4 m)
Description: The Payload Attach Fitting (PAF) is used for securing the spacecraft for the duration of the flight and separating it into the desired orbit. Sized for the 4 meter DCSS (1575-4 PAF).

Name: PAYLOADADAPTER2
Title: FB - Payload Attach Fitting - DCSS (5 m)
Description: The Payload Attach Fitting (PAF) is used for securing the spacecraft for the duration of the flight and separating it into the desired orbit. Sized for the 5 meter DCSS (1575-5 PAF).

Name: PAYLOADADAPTER2OPSX
Title: FB - Payload Attach Fitting - Base [Procedural]
Description: A generic payload attach fitting for mounting side fairings and payloads. Flat and raised surface that can be used for mounting additional hardware as required.

Name: PC_InflateHeatshield3HLxx
Title: CHAKA / Inflatable Heat Shield 2.7 (Extra LARGE)
Description: Remember to inflate before entry! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: PC_InflateHeatshieldLxx
Title: HIAD (20 m)
Description: The Hypersonic Inflatable Aerodynamic Decelerator (HIAD) consists of an inflatable main structure and the thermal protection system. The combination of the two creates a very light but extremely rugged aeroshell. Just remember to inflate it before entry.

Name: pCtrlSrf1
Title: Wing - Control Surface [Procedural]
Description: Control surface of unknown size, mass and other measurements as well.

Name: pioneer_0_1_2
Title: Pioneer 0/1/2
Description: Pioneer interplanetary probe 0/1/2 Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: pioneer_10_11
Title: Pioneer 10/11 Probe
Description: Pioneer 10/11 deep space probe

Name: pioneer_3_4
Title: Pioneer 3/4
Description: Pioneer interplanetary probe 3/4

Name: pioneer_5
Title: Pioneer 5
Description: Pioneer interplanetary probe 5

Name: pioneer_6_7_8_9
Title: Pioneer 6/7/8/9
Description: Pioneer interplanetary probe 6/7/8/9

Name: pioneer1_booster
Title: Pioneer 0/1/2 Top Boosters
Description: Pioneer 0/1/2 top booster block for Lunar orbital insertion. Place on top decoupler. Decouple once depleted. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: pit-0625
Title: KP-01 'Scintillator' Pulsed Inductive Thruster [Theoretical]
Description: A small inductive electric engine with a lot of magnets. Low power but good performance. Power input can be increased to boost the specific impulse, though this could also increase overheating.

Name: pit-125
Title: KP-XL 'Inductor' Pulsed Inductive Thruster [Theoretical]
Description: Kerbium engineers spent months working on the followup to the critically acclaimed KP-01. The KP-XL uses a patented "larger exhaust tube" principle and a ton more inductive coils. Not literally, it's more like 200 kilos. Has the same adjustable power capabilities as the previous model.

Name: pit-25
Title: KX-XK 'Repulsor' Pulsed Inductive Thruster [Theoretical]
Description: A large production-model pulsed inductive thruster, the KX-XK is a capable spacecraft main engine with variable power abilities. Kerbium used a palindromic designation in order to increase the quality and accuracy of their technical support calls. And yes, it is supposed to glow like that.

Name: PLE
Title: Phoenix Lander Engine (540N)
Description: A pair of MR-107 Monopropellant Engines, six of these pairs where used as retro-propulsion for the final decent phase of the Phoenix Mars Lander. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: plommsLandingLeg
Title: AIES PLOMM-S Landing
Description: Not the sturdiest landing strut, but is very compact when closed.

Name: pointyNoseConeA
Title: Advanced Nose Cone - Type A
Description: Less drag due to pointy shape.

Name: pointyNoseConeB
Title: Advanced Nose Cone - Type B
Description: Useful for boosters - the slanted shape is good for leading pressure away from the core stages.

Name: polyot
Title: Polyot
Description: Soviet Polyot anti-satellite Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: polyot_side_engine
Title: Polyot Side Engine
Description: Side translation engine for Polyot Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: PoodleM
Title: NT-5R "Shiba" Rocket Motor
Description: After a borrowing some plans from Jebediah Kerman's Junkyard and Spacecraft Parts Co., the Rockomax Conglomerate has entered the field of nuclear propulsion with this tiny little rocket nicknamed the "Shiba". The NT-5R Shiba has a much smaller profile than its predecessor, but is less efficient due to its smaller power source. Because the reactor is always active, it will constantly produce electricity as long as the engine isn't being fired. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: PotatoRoid
Title: A potato like rock
Description: Big ole, rock like thing. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: probeCoreCube
Title: Satellite Bus
Description: This satellite bus includes a small reaction wheel and a large omnidirectional antenna, and only the slightest power draw. Perfect for your geosynchronous satellites communications satellites. Includes data storage for returning data to Earth (use Ship Manifest to transfer the data from the experiment to this core).

Name: probeCoreHex
Title: Ranger Block III Core
Description: This automated control unit was originally developed for the NASA Ranger program. It is especially suited for lunar probes and flyby missions. Includes data storage for returning data to Earth (use Ship Manifest to transfer the data from the experiment to this core).

Name: probeCoreOcto
Title: (Deprecated) Surveyor Core
Description: Avionics and control unit for Surveyor landing probes. Includes data storage for returning data to Earth (use Ship Manifest to transfer the data from the experiment to this core).

Name: probeCoreOcto2
Title: (Deprecated) Early Controllable Core
Description: This relatively lightweight probe core allows early probes to be controlled during flight. However, it draws a fair amount of electricity for its abilities. Includes data storage for returning data to Earth (use Ship Manifest to transfer the data from the experiment to this core).

Name: probeCoreSphere
Title: Probodobodyne Stayputnik
Description: The Stayputnik offers the ultimate solution in crew safety. A lightweight sphere equipped with remote receivers and relay control input from the ground to the craft, it carries no crew at all, thus keeping them perfectly safe from all harm. This device does require electricity to operate however, and will cease to function if the power runs out. The built-in batteries should keep it going for about 10 minutes.

Name: probeStackLarge
Title: RC-L01 Remote Guidance Unit
Description: A larger version of the popular RGU system, developed in partnership with the Rockomax conglomerate.

Name: probeStackSmall
Title: RC-001S Remote Guidance Unit
Description: The STEADLER RGU core is one of the most complete command units available to date, featuring all the latest guidance systems, plus its own internal set of Reaction Wheels. STEADLER claims this is the closest one can get to a fully self-contained spacecraft. (Some assembly required. Spacecraft sold separately)

Name: ProceduralAllMovingWing
Title: Wing - Control Surface (Mark 1) [Procedural]
Description: Wing part of yet to be determined shape, size, mass and other measurements as well. Adjusts Orientation to allow you to control your craft.

Name: proceduralAvionics
Title: Avionics [Procedural]
Description: This is a procedural avionics unit.  It simply contains a battery and avionics control, so don't forget to add an antenna.

Name: proceduralBattery
Title: Battery [Procedural]
Description: With further refinements to procedural tech, we were able to fill a viscoelastic nanopolymer shell with electroactive particles. This gives you a battery able to be adapted to many shapes.

Name: proceduralCrewTube
Title: Crew Tube [Procedural]
Description: Air tight pressure hull protected by a thick layer of Kevlar and carbon nanofiber blankets to provide protection against micro-meteorites as well as thermal insulation and limited radiation shielding. These parts provide safe and structurally intact internal spaces to allow crew to move between crewed parts.

Name: proceduralHeatshield
Title: Heat Shield [Procedural]
Description: Made from viscoelastic nanopolymers (which were discovered by accident... growing in the back of the office mini-fridge) this ablative heat shield can be stretched to a range of sizes. Hardens to a rigid, heat resistant structure before launch! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0, RO IN PROGRESS)

Name: proceduralNoseCone
Title: Nose Cone [Procedural]
Description: Made from viscoelastic nanopolymers (which were discovered by accident... growing in the back of the office mini-fridge) this nose cone can be stretched to fit a range of diameters, and can be made more or less pointy. Hardens to a rigid structure before launch!

Name: proceduralSRBRealFuels
Title: Solid Rocket Motor [Procedural]
Description: Made from viscoelastic nanopolymers (which were discovered by accident... growing in the back of the office mini-fridge) this solid rocket can be stretched to accommodate fuel loads of a range of sizes and shapes. Can be optimized for sea-level or high altitude uses. Hardens to a rigid structure before launch! Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: proceduralStackDecoupler
Title: Decoupler [Procedural]
Description: Made from viscoelastic nanopolymers (which were discovered by accident... growing in the back of the office mini-fridge) this decoupler can be stretched to accommodate a range of sizes.

Name: proceduralStructural
Title: Structure [Procedural]
Description: Made from viscoelastic nanopolymers (which were discovered by accident... growing in the back of the office mini-fridge) this structural element can be stretched to range of sizes and shapes. Hardens to a rigid structure before launch!

Name: proceduralTankOre
Title: Tank - Ore [Procedural]
Description: Made from viscoelastic nanopolymers (which were discovered by accident... growing in the back of the office mini-fridge) this fuel tank can be stretched to accommodate ore in a range of sizes and shapes. Hardens to a rigid structure before launch!

Name: proceduralTankRealFuels
Title: Tank [Procedural]
Description: Switchable procedural tank. Comes in various levels of insulation, rigid/balloon, and pressurized/highly-pressurized forms. Defaults to type Default but can be switched to other types in the part popup menu.

Name: Proceduralwing2
Title: Wing [Procedural]
Description: Wing part of yet to be determined shape, size, mass and other measurements aswell.

Name: Proceduralwing2EndPiece
Title: Wing - (Mark 2) [Procedural]
Description: Wing part of yet to be determined shape, size, mass and other measurements aswell, this one is rounder than the others.

Name: Proceduralwing4
Title: Wing [Procedural]
Description: Wing part of yet to be determined shape, size, mass and other measurements aswell.

Name: ProceduralwingBac9
Title: Wing - (B9 SH) [Procedural]
Description: Wing part of yet to be determined shape, size, mass and other measurements as well. The results of many years of mutual industrial espionage / cooperation.

Name: ProceduralwingSPP
Title: Wing [Procedural]
Description: Wing part of yet to be determined shape, size, mass and other measurements as well. The results of many years of mutual industrial espionage / cooperation.

Name: PROGRESS
Title: Progress M/MM/MS Cargo and Refueling Module
Description: The primary cargo transfer module of the Progress spacecraft. It can carry propellant, equipment and life support consumables. It also contains the control systems of the spacecraft.

Name: PROGRESS_FG1
Title: Soyuz-U Progress Payload Fairing
Description: A payload fairing designed specifically for the Progress resupply spacecraft.

Name: quetzal
Title: Pioneer 10/11 Core
Description: Avionics and control unit for the Pioneer deep space probes.

Name: R_40B_4kN
Title: R-40B Bipropellant Engine
Description: The R-40B bipropellant Engine is designed for apogee orbit injection of geostationary satellites and for trajectory and planetary orbit manoeuvres of deep space probes. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_BLOCK_I
Title: Soyuz FG/U/ST Block I
Description: The Block I third stage is the most commonly used upper stage for the Soyuz launch vehicle. It can be fitted with either the RD-0110 engine or the newer RD-0124. It has a special liquid oxygen vent nozzle designed to put it into a tumble so that it doesn't collide with the payload after separation. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_Booster_Engine
Title: RD-107 Series
Description: Booster engine for the R-7 Semyorka and its derivatives, including the Sputnik, Luna, Voskhod, Vostok, Soyuz, and Molniya launch vehicles. Differs from the core engine series (RD-108) with a higher chamber pressure, thrust, and smaller vernier layout. The R-7 family core was supplemented for (roughly) two minutes by four strap-on boosters powered by these engines. Diameter: [1.85 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_Core_Engine
Title: RD-108 Series
Description: Core engine for the R-7 Semyorka and its derivatives, including the Sputnik, Luna, Voskhod, Vostok, Soyuz, and Molniya launch vehicles.  Differs from the booster engine series (RD-107) with a lower chamber pressure, thrust, and a wider vernier layout.  Powers the R-7 family core through a very long (roughly) five minute burn that starts on the pad alongside the boosters. Diameter: [1.85 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_FIRST_STAGE
Title: Soyuz FG/U/ST Booster
Description: One of the oldest parts of the R7 launch vehicle series, the strap - on booster was designed to support the core stage both in flight and on the ground. The individual boosters are designated as Blocks B,V,G and D and each one is powered by the RD-107 engine. It is ignited on the ground along with the second (core booster) stage. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_FIRST_STAGE_DECOUPLER
Title: Soyuz FG/U Booster Decoupler
Description: A small element that connects the R7 first stage to the second.

Name: R7_FS_TOP
Title: Soyuz FG/U/ST Booster LOX Valve (Top)
Description: A small dump valve that allows the venting of the liquid oxygen tank residuals to aid in booster separation. Place it at the top of the strap - on booster. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_RETRO_MOTOR
Title: Soyuz FG/U/ST Booster LOX Valve (Bottom)
Description: A small dump valve that allows the venting of the liquid oxygen tank residuals to aid in booster separation. Place it at the bottom of the strap - on booster. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R7_SECOND_STAGE
Title: Soyuz FG/U/ST Core Stage
Description: The Block A is one of the few parts that still remain mostly unchanged from the original R7 design. A very reliable element, powered by a single RD-108 engine with four verniers for attitude control. It is ignited on the ground along with the strap - on boosters. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: R8winglet
Title: AV-R8 Winglet
Description: The R8 Active Control Winglet series marked the debut of Kerlington Model Rockets in the Spacecraft engineering world. These winglets are equipped with movable pivots, which allow them to swivel and act as control surfaces. This feature was considered a huge advancement in control technology and most agree that it made Kerlington staff and R8 fans simply unbearable to be around.

Name: RadialavionicsHub

Description: The CH-R1 Avionics Module includes all the required communications and control circuitry for remote control of a craft, be it crewed or uncrewed. Radially mounted for easier placement.

Name: radialDecoupler
