Name: RSBtankAresIstage2
Title: Ares I Upper Stage
Description: The second stage of the Ares I rocket, originally designed for use by the NASA Constellation program as a crew launch vehicle.

Name: RSBtankArianeVcore
Title: Ariane 5 EPC-E
Description: The evolved cryogenic main stage of the Ariane 5 launch vehicle.

Name: RSBtankArianeVescA
Title: Ariane 5 ESC-A
Description: The second stage of the Ariane 5 launch vehicle family (ESC-A variant). Contains guidance capability.

Name: RSBtankAtlasCentaur
Title: Common Centaur
Description: The second stage of an Atlas V. Contains the necessary avionics, communications and power supply for mission times of up to 6 hours.

Name: RSBtankAtlasVcore
Title: Atlas V Common Core Booster
Description: This common booster core can either function as a single core, or center core, or strap-on booster. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RSBtankDelta2K
Title: Delta-K Upper Stage
Description: The second stage of a Delta II. Contains guidance capability.

Name: RSBtankDelta2thor
Title: Delta II EELT
Description: The Extra Extended Long Tank (EELT) for the Delta II 6000 and 7000 series launch vehicle families. Else known as the Thor 8000 series.

Name: RSBtankDelta3dcss4m
Title: Delta Cryogenic Second Stage 4M (Delta III)
Description: The Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS) used on the Delta III launch vehicle. Contains guidance capability.

Name: RSBtankDelta3thor
Title: Delta III EELT
Description: The first stage of the Delta III launch vehicle, based on the Delta II's Extra Extended Long Tank structure (Thor 8000 series).

Name: RSBtankDeltaIVcore
Title: Delta IV Common Booster Core
Description: The common booster for the Delta IV launch vehicle. Can be used alone, with SRM augmentation or as a separate strap-on booster.

Name: RSBtankDeltaIVdcss4m
Title: Delta Cryogenic Second Stage 4M (Delta IV)
Description: The 4 meter variant of the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS-4) used on the Delta IV Medium 4, 4+ and 5+. Contains guidance capability.

Name: RSBtankDeltaIVdcss5m
Title: Delta Cryogenic Second Stage 5M (Delta IV)
Description: The 5 meter variant of the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS-5). Contains guidance capability.

Name: RSBtankPSLVps2
Title: PSLV PS2 Propellant Tank
Description: The propellant tank of the Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle second stage.

Name: RSBtankPSLVps4
Title: PSLV PS4
Description: The fourth stage of the Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle (PSLV) designated as PS4. Equipped with guidance capability and small attachment points for secondary cubesat payloads. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RSBtankSaturn10m6m
Title: Saturn 10m to 6.6m Fueled Adapter
Description: A general purpose conical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSaturn10m7m
Title: Saturn 10m to 7.5m Fueled Adapter
Description: A general purpose conical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSaturn6m5m
Title: Saturn 6.6m to 5m Fueled Adapter
Description: A general purpose conical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIB
Title: Saturn S-I/IB Propellant Tank
Description: The first stage propellant tank for the Saturn I and IB.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIC
Title: Saturn V S-IC Propellant Tank
Description: The first stage of the Saturn V. Includes explosive bolts for separation in the forward skirt. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIC8
Title: Saturn C-8 S-IC-8 Propellant Tank
Description: The first stage of the Saturn C-8 (sometimes referred to as Nova).

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIE
Title: Saturn IC S-IE Propellant Tank
Description: The first stage of the fictional Saturn IC, from the Eyes Turned Skyward universe.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIF
Title: Saturn Multibody S-IF Propellant Tank
Description: The first stage of the fictional Saturn Multibody, from the Eyes Turned Skyward universe.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSII
Title: Saturn V S-II Propellant Tank
Description: The second stage of the Saturn V. For engine restarts, eight ullage motors are recommended for this stage. Manufactured by North American Aviation.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSII8
Title: Saturn C-8 S-II Propellant Tank
Description: The propellant tank of the Saturn C-8 second stage. For engine restarts, eight ullage motors are recommended for this stage.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIV
Title: Saturn I S-IV Propellant Tank
Description: Second stage of the Saturn I. For engine restarts, ullage motors are recommended for this stage.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIVB
Title: Saturn IB/V S-IVB Propellant Tank
Description: The third stage of the Saturn V. For engine restarts, two to three ullage motors are recommended for this stage. Manufactured by Douglas Aircraft Company.

Name: RSBtankSaturnSIVC
Title: Saturn Multibody S-IVC Propellant Tank
Description: The upper stage of the fictional Saturn Multibody configurations from the Eyes Turned Skyward alternate history. Typically used with a pair of J-2 engines.

Name: RSBtankSpehereAgena
Title: Spherical Tank (Agena)
Description: A general purpose spherical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSphereCentaur
Title: Spherical Tank (Centaur)
Description: A general purpose spherical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSphereDeltaIV
Title: Spherical Tank (DCSS)
Description: A general purpose spherical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSpherePSLV
Title: Spherical Tank (PSLV)
Description: A general purpose spherical propellant tank.

Name: RSBtankSTSET
Title: STS External Tank
Description: The external tank for the Space Shuttle (STS) or the DIRECT Jupiter.

Name: RSBtowerDelta
Title: Delta Fixed Umbilical Tower (FUT)
Description: The Delta II Fixed Umbilical Tower (FUT). Supplies all the required resources to the launch vehicle and it's payload.

Name: RSBtowerDelta2
Title: Delta Secondary Fixed Umbilical Tower (SFUT)
Description: Can be used in conjunction with the Delta II Fixed Umbilical Tower (FUT) to supply additional fuel and electricity as required.

Name: RSBullagePSLV
Title: PSLV Ullage Motor
Description: After stage separation, these ullage motors are used to generate a small amount of forward thrust to settle the contents of fuel tanks, prior to engine ignition. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RSBullageSaturnSII
Title: S-II Ullage Motor
Description: After stage separation, the Saturn's S-II stage needs ullage motors to provide a small amount of thrust, to settle the main fuels down into the fuel feeds. The S-II is usually equipped with four or eight of these. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RSBullageSaturnSIVB
Title: S-IVB Ullage Motor
Description: After stage separation, the Saturn's S-IVB stage needs ullage motors to provide a small amount of thrust, to settle the main fuels down into the fuel feeds. The S-IVB is usually equipped with two or three of these. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RT1
Title: Castor 4
Description: The Castor 4 was developed as the second stage of the Athena H missile and first flew in 1971. It was later adapted to replace Delta's Castor 2 boosters, increasing GTO capacity from 1593 lb (723 kg) to nearly 2000 lb (900 kg). The resulting Delta 3000-series launched in 1975 and was the first to adopt a staggered booster staging sequence. Previous Delta vehicles burned their motors in a 6-3 sequence and then jettisoned all SRMs at once. The heavier and longer-burning Castor 4 required that the ground-lit motors be jettisoned immediately after depletion to reduce dead weight. Early launches used a less efficient 5-4 sequence to reduce acceleration but returned to a 6-3 sequence after Delta was strengthened in the early 80s. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RT2
Title: Castor 2
Description: A derivative of the Castor 1 motor, the Castor 2 featured higher specific impulse and propellant load and lower dry mass fraction as well as a longer burn time. It was used as strap-on booster starting with Delta E and was also used in all but the early Scouts. Burn time 37s. Diameter: [0.79 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: rtg
Title: Multi-Hundred Watt RTG
Description: The Multihundred-Watt radioisotope thermoelectric generators (MHW-RTG) as found on the Voyager spacecraft and two Lincoln Experimental Satellites.

Name: rtg-0625
Title: NASA & DOE Advanced Sterling RG
Description: A much lighter and more efficient radioisotope generator by using the sterling cycle.

Name: RTGigaDish1
Title: Reflectron GX-128
Description: The folding mechanism doesn't really save mass. However, the huge 6.4m dish can provide a very decent data rate at comparatively little power. Effective range ~11 Tm, power consumption 80 Watts.

Name: RTGigaDish2
Title: Voyager Antenna
Description: Large dish suitable for deep-space missions well past Pluto; integrated circuitry largely makes up for the weight of the wider dish. Pretty good data rate. Effective range ~11 Tm, power consumption 240 Watts.

Name: rtgMini
Title: SNAP-3 Series RTG
Description: The SNAP-3 series were the first radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs) to ever operate in space, as part of the Transit system (precursor to the current GPS system). Very low overall efficiency and power generation.

Name: rtgMini
Title: PB-NUK-M Miniature RTG
Description: Through exploitation of the natural decay of Blutonium-238, this elegantly simple power generator can provide consistent, stable power for decades. Not to be used for providing heating during emergency rover excursions. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: RTLongAntenna2
Title: Communotron 32
Description: Using integrated circuits, the Communotron 32 outperforms its smaller sibling in any conceivable way, at comparable weight and power demands. Considerable range even when retracted, always on. Effective range 1.6 Gm, power consumption 15 Watts.

Name: RTLongAntenna3
Title: CommTech EXP-VR-2T
Description: CommTech EXP-VR-2T omnidirectional antenna: Effective range 1 Gm, power consumption 20 Watts.

Name: RTLongDish2
Title: Pioneer 10/11 Class Antenna
Description: Dish approximating those found on Pioneer 10/11; effective range ~1500Gm (good for Jupiter and beyond), high power demands at 160 Watts and comparatively low bandwidth.

Name: RTShortAntenna1
Title: Reflectron DP-10
Description: Omnidirectional antenna: Effective range 10 Mm, power consumption 5 Watts.

Name: RTShortDish2
Title: Reflectron KR-7
Description: An early, small high-gain antenna. Rather wide cone and high bandwidth for Comm satellites in GEO, live video from the Moon, and similar tasks. Effective range ~37 Gm, power consumption 50 Watts.

Name: Rutherford
Title: Rutherford
Description: The Rutherford Engine is the worlds first electric turbo-pumped LOX/RP-1 engine. Rutherford adopts an entirely new propulsion cycle, making use of brushless DC motors and high performance Lithium Polymer batteries to drive its turbo-pumps. The engine is named after the famous New Zealand born physicist Ernest Rutherford. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: RutherfordVacuum
Title: Rutherford Vacuum Engine
Description: The Rutherford Engine is the worlds first electric turbo-pumped LOX/RP-1 engine. Rutherford adopts an entirely new propulsion cycle, making use of brushless DC motors and high performance Lithium Polymer batteries to drive its turbo-pumps. The engine is named after the famous physicist Ernest Rutherford. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: S-3
Title: S-3
Description: Development version of the LR79 engine. Used on Thor R&D missiles.

Name: S-3D
Title: S-3D
Description: Production version of the LR79 engine, used on Thor and Jupiter.

Name: s1_dp
Title: Salyut 1/4 Docking Ring
Description: Docking port for salyut 1/4 station.

Name: s1_lsolar
Title: Salyut 1 Left Solar Array
Description: Salyut 1 series LEFT solar panels.

Name: s1_rsolar
Title: Salyut 1 Right Solar Array
Description: Salyut 1 series RIGHT solar panels.

Name: S10_Thruster
Title: S10 Bipropellant Thruster (10N)
Description: The S10 10N bipropellant thruster is a small rocket engine designed for both long term steady state and pulse mode operation. This engine is in service on board the LISA-Pathfinder experiment as well as the ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter.

Name: S10Block
Title: S10 Thruster Module (20N)
Description: The S10 Thruster Module comprises of two S10 thrusters in redundant configuration, ten of these modules provide three axis control for the ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter.

Name: S200_Block
Title: S200 ATV Aft Thruster Cluster
Description: The S200 ATV Aft Thruster Cluster was developed for attitude control, orbital manoeuvring and braking of ESA's Automated Transfer Vehicle (ATV). The thruster clusters deliver both steady state thrust and impulse bit and can also be used as back-up in the event of main engine failure.

Name: S200_Thruster
Title: S200 Bipropellant Thruster (200N)
Description: The S200 Bipropellant Thruster was developed for attitude control, orbital manoeuvring and braking of ESA's Automated Transfer Vehicle (ATV). The thruster has been selected to fly in the future NASA Programme ORION Multi Purpose Crew Vehicle, NASA's new spacecraft built to send humans further than ever before.

Name: S5_92fversion
Title: S5.92
Description: A gas generator cycle hypergolic vacuum engine. Used on the Fregat upper stage series. Diameter: 0.85 m. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: S5_98M
Title: S5.98M
Description: A staged combustion cycle hypergolic vacuum engine. Used on the Briz upper stage series. Diameter: 0.95 m. Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: s6_dp
Title: Salyut 6/7 Docking Ring
Description: Docking port for salyut 6/7 station. Attach one and top and bottom.

Name: saltguia
Title: AIES A1 'Saltguia' Laser
Description: Superior red beam projector. Used as a reference for approximation to ground when landing, especially when the place is very dark.

Name: salyut_asas
Title: Salyut ASAS
Description: Tiny ASAS for Salyut. Attach radially on the BOTTOM of the station main body. Allows the station to be controlled remotely for launch.

Name: salyut1-4
Title: Salyut 1/4
Description: Salyut 1 & 4 orbital laboratory. Salyut ASAS REQUIRED for station to function. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: salyut6
Title: Salyut 6
Description: Salyut 6 orbital laboratory. Salyut ASAS REQUIRED for station to function. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: salyut7
Title: Salyut 7
Description: Salyut 7 orbital laboratory. Salyut ASAS REQUIRED for station to function. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Sasdv4
Title: AIES DV4 - Advanced S.A.S
Description: A.S.A.S. module for large rockets with two pre-installed IK&K Labs 32A microprocessors!

Name: sasModule
Title: Small Inline Reaction Wheel
Description: Using a small electric motor, this reaction wheel lets probes and satellites adjust their attitudes without expending propellant.

Name: satpropt300FuelTank
Title: AIES T60 'SatProp' Fuel Tank
Description: After the satellite probes were designed a lot of golden tinfoil was left over. By using some metal boxes and battery parts this line of fuel tanks was created.

Name: SCANsat_Scanner
Title: SCAN RADAR Altimetry Sensor
Description: This radar set can provide low-resolution altimetry data. Best with low altitude orbits.

Name: SCANsat_Scanner2
Title: SCAN SAR Altimetry Sensor
Description: This Synthetic Aperture RADAR sensor uses its flight path to simulate a much larger antenna. This makes it possible to detect terrain elevation at much higher resolution. The downside is that its field of view is comparatively small, and it works better at higher altitudes. Min Alt: 10km, Max Alt: 8000km, Best Alt: 7500km, FOV: 2

Name: SCANsat_Scanner24
Title: SCAN Multispectral Sensor
Description: This multichannel sensor detects radiation across several infrared, visible light, and RADAR bands. This gives it the capability to differentiate between terrain types and biomes. It can also detect anomalies such as structures on the ground. Min Alt: 10km, Max Alt: 5000km, Best Alt: 2500km, FOV: 4

Name: SCANsat_Scanner32
Title: SCAN Anomaly Scanner
Description: This small sensor can automatically identify nearby anomalies. Since it only works over very short distances and at very low altitudes, it's primarily useful to track identified anomalies that have been visited. Min Alt: 0, Max Alt: 5km, Best Alt: 0, FOV: 1

Name: SCANsat_Tracker
Title: SCAN MapTraq
Description: Originally intended for the consumer market, this small device can communicate with a mapping satellite network and display a map and your position on it. Since nobody has actually built such a satellite network, these devices can currently be acquired very cheaply in bulk.

Name: science_module
Title: Early Film Camera
Description: The Early Film Camera is used to take photographs of Earth from space. This is a very early camera and lacks resolution in the images. Historically, these were flown on V-2 Rockets.\nThe photos cannot be transmitted and must be returned for further study. Level 1 Photograph Experiment. Can gather 20% of Photography Science. You can store up to 3 different photos before you need to return them to Earth.

Name: ScienceBox
Title: Experiment Storage Unit
Description: After discovering that old snack boxes were also really effective at storing mystery goo and data tapes, Kerbal scientists created the Experiment Storage Unit to help Kerbalnauts bring their valuable science back to Kerbin, while avoiding the hazards of reentry, rough landings, and Jeb's piloting skills. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: scout_stg1_dec
Title: Scout First Stage Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for first stage of the Scout rocket.

Name: scout_stg2_dec
Title: Scout second/third Stage Decoupler
Description: Decoupler for second/third and third/fourth stage of the Scout rocket.

Name: SDHIxADAPTERx
Title: FB - Payload Attach Fitting - Base (Expanded) [Procedural]
Description: A payload attach fitting for the Space Launch System payloads.

Name: SE_RWGS_10
Title: SE_RWGS_10
Description: Produces 5kg of total fuel per solar day, 10kg if run through the night. 7.67L LH2, 5.11L LCH4, 6.86L LO2 per day.

Name: SE_RWGS_100
Title: SE_RWGS_100
Description: Produces 50kg of total fuel per solar day, 100kg if run through the night. 76.7L LH2, 51.1L LCH4, 68.6L LO2 per day.

Name: SE_RWGS_1000
Title: SE_RWGS_1000
Description: Produces 500kg of total fuel per solar day, 1000kg if run through the night. 767L LH2, 511L LCH4, 686L LO2 per day.

Name: seatExternalCmd
Title: EAS-1 External Command Seat
Description: The EAS-1 External Command Seat provides all the controls needed to fully operate a spacecraft, just like a command pod, but without such needless frivolities as "pressurized interiors", or "seat belts". It's bare-bones, pedal-to-the-metal efficiency at its finest.

Name: sensorAccelerometer
Title: Double-C Seismic Accelerometer
Description: This device contains an extremely sensitive acceleration sensor, which when properly settled on a firm surface, will detect and record accurate seismic activity data. The accelerometer will still function while flying, so the Double-C can also be used to measure accelerations during flight. Warranty void if shaken or exposed to vacuum.

Name: sensorAtmosphere
Title: Gas Chromatograph-Mass Spectrometer (GC/MS)
Description: The Gas Chromatograph-Mass Spectrometer (GC-MS) is an analytical instrument used for identification of multiple different substances in a selected gas sample, capable of detecting even trace amounts of them. Ideal of analyzing the atmospheric composition of unknown environments. Mass spectrometry is an analytical technique that ionizes chemical species and sorts the ions based on their mass-to-charge ratio. Historically, these simple experiments were flown on interplanetary crafts including the Mars Viking Lander and Cassini.\nLevel 4 Mass Spectrometry Experiment Device. Can gather 100% of Mass Spectrometry Science.

Name: sensorBarometer
Title: Barometer
Description: A device for measuring the local atmospheric pressure. Warranty void if exposed to air.

Name: sensorGravimeter
Title: Orbital Perturbation Experiment
Description: Using radar and signals tracking from the surface, and alignment checks from the spacecraft, a detailed map of the orbital perturbation encountered by the spacecraft can be compiled, leading to knowledge about the various concentrations of mass on the body it orbits.

Name: sensorThermometer
Title: Thermometer
Description: This thermometer is definetely not a store-bought model with some wires stuck to it. Warranty void if an engineer admits it's actually a store-bought model with some wires stuck to it.

Name: Separatormultifs
Title: AIES Multi-FS Separator
Description: Multi-FS system allows a nice, clean separation of two parts. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: sepMotor1
Title: Separation Motor (Medium)
Description: Small solid motor use to help separate one stage from another or perform ullage. Best used with others. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: sepMotorLarge
Title: Separation Motor (Large)
Description: Larger solid motor use to help separate one stage from another or perform ullage. Best used with others.

Name: ServiceBay_125
Title: Service Bay [2m]
Description: Service bay for protecting small delicate instruments during spaceflight. Note: must be shielded for reentry, bay itself is delicate too.

Name: ServiceBay_250
Title: Service Bay [4m]
Description: Service bay for protecting small delicate instruments during spaceflight. Note: must be shielded for reentry, bay itself is delicate too.

Name: servicetank-25
Title: FL-T6000 Service Tank
Description: This multifunction fuel tank stores a respectable amount of rocket fuel, some monopropellant and even includes a cargo compartment for stowage of snacks and other sundries. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: servicetank-375
Title: FL-T9000 Service Tank
Description: This tank is pretty low profile and... hang on, the tank only takes up about half the space in here! We can totally fit some extra things in this service bay, where they might not catch fire! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SHABLANDER-SLRx32af
Title: CHAKA / HAB SLR Max Expanded Composite
Description: This is the largest rigid monkey hab designed to be landed on Duna or Mun. Contains Monkey Snaxx (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SHABLANDER-SLRx32xa4e
Title: CHAKA / HAB SLR Lander Composite
Description: This is the largest rigid monkey hab designed to be landed on Duna or Mun. Contains Monkey Snaxx (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: ShieldCapLarge
Title: Mk2 Pod Protective Cover
Description: Aerodynamic cover for the Mk2 Command Module. Provides protection from the aerodynamic forces inside the dense parts of the atmosphere and from the LES exhaust in the case of an emergency.

Name: SHIP_ABLE
Title: Able
Description: Able upper stage as used on the Thor/Able launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_ABLESTAR
Title: Able-Star
Description: Able-Star upper stage as used on the Thor/Able-Star launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_AJ_10_101_104
Title: AJ-10 101/104
Description: Flown on the Able, and AbleStar upper stages. Use the 10-101 with the Able upper stage, and the 10-104 with the AbleStar upper stage.

Name: SHIP_CENTAUR_G
Title: Centaur G
Description: Centaur upper stage used with the STS. Configured for longer payloads.

Name: SHIP_CENTAUR_GP
Title: Centaur G Prime
Description: Centaur upper stage modified for use with the STS.

Name: SHIP_CENTAUR_T
Title: Centaur T
Description: Centaur upper stage for Titan launch vehicles.

Name: SHIP_E1
Title: E-1
Description: Pump-fed kerolox open cycle (gas generator) booster engine developed from LR79/89. Backup proposal for the first stage engine on the Titan 1 ICBM, and proposed first stage engine on the Saturn 1 but ultimately never flown (4 E-1s replaced with 8 H-1s). Diameter: [2.14 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SHIP_HG_3_SL
Title: HG-3
Description: High pressure engine developed from the J-2. This version is for sea level applications. Theoretical upgrades are included.

Name: SHIP_HG_3_VAC
Title: HG-3
Description: High pressure engine developed from the J-2. This version is for vacum level applications.

Name: SHIP_LR_71
Title: LR-79 Series
Description: Engine used in a variety of launch vehicles, most notibly the Thor/Delta

Name: SHIP_LR_87_11
Title: LR-87-11
Description: The main engine block for the IV launch vehicles. 1.93 O/F Ratio.

Name: SHIP_LR_87_3579
Title: LR-87-3, 5, 7, 9
Description: The main engine block for the I/II/III launch vehicles.

Name: SHIP_LR_87_LH2
Title: LR-87-LH2
Description: The main engine block for the I/II/III launch vehicles.

Name: SHIP_LR_91
Title: LR-91 Series
Description: Upper stage engine for the Titan II/III/IV launch vehicles, with thrust plate.  1.79 O/F Ratio.

Name: SHIP_THOR_PGM_TANK
Title: THOR DM-19
Description: This stage is based on the Thor PGM, and used in the first stage of several launch vehicles. Later modified for the Delta series of lanchers.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_A_1
Title: Titan III A-1
Description: This is the first stage of the TITAN IIIC and IIIE launch vehicles.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_B_1
Title: Titan III B-1
Description: This is the first stage of the TITAN 34D launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_B_1_B
Title: Titan III B-1-B
Description: This is the first stage of the TITAN IIIB launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_B_1_C
Title: Titan III B-1 Commercial
Description: This is the first stage of the TITAN III Commercial launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_III_A_2
Title: Titan III A-2
Description: This is the second stage of the TITAN IIIC and IIIE launch vehicles.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_III_A_2B
Title: Titan III A-2-B
Description: This is the second stage of the TITAN IIIB Agena launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_III_B_2
Title: Titan III B-2
Description: This is the second stage of the TITAN 34D, as well as the TITAN IIIB.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_III_B_2_C
Title: Titan III B-2 Commercial
Description: This fuel tank was flown on the second stage of the TITAN III Commercial launch vehicle.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_IV_MainTank
Title: Titan IV 4-1
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the lower stage in Titan IV series builds.

Name: SHIP_TITAN_IV_UpperTank
Title: Titan IV 4-2
Description: This fuel tank can be used for the second stage in Titan IV series builds.

Name: shockConeIntake
Title: Shock Cone Intake
Description: A shocking new intake from the C7 Aerospace Division that brought you much adored parts such as the Delta Wing and the Standard Nosecone! Offers exceptional performance at all speeds and has some heat shielding of its own.

Name: shortDecoupler1-2
Title: Shorter Rockomax Brand Decoupler
Description: After receiving complaints that their previous product was far too tall, Rockomax Conglomerate created a shorter variant, letting the Rockomax Conglomerate avoid the inevitable lawsuits from rocket builders everywhere.

Name: size0PulseJet
Title: J-10 "Rattler" Pulse Jet Engine
Description: A Heavily modified version of an enthusiast grade pulse jet engine, it provides a surprisingly high Thrust to weight ratio in addition to a lightning quick spool up time, unfortunately it drains your fuel faster than any other jet. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Size2LFB
Title: Pyrios Booster
Description: An 18-foot diameter liquid fuel booster employing two F-1B engines built for cost efficiency. Dynetics teaming with Pratt & Whitney Rocketdyne. [5.5 m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Size2MedEngine
Title: RD-108 Series
Description: Core engine for the R-7 Semyorka and its derivatives, including the Sputnik, Luna, Voskhod, Vostok, Soyuz, and Molniya launch vehicles.  Differs from the booster engine series (RD-107) with a lower chamber pressure, thrust, and a wider vernier layout.  Powers the R-7 family core through a very long (roughly) five minute burn that starts on the pad alongside the boosters. Diameter: [1.85 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: size2nuclearEngine
Title: RE-N4 "Nova" Atomic Rocket Motor
Description: Rejoice! The glorious Rockomax Conglomerate has created the biggest and safest Nuclear rocket motor in existence! With a revolutionary design that passes the fuel over the reactor, instead of through it, The risk of radioactive exhaust is now (nearly) non-existant! Now no Kerbal has to worry about that pesky radiation! Plume configured by RealPlume. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Size3AdvancedEngine
Title: F-1 Series
Description: The massive Rocketdyne F-1 engine. One of the largest, most powerful rocket engines ever built. Ensure you enable roll capability or disable gimbal as required for your application. Diameter: [3.61 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: size3Decoupler
Title: TR-38-D
Description: Originally designed to separate buildings that were stuck together, O.M.B has repurposed these explosive bolts for use in separating stacks of massive rockets.

Name: Size3EngineCluster
Title: RS-25D/E 4 Engine mount
Description: Engine core for the Space Launch System (SLS). Features four Rocketdyne RS-25D/E engines. [8.4 m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Size3LargeTank
Title: Space Launch System Main Fuel Tank
Description: Taking the stock large tank, adding some more tanks to it and presto, the main tank for the Space Launch System.

Name: Size3MediumTank
Title: Kerbodyne S3-7200 Tank
Description: Kerbodyne's signature heavy fuel tank. Designed to be used with their advanced rocket engines.

Name: size3ReactionWheel
Title: XL Advanced Reaction Wheel
Description: A reaction control device made to fit within the 3.75 meter size range. Fastening bolts not included. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Size3SmallTank
Title: Kerbodyne S3-3600 Tank
Description: A half-capacity version of Kerbodyne's iconic fuel tank, for not quite exactly half the cost.

Name: Size3to2Adapter
Title: Kerbodyne ADTP-2-3
Description: This adapter is used to bridge between Kerbodyne and Rockomax rocket bodies.

Name: skylab
Title: Skylab
Description: Skylab orbital laboratory

Name: skylab_asas
Title: Skylab ASAS
Description: Tiny ASAS for Skylab. Attach radially on the BOTTOM of the station main body. Allows the station to be controlled remotely for launch. DO NOT ATTACH TO THE MICROMETEORITE SHIELDS OR IT WILL FALL OFF DURING LAUNCH.

Name: skylab_trs_docking
Title: Skylab TRS Docking Probe
Description: Skylab TRS docking port. Attach one of these to the top of the TRS module.

Name: skylab-trs
Title: Teleoperator Retrieval System
Description: TRS re-boost module for Skylab. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: sl_left_panel
Title: Skylab Left Solar Panel
Description: Left solar panel for Skylab. Can be detached for realistic Skylab or kept on for the unbroken version of the station. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: sl_right_panel
Title: Skylab Right Solar Panel
Description: Right solar panel for Skylab

Name: SLS_CM_FairingAdapter296
Title: Interstage Adapter - SLS Block I
Description: The structural adapter and explosive cord decoupler for the Interim Cryogenic Second Stage (ICPS).

Name: SLS_CM_FairingAdapter296-EM2
Title: CHAKA / SLS EM-2 Adapter for Orion
Description: The SLS-TF is equipped with a (hopefully) small explosive charge, that will sever the structural linkage between itself and whatever it's connected to. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SLS_CM_FairingAdapterBLOCK1B96
Title: SLS Block IB Orion Adapter
Description: A structural adapter for mounting the Orion MPCV on the Exploration Upper Stage. Allows for dual - manifested payloads.

Name: SLS_CM_stackDecouplerx30
Title: Orion - DCSS Adapter
Description: A structural adapter for mounting the Orion service module payload attach fitting to the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS). Does not include a decoupler!

Name: smallCtrlSrf
Title: Elevon 4
Description: Feel the need to attach an elevator, rudder or aileron to just about any surface you can get your mitts on? Well this small elevon is for you. Made of mostly new factory parts, it will fit just about anywhere. Just don't expect a huge performance out of such a small part.

Name: SmallFixedAntenna
Title: Comms DTS-M5 *Outdated*
Description: The DTS-M5 is a fixed, stack mounted solution to your communications needs. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SmallGearBay
Title: LY-10 Small Landing Gear
Description: High performance retractable landing gear. Comes with shock absorber, steering and a built-in spotlights. If we didn't tell you, you'd never know that most of those components were salvaged from scrapped machinery... oh.

Name: smallHardpoint
Title: Small Hardpoint
Description: A structural Pylon for engine Support. Designed to fit against fuselages, and hull bodies. This is the small variant, mostly for use with the smaller engines. Comes Equipped with emergency bolts to separate jet engines in the event of fire or catastrophic failure. (Not covered by warranty)

Name: SmallInflatableHAB
Title: IKU-02 Kerbal Safety Bubble
Description: One of the smaller crew storage solutions available to any space program, the IKU-02 is able to inflate to nearly triple it's initial size, letting it pack in a total of 2 kerbals. If it isn't inflated, however... let's just say that they'll have very little to no room to do anything. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: smallISRU
Title: Convert-O-Tron MINI-M
Description: A smaller version of Kerbodyne's mobile processing plant, this module can take raw materials containing even trace amounts of oxygen and hydrogen, and crack them into useful fuel products.  When operated by a skilled engineer, you will be able to operate with better efficiency.  This oddly shaped processor manufactures mono-propellant and nothing else, but is much lighter and smaller than the more versatile Convert-O-Tron 125. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SmallPointLight
Title: MK 4 Point Light
Description: A small lamp made to light up everything, weather you like it or not.

Name: smallRadialDecoupler
Title: TR-8A Radial Decoupler
Description: A small radial decoupler.

Name: smallRadialEngine
Title: RD-856 [Radial]
Description: Vernier thruster used on the second stage of the Tsyklon rocket. Diameter: [0.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SmallSpotLight
Title: MK 3 Mini Spotlight
Description: A miniature version of the large MK1 spotlight that's perfect for small rovers; or for the more adventurous, a large headlamp.

Name: SmallStripLight
Title: MK 5 Strip Light
Description: A small Strip light ideally used as aircraft navigation lights, but we can't stop you from trying to light up your house with em', because you will fail. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RO BUT PLACED AND COSTED BY RP-0)

Name: SmallTank
Title: Small Holding Tank
Description: A small tank for storing raw materials, or possibly spare snacks. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SMLadderUtility
Title: MK I Mobility Enhancer
Description: The MK I Mobility Enhancer, known in some circles as a "ladder", is a state-of-the-art vertical mobility device, allowing your intrepid crew to scamper around the exterior of your ship like highly caffeinated rodents.

Name: SNTPPFE100
Title: LV-NSNTP-PFE100 "Partial Flow Expander Cycle Space Nuclear Thermal Propulsion" Atomic Rocket Motor

Name: SnubOtron
Title: Separation Motor (Small)
Description: Small solid motor use to help separate one stage from another or perform ullage. Best used with others. Smaller and less advanced than the radial separation motor. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: softTankMK1
Title: Rockomax MK1 SoftShell LF tank
Description: This product is the result of a travelling vacuum saleskerbal's bright Idea, by removing most of the structural supports and thermal insulation, the tanks is much lighter and cheaper, but it can be torn in two by a single drifting Kerbal who's out of EVA propellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: softTankMK2
Title: Rockomax MK2 SoftShell LF tank
Description: This product is the result of a travelling vacuum saleskerbal's bright Idea, by removing most of the structural supports and thermal insulation, the tanks is much lighter and cheaper, but it can be torn in two by a single drifting Kerbal who's out of EVA propellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: softTankMK3
Title: Rockomax MK3 SoftShell LF tank
Description: This product is the result of a travelling vacuum saleskerbal's bright Idea, by removing most of the structural supports and thermal insulation, the tanks is much lighter and cheaper, but it can be torn in two by a single drifting Kerbal who's out of EVA propellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: softTankMK4
Title: Rockomax MK4 SoftShell LF tank
Description: This product is the result of a travelling vacuum saleskerbal's bright Idea, by removing most of the structural supports and thermal insulation, the tanks is much lighter and cheaper, but it can be torn in two by a single drifting Kerbal who's out of EVA propellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: softTankMK5
Title: Rockomax MK5 SoftShell LF tank
Description: This product is the result of a travelling vacuum saleskerbal's bright Idea, by removing most of the structural supports and thermal insulation, the tanks is much lighter and cheaper, but it can be torn in two by a single drifting Kerbal who's out of EVA propellant. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: solarpanel-blanket-1
Title: OKEB-500 Blanket Photovoltaic Array
Description: OKEB offers a new take on solar arrays - really, really big. Their first entry into the market dwarfs even Kerb Kastria Inc.'s Megalador panel. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 420m^2.

Name: solarpanel-blanket-2
Title: OKEB-100 Blanket Photovoltaic Array
Description: OKEB's smaller sized panel set is still quite large! Uses the latest state of the art technology. 73.125m^2.

Name: solarpanel-curved-25-1
Title: NIV-18 Curved Solar Array
Description: Might as well wrap a solar panel around your tank. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 2.823m^2.

Name: solarpanel-curved-375-1
Title: NIV-3 Curved Solar Array
Description: Might as well wrap a solar panel around your tank. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 0.675m^2.

Name: solarpanel-curved-deploying-25-1
Title: SOL-A Expanding Curved Solar Array
Description: Might as well wrap a solar panel around your tank. This one expands out for more area. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 1.2885m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-1x3-1
Title: KRX 1x3 Concentrating Photovoltaic Panels
Description: As a follow up to the underwhelmingly popular 1x4 series, the KRX also includes concentrator lenses for extra power at the cost of mass. On the KRX, support struts are sacrificed to cut down that mass, the result is a panel that is quite light for its generation capabilities. Just don't sneeze on it. 1.44m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-1x4-1
Title: KRK 1x4 Concentrating Photovoltaic Panels
Description: Kerb Kastria's solar panel offering includes special lenses that concentrate sunlight onto fewer, stronger solar cells. This increases power density by almost 50%, but also increases panel mass. 2.5m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-1x4-2
Title: KRQ 1x4 High-Efficiency Photovoltaic Panels
Description: The most advanced solar panel technologies available of all kinds! This panel improves on concentrator lenses by incorporating much more sensitive photodiodes. Do you really need to look at the price tag? Studies disagree. 3.2m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-1x5-1
Title: T65 1x5 Concentrating Photovoltaic Panels
Description: This versatile light panel provides a moderate amount of power without breaking the bank, or the back of the Kerbals assigned to carry it. It's a win-win for Finance and HR! 5.25m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-1x5-2
Title: T225 1x5 Concentrating Photovoltaic Panels
Description: A bendier but larger version of the T65, the KEDY engineers have created this largish panel set for those power-hungry governments and spacecraft out there. 7.875m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-2x1-1
Title: KR-XL Megalador Concentrating Solar Array
Description: Disputing the Gigantor-XL's claim of 'single largest solar array available', the Megalador is large and unwieldy - but, if you can get past all that, is packed with loads of advanced solar cells. 24m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-2x1-2
Title: KR-SL Solo Concentrating Solar Array
Description: A compact, pared down (with shears!) version of the Trio without some of that finnecky extension gear. Comes in a box advertising something about the odds, and how you shouldn't worry about them or even mention them. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 25.875m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-2x3-1
Title: KR-ML Trio Concentrating Solar Array
Description: A slightly heavy alternative to the Megalador, the Trio mounts a trio of paired solar panels for efficient generation. Tradeoffs include a more fragile structure and a larger undeployed footprint. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 32.625m^2.

Name: solarpanel-deploying-circular-1
Title: YF-1 Circular Concentrating Photovoltaic Array
Description: Now this is efficient use of space. Build a circular retracting, folding, sun tracking solar panel. Uses the latest state of the art technology. 3.14m^2.

Name: solarpanel-static-truss-1
Title: PX-STAT 1x4 Photovoltaic Truss
Description: Two sections of 2 truss segments all welded together? Double the madness! 2.88m^2.

Name: solarpanel-static-truss-2
Title: PX-STAT 1x2 Photovoltaic Truss
Description: Two truss segments welded together? Madness! 1.44m^2.

Name: solarpaneles1
Title: AIES ES-1B Solar Panel
Description: A little over two times bigger than the ST1 plus the latest state of the art technology, the ES1B gives the user that much more capability. 0.455m^2.

Name: solarPanels1
Title: XT2 Solar Panel Array Mk2
Description: Shielded extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel. 1.5m^2.

Name: solarPanels2
Title: XT2 Solar Panel Array Mk1
Description: Shielded extendable sun-tracking Level 2 solar panel. 1.5m^2.

Name: solarPanels3
Title: XT1 Solar Panel Array Mk2
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel. 0.96m^2.

Name: solarPanels4
Title: XT1 Solar Panel Array Mk1
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 2 solar panel. 0.96m^2.

Name: solarPanels5
Title: ST1 Solar Panel
Description: Static Level 1 solar panel. 0.25m^2.

Name: solarPanels5HiTech
Title: ST2 Solar Panel
Description: Static Level 2 solar panel. 0.2m^2.

Name: solarPanels6
Title: HAB - ST6 Solar Array
Description: Level 6 static solar array. 4.5 m2.

Name: solarPanelsfa
Title: AIES SFA Solar panel
Description: Making things bigger only helps if you can make them more compact for launch...so fold things up. 1.8m^2.

Name: solarPanelsfa2
Title: AIES SunCat-2B Solar Panel
Description: The newest technology and folding for compact, narrow storage for launch. 1.725m^2.

Name: solarPanelsond1
Title: AIES SON-D1 Solar Panel
Description: Slightly larger than the ST1 (1.5x) but the newest technology and folding for compact, narrow storage for launch. 0.33m^2.

Name: solarPanelsuncat1
Title: AIES SunCat-1B Solar Panel
Description: The newest technology and folding for compact, narrow storage for launch. 0.8625m^2.

Name: solidBooster
Title: Castor 30XL
Description: The Castor 30XL is an enlarged Castor 30. Designed for the second stage of the Antares launcher. Diameter: [2.34 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: solidBooster_sm
Title: Star 48B
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: solidBooster1-1
Title: Castor 120
Description: The Castor 120 is a medium solid booster used on the Minotaur and Athena launch vehicles. Its design was based on the TU-903, which serves as the first stage of the Peacekeeper ICBM. The standard thrust curve can be modified to produce a regressive burn that reduces maximum acceleration or a saddle-shaped profile that limits aerodynamic forces. Burn time 79 seconds. Diameter: [2.34 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: solidBooster1-1Small
Title: Castor 1
Description: The Castor 1 was first used for a successful suborbital launch of a Scout X-1 rocket on September 2, 1960. Castor 1 stages were also used as strap-on boosters for launch vehicles using Thor first stages, including the Delta-D. Diameter: [0.79 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: solidBoosterMAX
Title: UA1205
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. Diameter: [3.05 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: solidBoosterSmall
Title: Castor 30B
Description: A shortened Castor 120 became the Castor 30 used as an upper stage. [2.34 m] Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: sondex2pod
Title: Modular Common Spacecraft Bus
Description: Main Core for a satellite designed around the MCSB (Modular Common Spacecraft Bus).

Name: SOYUZ_DockingAntenna
Title: Soyuz/Progress AKR-2/3 Antenna
Description: A set of two antennas used by Soyuz and Progress KURS system for communicating with the target.

Name: SOYUZ_ENGINE
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Service Module
Description: The Soyuz Instrument and Service Module (PAO) contains everything that the Soyuz needs for orbital operations. It is jettisoned just before reentry. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SOYUZ_F_2
Title: Soyuz ST Payload Fairing (Type II)
Description: The largest fairing available in the entire Soyuz launch vehicle family, most notably used by the European Space Agency (ESA) for commercial launches.

Name: SOYUZ_FG1
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Fairing (Front)
Description: This fairing is designed specifically for the Soyuz TM/TMA/MS spacecraft. It has many provisions to allow the crew to escape disaster in case of an emergency. The most notable element are the grid fins, acting as air brakes to stabilize the shroud. The lower section can also separate, lightening the load for the escape tower. It also includes two small abort motors designed to pull the Orbital and Descent modules away from the shroud after the launch escape system has separated, but before shroud jettison. This segment is equipped with housings for VZOR periscope and docking sensors. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SOYUZ_FG2
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Fairing (Back)
Description: This fairing is designed specifically for the Soyuz-TMA spacecraft. It has many provisions to allow the crew to escape disaster in case of an emergency (actual functionality WIP). The most notable element are the grid fins, acting as air brakes to stabilize the shroud. The lower section can also separate, lightening the load for the escape tower. Due to changes in abort sequence with Soyuz-TM and TMA, it even has two small abort motors designed to pull the spacecraft away after the tower has separated, but before the shroud did. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SOYUZ_HEAT_SHIELD
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Heatshield
Description: The heat shield for the Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Descent Module. It is jettisoned after main parachute deployment.

Name: SOYUZ_orbitalSegment
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Orbital Module
Description: The Orbital Module (BO) of the Soyuz contains everything that it is not needed for reentry. This includes the docking system, the airlock and the KURS automatic docking antennas. It is jettisoned before entering the atmosphere.

Name: SOYUZ_PAO_PROGRESS
Title: Progress M/MM/MS Service Module
Description: The Progress Instrument and Service Module (PAO) is a simplified version of the Soyuz PAO. The attitude control system is slightly less precise due to removal of the vernier RCS thrusters. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SOYUZ_PARASHUTE
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Main Parachute
Description: The primary parachute of the Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Descent Module (SA).

Name: SOYUZ_PARASHUTE_SPARE
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Emergency Parachute
Description: A fast-opening emergency parachute for the Soyuz Descent Module. It is used after the abort sequence and it also serves as a backup for the main parachute.

Name: SOYUZ_PERESCOPE
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Vzor Periscope
Description: A periscope with two viewing ports. It is used to manually maintain attitude during free flight and to dock the spacecraft in the case of a KURS malfunction.

Name: SOYUZ_REENTRY_CAPSULE
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Descent Module
Description: The Soyuz Descent Module (SA) is where the crew sits during both ascent and reentry. It's equipped with basic life support, RCS for control during reentry and landing engines for softening the landing. Another notable feature is the offset COM, which allows the pod to generate lifting force during reentry and allow a small degree of control over it's landing zone. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SOYUZ_SEPARATOR
Title: Soyuz TM/TMA/MS Service Module Decoupler
Description: A structural truss decoupling system that connects the Soyuz Service Module (PAO) to the Descent Module (SA).

Name: SOYUZ_SOLAR_PANEL
Title: Soyuz/Progress Solar Array
Description: A solar array used on modern Soyuz and Progress spacecraft variants. Efficient, reliable and lightweight.

Name: SOYUZdockingPort
Title: Soyuz/Progress Docking System
Description: The Soyuz and Progress docking system is the male part of a probe and drogue system. It's equipped with a rendezvous antenna and the soft-docking system. To use the docking system first extend the probe and then dock the two spacecraft. The probe will prevent them from connecting so that the Soyuz spacecraft can be rotated precisely to the desired position. Once that is done the probe is retracted, allowing hard docking to take place.

Name: SoyuzHeatshieldLEO
Title: Soyuz Heat Shield (2.2m)
Description: LEO-rated heat shield. Not rated for lunar returns.

Name: sp_express_a
Title: Venus Express Solar Array Wing (SAW)
Description: A solar array wing used on the Venus Express spacecraft. 2.88 m2.

Name: sp_express_b
Title: Mars Express Solar Array Wing (SAW)
Description: A solar array wing used on the Mars Express spacecraft. 5.76 m2.

Name: sp_mariner_a
Title: CA-E100 1x2 Solar Panel
Description: A solar array wing, similar to the one used by the Mariner Venus spacecrafts, featuring increased power generation efficiency. 2.43 m2.

Name: sp_mariner_b
Title: CA-E100-SPV 1x2 Solar Panel
Description: A solar array wing, similar to the one used by the Mariner Mars spacecrafts. Includes Solar Pressure Vanes for finer attitude control. 2.34 m2.

Name: sp_maven
Title: MAVEN Solar Array Wing (SAW)
Description: A solar array wing used on the Mars Atmosphere and Volatile EvolutioN (MAVEN) spacecraft. Includes a three - axis magnetometer. 12 m2.

Name: sp_odyssey_a
Title: Mars Odyssey Solar Array Wing (SAW)
Description: A very efficient Gallium Arsenide (GaAs) photovoltaic array with an eccentric pivot point to minimize it's stowed footprint. 5.88 m2

Name: sp_odyssey_b
Title: CA-E200B 1x2 Solar Panel
Description: An alternate photovoltaic system with vastly improved clearance, based on our award-winning E200 Series. 5.46 m2.

Name: spotLight1
Title: Illuminator Mk1
Description: The Illuminator Mk1 from RKEA projects a strong beam of photons in its prograde direction, increasing the brightness of surfaces exposed to the beam (it's a big flashlight).

Name: spotLight2
Title: Illuminator Mk2
Description: The Illuminator Mk2 is an extra-wide beam, low-power Illuminator, for lighting up large swaths of whatever you wish. However, its beam does not shine very far.

Name: SPUTNIK_1
Title: Sputnik 1
Description: The first satellite ever launched by mankind, this is little more than a metal sphere with a radio transmitter inside and four antennas on the outside. It goes "beep" on the radio to allow tracking and showing that it really is out there. It's not much, but you have to start small. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SPUTNIK_1_FAIRING
Title: R7 Sputnik Adapter
Description: This little thing goes on top of the R7 Second Stage. It contains basic avionics and an adapter for Sputnik 1. An aerodynamic cap protects the satellite. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: sputnik1
Title: Sputnik 1
Description: First artificial satellite

Name: sputnik2
Title: Sputnik 2
Description: Second Soviet satellite

Name: sputnik3
Title: Sputnik 3 "Object D"
Description: Third Soviet satellite

Name: squad_interstage_adapter
Title: Interstage Adapter (Passable)
Description: This interstage adapter allows crew transfer. Slightly heavier than equivalent interstage ring.

Name: squad_interstageSize3
Title: IB - TR-38-D Interstage Shell
Description: A large interstage structure to go between your stages.

Name: SquadRCSBlockHalf
Title: RCS Quad (138/223 N class)
Description: A generic RCS quad. Use this for attitude control or translation/ullage for small stages and spacecraft.

Name: SquadRCSBlockTenth
Title: RCS Quad (28/45 N class)
Description: A generic RCS quad. Use this for attitude control or translation/ullage for very small stages and spacecraft.

Name: SSME
Title: RS-25 (SSME)
Description: The RS-25, also known as the Space Shuttle Main Engine (SSME), is a LH2/LOX fuel-rich staged combustion engine. Though complex and expensive, these engines provide very high performance and are extremely reliable. Three of these engines powered each Shuttle Orbiter and four will be used on the core stage of the SLS. Diameter: [2.4 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSME_Engine
Title: RS-25 (SSME)
Description: The RS-25, also known as the Space Shuttle Main Engine (SSME), is a LH2/LOX fuel-rich staged combustion engine. Though complex and expensive, these engines provide very high performance and are extremely reliable. Three of these engines powered each Shuttle Orbiter and four will be used on the core stage of the SLS. Diameter: [2.4 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU_LanderCore_LC3-POD
Title: SSTU - LC3-POD
Description: LC3-POD

Name: SSTU_LanderCore_LC5-POD
Title: SSTU - LC5-POD
Description: LC5-POD
PLACEMENT NOTES: Fictional Advanced Lander, Same time as Altair

Name: SSTU-AJ10-CustomAdvanced
Title: AJ10 Series (Advanced)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents advanced era AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Transtage as AJ10-138; similar models but back with the -118 designation were used on the Delta F and Delta K upper stages. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-AJ10-CustomEarly
Title: AJ10 Series (Early)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This is the original Vanguard second stage / Able / Delta configuration, without restart capability. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-AJ10-CustomMid
Title: AJ10 Series (Mid)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents mid-period AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Thor-Ablestar and Delta E through Delta N. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-LC2-POD
Title: SSTU - LC2-POD
Description: LC2-POD

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRB2
Title: RSRM (2-segment)
Description: Proposed 2-segment version of RSRM.

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRB3
Title: RSRM (3-segment)
Description: Proposed 3-segment version of RSRM that includes a new aft skirt and TVC system.

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRB4
Title: RSRM
Description: The Redesigned Solid Rocket Motor (RSRM) was a modification of the High-Performance Solid Rocket Motor (HPM), which failed catastrophically on STS-51L. The RSRM incorporated many safety improvements but was intended to be used only temporarily, until the introduction of the Advanced Solid Rocket Motor (ASRM). Eventually development of the ASRM was terminated and the RSRM (renamed the Reusable Solid Rocket Motor) was used on all remaining shuttle flights.

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRB5
Title: RSRMV
Description: The 5-segment Reusable Solid Rocket Motor (RSRMV) was first studied as a performance and safety enhancement for the space shuttle. Adding an additonal segment to the RSRM improved the shuttle's payload capacity ISS's high-inclination orbit and made the Trans-Atlantic Abort option available immediately after booster burnout, reducing the chance of a Return to Launch Site Abort. Though work on the RSRMV for the shuttle was eventually terminated, the need of a more powerful booster for Ares I led to the motor's full-scale development. When Ares I was cancelled, the RSRMV was selected for use on the Space Launch System.

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRBA
Title: RSRM (Modular)
Description: Modular RSRM booster.  Has options for up to 6 segements, with optional scaling of diameter
COST NOTES: Based on costs of RSRM, handled by Procedurals

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRBC
Title: UA-120 (Modular)
Description: Modular UA-120 booster.  Has options to vary the number of segments, with optional diameter scaling.
COST NOTES: Based on costs of UA12xx, fixed by Procedurals

Name: SSTU-RO-ENG-SRBD1
Title: GEM-40/46/60 (Modular)
Description: Modular GEM booster. 1.05m for GEM-40, 1.50m for GEM-60.  Also has options for varying the length, and additional diameter scaling.
COST NOTES: Same entry cost as GEM-40, Cost is determined by Procedural

Name: SSTU-SC-A-BPC
Title: Soyuz LAS
Description: SSTU - Ship Core: Series A - Launch Abort System.  Includes launch abort motors and jettison capability.  Ensure the safety of your crew on their way to the outer reaches with this reliable launch abort system.  To activate the abort mode, first decouple the Descent Module from the Service Module and then activate the BPC engine.  To jettison the BPC after a successful ascent merely press the Jettison button.

Name: SSTU-SC-A-DM
Title: Soyuz Descent Module
Description: SSTU - Ship Core: Series A - Descent Module.  This cozy module seats two Kerbals and is intended to allow for safe re-entry from low-Kerbin orbit.  Includes SAS, reaction wheels, parachutes, cabin lighting, heat-shield, batteries, decouplers on both top and bottom, and an integrated short-range transmitter (WIP).

Name: SSTU-SC-A-OM
Title: Soyuz Orbital Module
Description: SSTU - Ship Core: Series A - Orbital Module.  An orbital support module for the Series A spacecraft enabling docking operations and including additional (not-so-cramped) living space for the two Kerbals from the Descent Module.  Includes integrated SAS, reaction wheels, batteries, docking port, docking lights, cabin lighting, and short-range transmitter (WIP).  Not intended to be launched with crew; the crew should undergo the launch while seated in the Descent Module.

Name: SSTU-SC-A-SM
Title: Soyuz Service Module
Description: SSTU - Ship Core: Series A - Service Module. Includes fuel, engines, batteries, SAS, reaction wheel, RCS thrusters, solar panels and supplies to support the SC-A spacecraft on local-area orbital missions.  Intended to carry enough fuel for an in-orbit rendezvous and a following de-orbit burn.

Name: SSTU-SC-A-SMX
Title: Progress Spacecraft
Description: SSTU - Ship Core: Series A - Station Service Module. A disposable service craft intended for station resupply missions.  Includes fuel, engines, RCS thrusters, solar panels, docking port, docking lights, SAS, reaction wheels, short range transmitter (WIP), and storage space for various supplies.  Payload resources may be configured prior to launch.

Name: SSTU-SC-B-BPC
Title: Apollo Launch Escape System
Description: The Apollo launch escape system (LES) purpose was to abort the mission by pulling the Command Module (the crew cabin) away from the launch vehicle in an emergency, such as a pad fire before launch, guidance failure, or launch vehicle failure likely to lead to an imminent explosion.

Name: SSTU-SC-B-CM
Title: Apollo Command Module
Description: Apollo Command Module. Contains three astronauts.

Name: SSTU-SC-B-CMX
Title: Apollo Command Module - Orbital Module
Description: Apollo Command Module - Orbital Module variant. Contains three astronauts. DO NOT USE FOR RE-ENTRY!
COST NOTES: Same cost as Apollo, but no Heat Shield, lower Entry Cost

Name: SSTU-SC-B-SM
Title: AJ10-137 (Service Propulsion System)
Description: The Aerojet AJ10-137 rocket engine used on the Apollo Service Module as the Service Propulsion System. Diameter: [3.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-BAY-MCB-A
Title: Modular Cargo Bay
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Bays - Saddle Truss Cargo Bay.

Name: SSTU-SC-C-BPC
Title: Orion Launch Escape Assembly
Description: The LEA provides the means for separation the CM from the launch vehicle during pad or suborbital aborts. This assembly consists of a Q-ball instrumentation assembly, ballast compartment, canard surfaces, pitch control motor, tower jettison motor, launch escape motor, a structural skirt, an open-frame tower, and a boost protective cover.

Name: SSTU-SC-C-CM
Title: Orion Command Module
Description: Orion Command Module. Contains between 2 and 6 astronauts.

Name: SSTU-SC-C-CMX
Title: Orion Command Module - Orbital Module
Description: Orion Command Module - Orbital Module variant. Contains between 2 and 6 astronauts. DO NOT USE FOR REENTRY!
COST NOTES: Same cost as Orion, but no Heat Shield, lower Entry Cost

Name: SSTU-SC-C-HUS
Title: Exploration Upper Stage [8.4m]
Description: The Exploration Upper Stage (EUS) is being developed for SLS Block 1B and will enable large payloads to be injected on high energy trajectories to destinations throught the solar system. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-C-ICPS
Title: Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage [5m]
Description: The Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage (ICPS) consists of a modified Delta IV 5 m upper stage. Its structure has been strengthened to support SLS flight loads and the hydrogen tank has been stretched by 46 cm to account for on-orbit boiloff. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-C-SM
Title: Orion European Service Module
Description: The Orion Service Module is the service module component of the Orion spacecraft, serving as its primary power and propulsion component until it is discarded at the end of each mission. In January 2013, NASA announced that the European Space Agency (ESA) will construct the service module for Exploration Mission 1, replacing the previous design. Based on ESA's Automated Transfer Vehicle (ATV), the new design is also known as the European Service Module (ESM). Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-E-DA
Title: SSTU - SC-E - DA - Docking Adapter
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Docking Adapter.  Includes a one-Kerbal airlock.  To be used with the SSTU - Series E spacecraft system, but can also be used with the cargo bays manufactured by C7 Aerospace. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-DAX
Title: SSTU - SC-E - DAX - Extensible Docking Adapter
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Extensible Docking Adapter.  Includes a one-Kerbal airlock.  To be used with the SSTU - Series E spacecraft system, but can also be used with the cargo bays manufactured by C7 Aerospace.  This version includes an extending docking port (must be extended in order to dock). (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-EL
Title: SSTU - SC-E - EL - Left Elevon
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Left Elevon.  To be used with the Series E spacecraft system. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-ER
Title: SSTU - SC-E - ER - Right Elevon
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Right Elevon.  To be used with the Series E spacecraft system. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-FS
Title: SSTU - SC-E - FS - Fuselage
Description: Ship Core - Series E - Fuselage.  Regarded as one of the most innovative developments ever to come out of SSTU's Labs division, the Series E is the first partially re-usable spacecraft to be developed.  Fully equipped for long duration orbital missions, it comes equipped with SAS, reaction wheel, RCS, orbital engines and fuel, ascent engines, short range transmitter (WIP), landing gear, cabin lighting, and a very spacious cargo bay.  Includes accommodations for 7 Kerbals for shorter missions, or 4 Kerbals for longer-duration use.  Rated for 12t lifted cargo payload, and/or 6.5t of returned-from-orbit cargo payload. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-FSX
Title: SSTU - SC-E - FSX - Fuselage (No Engines)
Description: Ship Core - Series E - Fuselage (No Engines).  Regarded as one of the most innovative developments ever to come out of SSTU's Labs division, the Series E is the first partially re-usable spacecraft to be developed.  Fully equipped for long duration orbital missions, it comes equipped with SAS, reaction wheel, RCS, orbital fuel, short range transmitter (WIP), landing gear, cabin lighting, and a very spacious cargo bay.  Includes accommodations for 7 Kerbals for shorter missions, or 4 Kerbals for longer-duration use.  Rated for 12t lifted cargo payload, and/or 6.5t of returned-from-orbit cargo payload.  This version comes without integrated engines so that custom solutions may be used. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-WL
Title: SSTU - SC-E - WL - Left Wing
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Left Wing.  To be used with the Series E spacecraft system. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-WR
Title: SSTU - SC-E - WR - Right Wing
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Right Wing.  To be used with the Series E spacecraft system. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-E-WT
Title: SSTU - SC-E - WT - Tail
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Series E - Tail.  To be used with the Series E spacecraft system.  Includes drag parachute for shorter runway use. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-AJ10-137
Title: AJ10-137 (Service Propulsion System)
Description: The Aerojet AJ10-137 rocket engine used on the Apollo Service Module as the Service Propulsion System. Diameter: [2.6 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-AJ10-190
Title: AJ10-190
Description: Low thrust pressure-fed hypergolic engine. It was used on the Space Shuttle for orbital insertion, maneuvering and deorbiting. Currently used by the Orion MPCV. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-F1
Title: F-1 Series
Description: The massive Rocketdyne F-1 engine. One of the largest, most powerful rocket engines ever built. Ensure you enable roll capability or disable gimbal as required for your application. Diameter: [3.61 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-F1B
Title: F-1B
Description: The F-1B engine was designed to power the proposed Pyrios advanced boosters for the Space Launch System. A highly modified version of the original F-1, the F-1B uses modern manufacturing techniques including 3D printing and features a simpler gas generator exhaust arrangment in order to reduce manufacturing costs and increase thrust at a slight cost of efficiency. Mount size can be adjusted from 2.5m to 10m in 1m increments. Diameter: [3.61 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-H1
Title: H-1/RS-27 Series
Description: The H-1 is an upgrade to the LR79 engine that propelled the Saturn-I and IB vehicles, as well as late-model Delta rockets (as the RS-27). The H-1/RS-27 are optimized for the first-stage main engine role. The RS-27A has a higher expansion ratio for increased performance at altitude since liftoff thrust on the Delta II is augmented by solid boosters and the core burns rather longer. Diameter: [1.0 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-J-2
Title: J-2 Series
Description: The Rocketdyne J-2 rocket engine found on the Saturn S-IVB and S-II stages. Ensure you enable roll capability or disable gimbal as required for your application. Diameter: [2.01 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-J-2X
Title: J-2X
Description: 2000s medium TWR, vacuum engine. The J-2X was intended to be used on the upper stages of Ares I and Ares V. Development continued after the cancellation of Ares, and early designs of SLS incorporated the engine, but selection of the RL10-powered Exploration Upper Stage resulted in the project being mothballed. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-LMAE
Title: Lunar Module Ascent Engine
Description: Pressure-fed engine used for the ascent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Diameter: [0.86 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-LMDE
Title: Lunar Module Descent Engine
Description: Deeply throttleable pressure-fed vacuum engine used for the descent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Uses storable propellants which are not subject to boiloff, but are far less efficient than hydrolox or even kerolox. The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-LR81-8048
Title: XLR81 (Agena) Vacuum Engine
Description: Gas-generator nitric acid/UDMH vacuum engine used on Agena. The XLR81 family was derived from the Bell Hustler Rocket Engine, which was developed for use on an air-to-surface missile. Early engines were nearly identical to the Hustler engine, while later variants offered new capabilities and improved performance. Engine restart was introduced on the Agena B's XLR81-BA-7 (Model 8081). The XLR81-BA-11 (Model 8096) used on Agena D used propellant sumps to eliminate the need for ullage thrust. The XLR81-BA-13 (Model 8247) powered the Gemini Agena Target Vehicle (a modified Agena D) and was rated for up to 14 restarts. Diameter: [0.9 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RD-107A
Title: RD-107 Series
Description: Booster engine for the R-7 Semyorka and its derivatives, including the Sputnik, Luna, Voskhod, Vostok, Soyuz, and Molniya launch vehicles. Differs from the core engine series (RD-108) with a higher chamber pressure, thrust, and smaller vernier layout. The R-7 family core was supplemented for (roughly) two minutes by four strap-on boosters powered by these engines. Diameter: [1.85 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RD-107X
Title: RD-107X
Description: The RD-107X is a gas generator multi-chamber engine.  Each of the four nozzles is fed from a single set of turbopumps.  This is the same engine as the RD-107A, but without the vernier motors.  This engine has no gimbal or thrust vectoring, so you will need to provide your own means of attitude control for the stage. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RD-108A
Title: RD-108 Series
Description: Core engine for the R-7 Semyorka and its derivatives, including the Sputnik, Luna, Voskhod, Vostok, Soyuz, and Molniya launch vehicles.  Differs from the booster engine series (RD-107) with a lower chamber pressure, thrust, and a wider vernier layout.  Powers the R-7 family core through a very long (roughly) five minute burn that starts on the pad alongside the boosters. Diameter: [1.85 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RD-180
Title: RD-180 Series Engine
Description: SSTU - ShipCore: Engines - RD-180.  The most powerful single-combustion chamber engine ever produced*, the RD-180 is often a good choice when you need to land skyscrapers on the Mun.  Even more impressive(ly insane) when used in engine clusters.  While its efficiency might be lacking by modern standards it more than compensates for it with its incredible thrust output.  Due to this it is most useful in the lowest stage of a rocket where the most thrust is needed.  (* SSTU engineers are currently prototyping an upgraded and modified RD-180 engine with even more power, however it is not yet in full production; see the F1B for more info). Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RO BUT PLACED AND COSTED BY RP-0)

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RL10A-3
Title: RL10 Series Vacuum Engine
Description: Hydrolox restartable expander-cycle vacuum engine used in multiple upper stages, including Centaur, the Saturn I S-IV, and the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage. It has low thrust, but very high specific impulse and low mass, making it ideal for high energy, beyond-low-Earth-orbit applications like launching satellites to geostationary transfer orbits or to the Moon or other planets. However, like all hydrolox engines, hydrogen boiloff is a serious issue without heat pumps or radiators. Diameter: [0.92 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RL10A-4
Title: RL10A-4 Series Vacuum Engine
Description: Hydrolox restartable expander-cycle vacuum engine used in countless applications. Most famous applications include the Centaur upper stage, the S-IV upper stage of the original Saturn I launcher, and the new Delta Cryogenic Second Stage. The RL10 uses liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen (so beware of boiloff); it has very low thrust, but very high specific impulse, and is designed for beyond-Low-Earth-Orbit applications like launching satellites to geostationary transfer orbits or to the Moon or other planets. However, like all cryogenic engines, boiloff is a serious issue without heat pumps or radiators. Mount size can be adjusted from 1.25m to 10m in 1m increments. Diameter: [1.25 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RL10B-2
Title: RL10B-2 Vacuum Engine
Description: Developed for the Delta Cryogenic Second Stage (DCSS), which was first used on the Delta III then modified for the Delta IV. Its extending nozzle increases specific impulse compared to the RL10A, at the cost of greater dry mass. Boeing purchased a large number of these engines for the Delta IV, but the launcher's low flight rate led to ULA converting many of them to RL10C-1 engines for use on the Atlas V's Centaur upper stage. Also includes a config for the European Vinci 180kN engine. Mount size can be adjusted from 1.25m to 10m in 1m increments. Diameter: [2.15 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Name: SSTU-SC-ENG-RS-25
Title: RS-25 (SSME)
Description: The RS-25, also known as the Space Shuttle Main Engine (SSME), is a LH2/LOX fuel-rich staged combustion engine. Though complex and expensive, these engines provide very high performance and are extremely reliable. Three of these engines powered each Shuttle Orbiter and four will be used on the core stage of the SLS. Diameter: [2.4 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Title: RS-68 Series
Description: 1990s Medium TWR atmospheric engine. Using technology developed for the Space Shuttle SSME, the RS-68 is a single-use engine, featuring a simplified design with less parts and an easier construction. The RS-68 powers the Delta IV launch vehicle family and is the most powerful LH2/LOX engine ever flown. Exhaust from the gas generator is used for roll control. Diameter: [5.0 m].
